<FIRST>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia Bjt   09-27 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia, Bjt ,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Suffers in Cambodian Quagmire</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twice a month, when the moon is full, Muoi
Cao Am and his wife take white flowers and incense to pray at the
graves of their sons, soldiers who died because of Vietnam's
intervention in Cambodia.
   ``We burn this incense to remember you. May God give you good
fortune,'' said Muoi, 70, bowing before the peeling white
tombstones invaded by grass. His wife, 66, stood aside and wept
quietly.
   Thinh, 18, was killed in Cambodia in October 1978, when Khmer
Rouge soldiers ambushed Vietnamese forces operating in the country
two months before Hanoi's invasion.
   The next year, Sau, 21, died along Vietnam's northern border
with China, which Beijing attacked to ``punish'' Vietnam for
invading Cambodia. That was two months before his first child was
born.
   The tombstones, yellowing photographs, and the equivalent of $2
a month compensation from the government are virtually the only
reminders of the youths their parents called ``kind and friendly.''
   The tragedy of the Muois, of Dan Phuong Tri village near Hanoi,
is the tragedy of the 11-year Cambodian war that some foreigners
have called ``Vietnam's Vietnam'' _ a comparison to America's
intervention in Vietnam in the 1960s and 1970s.
   Vietnam says it has withdrawn its soldiers and will let the
Hanoi-installed government fight the guerrillas Vietnam couldn't
eradicate despite superior firepower.
   Vietnam is a Communist nation so the war has not provoked the
public anguish that tore America. But it is clear it was a costly
venture for Vietnam.
   The former deputy commander of Vietnamese forces in Cambodia
said last year that 30,000 Vietnamese died in border clashes with
Pol Pot's fanatical Khmer Rouge regime in 1977 to 1978, and 25,000
Vietnamese soldiers have died since Vietnam invaded in December
1978 and drove the Khmer Rouge to the jungles.
   Many of the remains of Vietnamese soldiers are along the
frontier at western Tay Ninh province, waiting to be returned to
families, said Gen. Tran Cong Man, editor of the official army
newspaper Quan Doi Nhan Dan.
   ``We will build a memorial for them at the border,'' he said.
   Tens of thousands of young Vietnamese served in what must be
among the world's most difficult battlefields. Tran Dinh Dac, 31,
recalled long periods in the forests, hungry, often stricken by
malaria, always fearful of guerrilla mines and ambushes.
   ``And the skins of the Pol Potists are thicker than that of the
Vietnamese,'' he said at his roadside drinks stand. ``They are not
affected by thorns.''
   The Cambodian war broke out after millions of Vietnamese already
had been killed or wounded in four decades of virtually continuous
fighting.
   The North Vietnam Communists had fought the French colonial
rulers, the Japanese occupiers of World War II, then South Vietnam
and its American allies. Thousands more died in China's punitive
strike across the border.
   Many millions who escaped the fire of battle also suffered.
   Non-Communist nations punished Vietnam for invading Cambodia by
diplomatic and economic blockades that have added to the poor
living conditions for Vietnam's 65 million people. More than
600,000 people have fled the country by boat in the last decade.
   ``Ten years ago the development of Vietnam and South Korea was
at the same level but now Korea has left us far behind,'' said a
Vietnamese government economist who requested anonymity.
   ``We hope to have peace to concentrate all our efforts to
rebuild our country, our economy. We want to begin a new period,''
Minister of Justice Phan Hien said in an interview.
   The young people today talk not of sacrifice for the revolution
but of school and careers, marriage and children, or simply
enjoying life.
   ``We have a hard time having fun. We are always working,'' said
a young Foreign Ministry worker whose major goals are being able to
go dancing to American pop music and to buy a Japanese-made
motorbike.
   A couple of months ago, students at the University of Hanoi
protested the conditions on campus, including the lack of equipment
and the meager salaries of teachers, a Western ambassador said. The
government promised improvements.
   The burden of the war in Cambodia probably won't end with the
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops.
   Tens of thousands of demobilized soldiers need jobs in a society
already troubled by high unemployment.
   Vietnam may also remain isolated because its pullout was not
internationally monitored and thus will be greeted with skepticism.
Also, the non-Communist world demands not just a pullout but a
political settlement in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
