<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba-Activists     09-27 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Activists,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Rights Activists To Be Tried Next Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Cuban human rights activists will be
tried next month on charges of spreading false information after a
drug trafficking trial that led to several executions, Cuban's
official news agency said.
   Prensa Latina said Tuesday that Elizardo Sanchez, Hiram Abi
Cobas and Hubert Jerez were arrested in August and charged with
giving false information to U.S. television networks and Radio
Marti, a U.S. government station beamed to Cuba, in an attempt to
discredit Cuban courts.
   The prosecution has asked for prison terms of three or four
years for the three activists.
   Prensa Latina said lawyers for the defendants would have 10 days
to study the charges and prepare their cases, and that the trial
would begin within 20 days after that.
   The defendants were accused of telling U.S. media that Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez had been psychologically tortured and had
confessed to drug trafficking while under the influence of drugs
administered by his interrogators.
   Ochoa, a Cuban war hero, and three other men were executed in
July following trials that revealed a criminal ring in the Cuban
defense and interior departments that helped smuggle drugs from
Colombia to the United States.
   The trial and the corruption it revealed were extremely
embarrassing to Cuba's communist leader, Fidel Castro, who had
insisted for years that accusations of drug trafficking were part
of a U.S. plot to discredit his government.
   The three rights activists were members of a group called
Defenders of Human Rights, which Prensa Latina said was
``counterrevolutionary'' and illegal.
</TEXT>
