<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-ConfederateMuseum     09-27 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Confederate Museum,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Destroys Civil War Relics, Forces Museum Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Priceless diaries and other Confederate
relics have been destroyed or damaged by Hurricane Hugo, the
director of the Confederate Museum says.
   What's left of the collection was to be moved today, said the
director, June Wells.
   The roof of the 148-year-old Market Hall building was blown
away, exposing the collection's flags, papers and uniforms to wind
and rain.
   ``The damage is quite extensive,'' said Mrs. Wells, one of the
160 or so members of the Charleston Chapter of the United Daughters
of the Confederacy, which owns the collection.
   ``The reason we're having to leave so quickly is the ceiling is
falling.''
   Many paper items have been damaged, she said, including portions
of a daily log kept at Fort Sumter by the fortress' engineer during
fighting in 1861 and 1863 after Confederate forces occupied the
site.
   Those papers, she said, are now ``soaking wet, and of course it
was water-soluble ink. Some of them hopefully we can dry out.''
   Mrs. Wells said the collection was started when Confederate war
veterans convening in Charleston in 1898 donated memorabilia.
   The city-owned building is itself significant.
   ``When the War Between the States started, our Market Hall was
where the young men came into Charleston to get their armaments and
supplies and destinations,'' she said.
   The collection includes the first rifle cannon made in America,
the original secession flag flown at Charleston's Customs House
after South Carolina seceded from the Union on Dec. 20, 1860, and
the first and last Confederate flags to fly over Fort Sumter, where
the first shots of the war were fired, on April 12, 1861.
   The museum is selective.
   ``Nothing from Sherman,'' she said of William Tecumseh Sherman,
the Union general who led the March to the Sea from Atlanta to the
Atlantic.
   ``No Yankee things. The only thing we have are a few captured
Yankee things.''
   Mrs. Wells is uncertain where or for how long the collection
will be stored.
   ``This will be first time they've ever left that building since
they were put there in 1898,'' she said. ``The building is unsafe
and the collection is unsafe. ... It's kind of unbelievable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
