<FIRST>r i AM-CanadaCrash     09-27 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada Crash,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Killed In Commuter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TERRACE, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter plane crashed and
burned as it attempted to land in heavy fog Tuesday and all seven
people aboard were killed, officials said.
   The twin-engine Skylink Airlines jet was on its second approach
to the Terrace-Kitimat airport in northwest British Columbia when
it went down, said Christiane Cote, a spokesman for Canada's
transporation department. The plane was carrying five passengers
and two crew members.
   ``What we know at this stage is the weather conditions were very
bad and the airport was covered with fog,'' Cote said from
Vancouver. ``Therefore visibility was minimal.
   The plane crashed at 8:25 a.m. in a heavily wooded area just
west of the airport, said Ian Swan, base manager for Northern
Mountain Helicopters in Terrace who flew over the site.
   Rafael Zur, president and owner of Skylink, said the airplane
was four years old and had passed an inspection two weeks ago.
   Flight 70 was on a regularly scheduled flight from Vancouver to
Terrace and Smithers when it crashed, said Zur. Terrace is in the
west-central area of British Columbia, about 435 miles northwest of
Vancouver.
   Skylink Airlines, based in Richmond, British Columbia, was
founded in 1984 as a commuter service. It has a fleet of 11 planes.
</TEXT>
