<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-27 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who won a $6.5 million Lotto jackpot put
off claiming their prize for a couple of days. They first had to
take care of their tomatoes.
   Forrest and Edna Hiller of Arvada learned Sunday they had won,
but didn't turn in their ticket until Tuesday so they could cook
and can a six-month supply of homemade spaghetti sauce.
   ``Our tomatoes were at a crucial point where we had to take care
of them, or we would have lost them,'' said Hiller, a 66-year-old
retiree.
   On Sunday, he picked up the newspaper and checked the numbers.
``There, just like a bolt out of the blue, those beautiful numbers
showed up,'' he said.
   ``I began to shake a little downstairs and then I went up to
where she was,'' he said of his 74-year-old wife. ``I was a little
frightened to know how to tell her for fear she might have a heart
attack or something. ...
   ``Finally, I just broke down and said, `Well, Maw, hang onto
your hat, we hit the big one.'''
   On Tuesday, the couple, who have been married 33 years, received
their first annual payment, $123,500 after taxes.
   The remaining progressive payments will be made over 25 years,
with the last to total $295,347. That payment will come when Hiller
is 91 and his wife 99.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goats love to eat kudzu. The South is full of
the tangly vine. A scientist thinks the South needs goats.
   Al Smith, a University of Georgia agronomist, says that's a
simple way to control kudzu.
   Kudzu, which clogs prime development property and can kill trees
by blocking out sunlight, came from Japan as an ornamental plant in
1876.
   It has spread to more than 1 million acres in the South.
   He said four goats will kill an acre of the vine in two years of
grazing.
   Chemicals might do the job faster, but goats won't hurt the
environment _ except for kudzu, he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 42 days of smooching, a lawyer unlocked
the lips of three couples in the first annual Great American
Kiss-Off. Lips are sealed, though, as to how they'll split the
$10,000 top prize.
   ``We thought it was going to be a two-week thing, but it turned
into a marathon,'' Fernando Gonzales said Tuesday, one day after
all parties embraced the pact. ``I'm recovered now. But it still
feels like I'm kissing.''
   He and his wife, Karen, were declared the official first-place
finishers after they and two other couples outlasted 11 other pairs
who entered the contest sponsored by a furniture company. Company
officials also are keeping their quiet over the $10,000 split.
   Reno attorney Pat Cashill said he was hired by parents of the
two other couples in their late teens and early 20s to help end the
contest so their children could get on with their lives.
   ``These people were really caught up in a horrible situation,''
Cashill said. ``It was like they were in bondage. They wouldn't
quit; $10,000 is a lot of money.''
   Under the agreement, the Gonzaleses got the deed to an Idaho
time-share condominium, which was the first-place prize along with
the money.
   The declared second-place finishers and winners of an
expenses-paid trip to Mexico were Lloyd and Laura Gubler of Reno.
Bret Watson and Lori Block of Reno claimed the third-place prize of
new living room furniture.
