<FIRST>r a PM-SummitSite     09-27 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Site,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jefferson's `Academical Village' is Education Summit Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Education Summit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The setting for President Bush's
education summit this week is the University of Virginia, the
``academical village'' that Thomas Jefferson founded in the serene
foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains as an experiment in learning.
   Jefferson wanted to avoid the usual ``large and common den of
noise'' at other universities, but whether Bush and the nation's
governors respect Jefferson's wishes will be evident when they
convene today.
   The purpose of the two-day summit, a major Bush initiative, is
to look for ways to improve American public education. Jefferson
also was searching for something different _ and better _ in higher
education.
   The third U.S. president and squire of nearby Monticello, where
Bush and the governors will dine during the summit, Jefferson
sought a new kind of learning environment at his university.
   Rather than building a single huge structure, Jefferson
envisioned a campus of small classroom dwellings where professors
and students would live closely together as a community of scholars.
   Such a concept, he wrote, would amount to ``an academical
village, instead of a large and common den of noise, of filth and
of fetid air.''
   Jefferson also redirected the focus of higher education toward
public service and practical matters, and away from the university
as a training academy for clergymen and academics.
   The university received its charter from the state in 1819 and
opened with 68 students and a faculty of eight in 1825. It has
grown to an enrollment of 17,000 undergraduates and 6,000 graduate
students today, but still preserves much of its Jeffersonian
heritage.
   Students still live on the Lawn designed by Jefferson, four
colonnaded rows of rooms reserved for selected applicants. Claiming
an address on the Lawn is regarded as a high honor, even though
residents must walk outside on winter mornings to reach the
bathroom.
   At the end of the Lawn is the Rotunda, a former library and
classroom building which Jefferson modeled after the Roman
Pantheon. It is now reserved for important meetings such as the
Bush summit.
   If Bush or the governors refer to the ``campus'' here, they will
be wrong. According to Jeffersonian tradition, it is called the
Grounds. And students are first-year, second-year and so on,
instead of freshmen, sophomores, juniors and seniors.
   Bush is following Jefferson's example in wanting to be known as
``the education president,'' says Jennings L. Wagoner, a university
professor who is an expert on Jefferson's educational views.
   Jefferson saw education as a national priority that required
federal leadership, Wagoner said, and believed that carrying out
those priorities was the responsibility of state and local
governments.
   Most of the university's students are likely to regard the
summit as a sideshow causing only minor inconvenience, such as
cancellation of boxing and weightlifting classes because of the
gymnasium's conversion into a press center.
   Nonetheless, some students are keenly interested in the summit.
   ``I think it's exciting that the 51 most important
administrators in the country are meeting here,'' said Jim Greiner,
a junior who is studying government.
   Greiner said summits tend to be ``exercises in press relations''
where no real work is accomplished. What really matters here, he
said, is how much money Bush is willing to pump into the schools.
   ``If Bush wants to be known as the education president, he will
have to restructure his spending priorities,'' Greiner said. ``When
people say `what has he done for education,' he can point to the
conference as a positive step. But the bottom line is money.''
</TEXT>
