<FIRST>r w PM-DisabilitiesAct     09-27 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disabilities Act,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Operators Say Access for Disabled Would End Some Bus Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intercity bus service operators say attempts
to open all buses to disabled Americans will instead mean the end
of public transportation for many rural areas and the poor.
   Bus operators from Greyhound down to small regional carriers
told a House subcommittee Tuesday that the proposed Americans With
Disabilities Act unfairly singles them out with its requirement
that all buses be equipped with wheelchair lifts.
   No other segment of the transportation industry would be told
how to make vehicles accessible, and none are being told to make
every vehicle accessible, bus operators said.
   ``The mandatory lift requirement with its attendant costs,
including installation ... would spell the end of intercity service
in the United States,'' Frank M. Henry of the American Bus
Association told the House Public Works and Transportation surface
transportation subcommittee.
   ``Rural communities now served only by intercity bus would have
no public transportation available,'' he said. ``Customers now
served, many of whom are young, old, and poor and who have no other
means of transportation, would be stranded.''
   Advocates for the disabled say many handicapped people are poor
and live in the country, so it is essential they have access to
intercity buses.
   ``Without access to transportation, all the other things the act
provides don't matter,'' said Tim Cook, director of the
Washington-based National Disability Center.
   The act guarantees a broad range of rights to the nation's
estimated 43 million disabled. Estimates by various groups at the
hearing were that anywhere from 760,000 to 1.7 million of those
disabled use wheelchairs.
   Fred G. Currey, head of Dallas-based Greyhound Bus Lines Inc.,
said 50 percent of the company's passengers earn less than $15,000
a year. Even a slight increase in ticket costs due to the act would
price many passengers out of a ticket, he said.
   The company would have to cut service to up to half its 10,000
communities, and companies that operate feeder lines would have to
do the same.
   The bus operators propose that service be available on demand.
Advocates of the disabled say this violates the intent of the bill,
since the disabled have the same right to spontaneous travel that
others have.
   The disabled advocates also say the intercity bus services are
treated more leniently because of compromises in the version of the
bill passed earlier this month by the Senate.
   The Senate bill gives the bus industry six to seven years to
comply, longer than anyone else, they say. They also say that
wheelchair lifts are not the only way to provide access, although
the lifts have been the main item of discussion in testimony on the
legislation.
</TEXT>
