<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-ReportCard     09-27 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Report Card,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Report Card Includes Many Incompletes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may be fulfilling one campaign
promise with his education summit that begins today, but his
overall report card at this point would bear a lot of incompletes.
   Any compilation of the president's record _ eight months into
his first year _ would show movement on dozens of campaign pledges
but final action on only a few, particularly in the domestic arena.
   In fact, many of Bush's first-term initiatives are caught in a
colossal congressional logjam just days before the start of fiscal
year 1990.
   The president did score some impressive victories in recent days
on the foreign policy front, including his well-received U.N.
initiative to limit chemical weapons and an array of Soviet
concessions on arms control issues.
   And a Senate deadlock over funding Bush's war on drugs appeared
to be broken with White House acceptance of a compromise plan.
   Still, the bulk of Bush's domestic proposals to Congress _
nearly all of them reflecting campaign promises _ appeared to be
languishing.
   And then there are the Bush ``summits.''
   The two-day conference of the nation's governors _ today and
Thursday in Charlottesville, Va. _ is just one of five separate
summits Bush, the candidate, said he would call in his first year.
   Only one other has actually been held, last May's summit of
North Atlantic Treaty Organization members. But that coincided with
NATO's 40th anniversary celebration and was not specifically
arranged by the United States.
   Another summit is said to be in the planning stage, although no
date or location has yet been set: a Latin American summit on drug
trafficking.
   Bush also proposed an international summit on global warming, to
be held in Washington and to include the Soviet Union, China and
developing nations as well as western industrial nations.
   But little has been heard on that subject since he took office.
   Also proposed but not heard from again: Devoting a seven-nation
economic summit to agriculture.
   The president has a better track record on submitting items on
his 1988 campaign agenda to Congress. But the bulk of them are now
bogged down in the Democratic-controlled House and Senate.
   For instance, on education, subject of today's summit, Bush last
spring proposed a $414 million package that included a $250 million
proposal for national merit scholarship and $100 million for magnet
schools.
   But the only part of Bush's package to make any headway in
either chamber to date is a relatively modest math and science
scholarship program, which has passed the House.
   Bush's proposal to overhaul the Clean Air Act, following up on
campaign pledges to be the environmental president as well as the
education president, is creeping along. House Speaker Thomas Foley,
D-Wash., recently said House action on it this year is unlikely.
   Bush's proposal for child care and adoption tax credits are also
in congressional limbo, and his proposal to reduce the capital
gains tax is now the subject of fierce partisan wrangling.
   The president vowed anew on Tuesday to fight for the lower rate,
even if it means prolonging an impasse that threatens to trigger
automatic spending cuts next month.
   Chances seem good that fiscal 1990 will begin without agreement
on deficit-reduction legislation to which the capital gains issue
is tied.
   A variety of other Bush proposals, including much of his
anti-crime package, also are making little headway.
   One problem, suggested political analyst Norman Ornstein at the
conservative American Enterprise Institute, is that Bush may have
waited too long, allowing the mythical ``first 100 days'' to elapse
before submitting many of his proposals.
   ``We did not have the usual pattern of a new president coming in
and having a package of items being ready to go,'' Ornstein said.
``After all, for months we were saying, `is he ever going to
propose anything?'''
   Now, ``It means more than our usual share of chaos'' as a new
fiscal year is about to begin ``without a budget, without a great
sense of direction,'' he added.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, also contended Bush dumped too many initiatives on
Congress at once _ without suggesting how he would pay for them all.
   ``It's kind of the free lunch approach to dealing with national
issues,'' Panetta said.
   Then there are some Bush campaign pledges that haven't yet
surfaced.
   For instance: his proposal for Individual Savings Account, a
plan under which Americans could stash away up to $2,000 a year and
not pay taxes on the interest until the account matured, after five
years or so.
   When Bush unveiled the plan it was immediately ridiculed by
Democrats, who challenged GOP campaign aides to explain how it
differed significantly from U.S. savings bonds.
   They couldn't. And that was the last heard about it.
</TEXT>
