<FIRST>r w PM-Transportation-DrugTests     09-27 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transportation-Drug Tests,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Employees Test 99 Percent Drug Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department says it's
employees responsible for public safety and security are almost 100
percent drug-free.
   Random drug tests on 15,352 department workers _ most of them in
sensitive jobs at the Federal Aviation Administration _ turned up
illegal drug use in 99, the Transportation Department said Monday.
   The 99 positive results were 0.6 percent of the total tests
conducted between Jan. 1, 1988 and April 30, 1989, according to the
department's ``Drug-Free Workplace Program Evaluation Report'' for
   ``Marijuana use accounted 
September 1989.for approximately two-thirds of
positives with cocaine for all but a small percentage of the
rest,'' the report says.
   The department said it spent $4 million on its anti-drug program
in the 1988 fiscal year, which ended last Sept. 30, covering
collection, laboratory testing, staff support and informational
services, according to the report.
   Federal Aviation Administration employees accounted for 95
percent of those tested under the random testing program, which
focuses on safety and security workers who have a direct impact on
public safety, the protection of life and property, law enforcement
or national security.
   Of these employees, 65 percent were air traffic controllers, 16
percent electronic technitment did
drug tests for what it called reasonable suspicion, post-accident
tests and follow-up tests.
   The 26 drug tests taken after accidents in the FAA and two in
the U.S. Coast Guard all turned up negative, the report said.
   Of the 17 reasonable suspicion tests during the 16-month period
cited in the report, nine showed negative results.
</TEXT>
