<FIRST>r a PM-US-Nicaragua     09-27 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Asks for Funds to Defeat Ortega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III is using
his meetings here with foreign ministers to appeal for private
contributions to defeat Daniel Ortega, the Sandinista president of
Nicaragua, U.S. officials say.
   He made the request of the foreign ministers of Japan and West
Germany on Tuesday ``and he did make it with others,'' the
officials said in confirming a Japanese report.
   Baker did not specify how much of a contribution the Bush
administration wanted for Violeta Chamorro, the newspaper publisher
who is running against Ortega, and he was given no commitments by
the ministers, said the officials, who demanded anonymity.
   Last week Baker abandoned a plan to have the National Endowment
for Democracy make contributions to Mrs. Chamorro's campaign to
defeat Ortega in next year's presidential election in Nicaragua.
   Baker concluded such use of the group went beyond its
congressional charter. The National Endowment for Democracy will
participate in poll watching, as it has done in Panama, Chile and
other countries.
   Appealing to the foreign ministers to arrange private
contributions ``was something that was suggested by some members of
the Democratic leadership when we talked with them about NED
funding,'' an official said.
   Baker asked Japanese Foreign Minister Taro Nakayana to use his
influence with the Liberal Democratic Party to obtain contributions
for Mrs. Chamorro's campaign, the officials said.
   Baker made an indirect approach also to Hans-Dietrich Genscher,
the West German foreign minister, at a separate meeting, the
officials said.
   The Free Democrats have ties to one political institute, and the
Christian Democrats to another one.
   ``It's an effort that we are making and an effort that we will
pursue,'' the official said.
   ``It wasn't just funds,'' said another U.S. official. ``This
came up in several meetings. He also has encouraged people, if they
wished, to send election observers to have visits down there. So it
wasn't just funds.''
   Baker is in New York to attend the special session of the United
Nations General Assembly. But he is spending most of the week
meeting with dozens of foreign ministers here for the session.
   Baker also met Tuesday with Foreign Ministers Krzysztof
Skubiszewski of Poland and Gyuia Horn of Hungary.
   The U.S. officials said the Pole outlined a ``major overhaul''
of the East European country's monetary policy and economic
structure.
   ``We're very pleased to see that, because we see it as moving in
the direction that we had set out from the very start, which is to
try and build an effective private sector to try and deal with
problems,'' an official said.
   The plan, he said, is designed to cope with inflation, now about
40 percent a month, and to promote private enterprise.
   The program impressed Baker and his aides, but the officials
declined to say whether it would cause the Bush administration to
increase aid to Poland.
   President Bush has asked Congress for $119 million in
developmental assistance. Last week, bowing to pressure from
Congress, an additional $50 million in food aid was tacked on.
   Still, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, led by the
Democrats, approved a nearly $1.2 billion three-year aid package
for Poland and Hungary.
   ``I think from the outline of what we've seen it's a very
positive development,'' the official said of the Polish program.
</TEXT>
