<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two B-2 Tests Cut Short</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more tests of the B-2 bomber have been cut
short, once because of high winds and another time because of
another oil pressure problem, according to the Pentagon.
   A Sept. 21 flight was scrubbed after three hours after
indications of low oil pressure in the plane's No. 1 airframe
accessory drive, said Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams. A similar
problem had forced cancellation of a flight on Aug. 16.
   A flight Saturday ended after 77 minutes ``because of gusty
winds at the altitude at which the plane was flying,'' William
said, adding that he could not say what the wind strengths were.
   The bat-winged bomber is designed to pass through enemy radar
virtually undetected. The accessory drive is the gear box that
powers the jet's generators and controls.
   The government has spent about $22.4 billion in the B-2 program,
which is 18 months behind schedule, and Congress has balked at
paying more than $500 million each for 132 bombers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Meredith Working for Helms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Meredith, the first black to attend the
University of Mississippi 27 years ago, is now working for Sen.
Jesse Helms, the conservative North Carolina Republican who has
been a critic of civil rights legislation.
   Meredith said Tuesday he had been hired to advise Helms on
questions of race, education, drugs and urban problems, after
providing informal advice for the last year.
   Meredith, 58, has sharply changed his views since becoming the
first black at Ole Miss in 1962. Since then, he has called
integration the ``biggest con job ever pulled on anybody.''
   In a letter to acquaintances, Meredith wrote that Helms, who is
up for re-election next year, ``wants to provide the best possible
representation to them as well as the entire black population.''
