<SECOND>PM-People-Vinton,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Says `Blue Velvet' Could Have Been a Comeback Hit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Bobby Vinton said the 1986
movie ``Blue Velvet'' could have put him on the comeback trail but
he wasn't able to get his his version of the title song re-released.
   Vinton said Roy Orbison gained newfound popularity after his
label re-released his ``In Dreams,'' which also was featured in the
movie about a young man's look at the seamier side of his small
town.
   Orbison went on to record three other albums, one as a
``Traveling Wilbury'' with Tom Petty, Bob Dylan, George Harrison
and Jeff Lynne, before his death earlier this year.
   ``The record company didn't want to release it before the movie
came out,'' Vinton said of his song ``Blue Velvet.''
   ``Then when the the movie became successful they decided to put
it back out. But (director) David Lynch didn't want deal with it
then. He said he didn't want to make a video using outtakes to sell
his movie. He was up for an Academy Award and didn't want to be too
commercial.''
   ``But the way Roy Orbison's career came back it would have been
a good shot for me,'' he said. ``It could have been a moneymaker.''
   Vinton, who is appearing at Harrah's Marina Hotel Casino this
weekend, has returned to Nashville, where he originally recorded
the 1960's hits ``Blue Velvet'' and ``Roses are Red,'' for his
latest album, ``Timeless.''
</TEXT>
