<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TerrorSuspect     09-27 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Terror Suspect,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Extradition of American Suspected in Terrorist Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian-American accused of participating
in a deadly terrorist attack on a bus in Israel should be
extradited to the Jewish state to face trial, a federal judge ruled.
   Mahmoud El-Abed Ahmad, 36, hasn't been charged in the United
States, but has been imprisoned nearly 2{ years while attorneys
argued whether he would get a fair trial in Israel.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein ruled Tuesday that Ahmad
should be extradited, but then delayed the order for 10 days to
allow an appeal.
   American and Israeli authorities say Ahmad played a major part
in a 1986 firebomb and machine gun attack on a bus, killing four
Israelis.
   Ahmad's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, said
Ahmad did not participate in the attack but was implicated by two
cousins after they were tortured by Israeli security agents.
   In his ruling, Weinstein said Ahmad failed to show he ``would be
subject to procedures or treatment so offensive to our nation's
sense of decency as to obligate the court to block his
extradition.''
   Clark was in Los Angeles on Tuesday and did not immediately
return a call for comment. Clark has said he would appeal if
Weinstein ruled for extradition.
   Weinstein also rejected an argument that the bus attack was a
political act that would exempt Ahmad from extradition.
   ``Were a civilian to detonate a bomb in a peaceful marketplace
or rake peaceful shoppers with a machine gun to make a political
point, this and most civilized countries would not consider such
indiscriminate violence an unpunishable political act,'' Weinstein
said.
   Ahmad, who Israeli authorities sometimes refer to as Mahmoud
Abed Atta, is charged with taking part in an April 12, 1986, attack
in which three terrorists hurled Molotov cocktails and then opened
fire with machine guns on a bus carrying Jewish settlers in the
Occupied West Bank.
   Ahmad, who Israel says is a member of the Abu Nidal Palestinian
terrorist group, was born in the West Bank town of Ramallah and
became a U.S. citizen seven years ago. His last job was working at
his brother's filling station in Puerto Rico.
   According to travel documents, he was visiting his family in the
West Bank at the time of the attack, but he denies involvement.
   He was arrested upon entering Venezuela in April 1987. That
country did not have an extradition treaty with Israel and he was
handed over to U.S. authorities. Clark said that was illegal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0348EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Soviet     09-27 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Soviet,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Hails U.S. Chemical Weapons Ideas; Calls for End to Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze has hailed President Bush's call for the superpowers
to destroy most of their chemical weapons, but says Washington
should go further and agree to stop making all types of poison gas.
   In his speech Tuesday to the General Assembly, Shevardnadze also
challenged the United States to join the Soviets in halting all
nuclear tests and ending the production of weapons-grade plutonium
and uranium.
   Shevardnadze's address was a rapid reply to Bush's offer, in a
speech to the assembly on Monday, to cut U.S. chemical weapons
stockpiles by 80 percent if the Soviets reduce their arsenal to the
same level.
   The Soviet envoy said Moscow is ready to join the United States
and ``radically reduce or completely destroy'' all its chemical
weapons even before an international treaty is adopted.
   He said the Soviets had stopped producing some chemical weapons
already, and challenged Washington to do the same:
   ``Cease the production of chemical weapons, as we have done
already. I am referring also to binary weapons,'' said
Shevardnadze. Binary weapons are harmless until two chemicals are
combined just prior to use of the gas shell.
   Congress has approved funds to continue production of binary
poison gas bombs and shells.
   Viktor P. Karpov, the Soviet Union's chief arms control expert,
said ``It will not be sufficient only to get rid of old weapons if
the United States is going to produce new chemical weapons.''
   It was not clear from Shevardnadze's address whether Soviet
cooperation with a weapons cut hinged on Washington agreeing to end
poison gas production. The speech seemed deliberately vague on that
point.
   At White House, Bush said Tuesday: ``The reaction from the
Soviets to our proposals yesterday has been positive, so now the
goal is to get moving and try to work out these agreements.''
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater called
Shevardnadze's statements ``a very constructive response. Our
ultimate objective is total elimination of chemical weapons. And it
appears that both nations are now ready to act.''
   Bush's proposal is intended to spur a 40-nation conference in
Geneva to ban all chemical weapons within 10 years.
   The Soviets would have to scrap more poison gas, as U.S.
officials contend Moscow has far greater stockpiles than Washington
_ an acknowledged 50,000 tons compared to an estimated 30,000 tons
for the United States.
   Bush proposed a U.S.-Soviet agreement to begin those cuts at
once, while an international treaty is worked out in which the
United States would destroy 98 percent of its chemical weapons over
eight years if the Soviets joined the ban.
   The remaining 2 percent would be destroyed within 10 years if
all nations capable of building such weapons agreed to a total ban.
   Speaking to delegates of 159 nations on Tuesday, Shevardnadze
also said Moscow ``is ready to reinstate its moratorium on all
nuclear explosions any day and hour, if the United States
reciprocates.''
   He said Moscow was considering extending the 1963 Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty to cover underground nuclear explosions.
   In another disarmament proposal, Shevardnadze said that ``if
NATO countries agree to start talks on tactical (short-range)
nuclear weapons, the USSR will respond by further unilateral cuts
in its tactical nuclear weapons in Europe.''
   He also proposed that the production of nuclear fissionable
material for weapons be halted and that the ban be verified.
   The Soviet Union has announced it is halting the production of
enriched uranium.
   The weekend agreement that Bush and Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev will hold a summit meeting ``shows that we have moved
quite far ahead in solving a number of major bilateral and
international problems,'' Shevardnadze said.
   ``In our view, by the time the summit is held next year in late
spring or early summer, we may have passed the last turn on the
road toward a treaty reducing strategic offensive arms'', or
long-range nuclear missiles, by 50 percent.
   In a speech that praised the right of a people to choose its
government and course of development, Shevardnadze also wished
``every success'' to Poland's new government, the first East bloc
government not led by Communists.
   He pledged to cooperate with it.
   Shevardnadze denounced the ``so-called movements that allow
actions humiliating other nations, or use terrorist, barbaric and
inhuman methods in waging their struggle,'' a pointed reference to
kidnappings by Shiite Moslem extremists in Lebanon and Palestinian
guerrilla attacks on Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
