<DOCNO> AP890927-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     09-27 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Ends Restrictions On Travel, Takes Up Bill On Free Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under a bill being taken up by
Parliament, Hungarians will now be able to speak their mind and
agitate for political and social change without fear of
prosecution, the country's justice minsiter says.
   The amendment to the penal code, to be debated today, is just
another step toward the greater democracy promised by Hungary's
Communist leaders as they prepare for the free elections they have
promised by June.
   The bill is part of a package of legislation now before
Parliament that is designed to prepare the East bloc country for a
multiparty system and bring its laws in line with international
covenants on human rights.
   With Poland, Hungary is taking advantage of Moscow's greater
tolerance to end decades of one-party authoritarian rule.
   As Parliament convened Tuesday, it adopted important new bills
that will liberalize travel and emigration, removing most
restrictions on Hungarians wishing to travel or live abroad.
   Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar told Parliament that ``with the
broadening of civic rights, the penal code must be appropriately
reformed.''
   He said the amendment to be debated today aimed to ``guarantee
greater freedom for political activity.''
   Kulscar said a comprehensive reform of the penal code was under
way but that the amendments now before Parliament addressed certain
``urgent problems'' that could not wait.
   Hungary's rapid liberalization has allowed a degree of free
expression that would have been difficult even one year ago.
   Opposition leaders are now quoted in the official media and, in
most instances, people are permitted to demonstrate freely on a
wide range of issues including such sensitive topics as the
withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   The Communist Party has agreed to relinquish its leading role
and enter into free elections with independent parties, even
pledging to go into opposition if it loses.
   The Communists have also sat down with opposition groups and
parties to work out the transition to a multiparty system and the
country's first free elections in more than 40 years.
   The legislation now before Parliament at this session is partly
a result of agreements reached at those talks.
   Other key bills are to be taken up by Parliament in October.
They will include bills on political parties, electoral law and
changes in the judiciary. A measure on changes in the constitution
will remove references to the leading role of the Communist Party,
officials say.
   The emigration and travel laws adopted Tuesday lifted most
restrictions on travel and guarantee the right of Hungarians to
choose freely their desired place of residence, to leave and return
to their own country.
   Interior Minister Istvan Horvath said Hungarians who had
emigrated for personal or even for political reasons would be
allowed to return at any time.
   He said 19 restrictive measures would be removed when the laws
take effect Jan. 1.
   Hungary's liberal policies on travel have already been
illustrated by the government's decision in May to remove barbed
wire and other barriers along its border with Austria.
   The Budapest leadership angered its hard-line East German,
Czechoslovak and Romanian allies earlier this month when it decided
to open its borders to thousands of East Germans seeking to
emigrate to the West.
</TEXT>
