<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-27 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Share Prices Tumble After Early Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange erased
early gains and fell back.
   The dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 1.45 yen from Tuesday's
close of 142.80 yen. It opened lower at 141.60 yen and moved beteen
140.95 yen and 141.62 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 74.25
points, or 0.21 percent, erasing morning gains to finish at
35,370.57.
   Currency dealers said central banks from Japan, the United
States and Canada stepped into the market in an apparent
coordinated action meant to stem the dollar's upward trend. The
amount of intervention by the three banks was not immediately known.
   It was the second such concerted action by the three central
banks this week in Tokyo. The first one was on Monday.
   The Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, does not comment
on its monetary activities.
   ``The concerted intervention represented a firm commitment by
the monetary authorities to contain the dollar's upward move,''
following the weekend meeting of the Group of Seven nations, a
dealer at a major commercial bank said on condition of anonymity.
   Finance ministers and central bankers from the United States,
Japan, Canada, Britain, West Germany, France and Italy agreed at
the Washington meeting to closely cooperate in exchange markets to
check the dollar.
   Meanwhile, securities dealers said the market mood remained
positive after Tuesday's early advances. But the advances were
rolled back later in the day as investors sold for profit-taking.
   Institutional investors were still cautiously watching the
direction of foreign exchange rates, they said.
</TEXT>
