<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Garcia     09-27 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Garcia,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>N.J. Gubernatorial Candidate Reportedly Urged Wedtech Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's Republican gubernatorial candidate
wrote to the secretary of the Army in 1981 urging consideration of
the Wedtech Corp. for a contract, according to testimony in Rep.
Robert Garcia's extortion trial.
   In his letter to then-Army Secretary John O. Marsh, U.S. Rep.
James Courter called Wedtech a ``remarkable operation.''
   Wedtech, a Bronx defense contractor, collapsed in 1986 amid
allegations of corruption.
   Mario Moreno, former Wedtech vice chairman, testified Tuesday
that Garcia, D-N.Y., also showed other politicians Wedtech's
operations.
   Garcia's attorneys introduced the letter into evidence in the
U.S. District Court trial.
   Courter's campaign spokesman, Donald Sico, confirmed that Garcia
took the New Jersey congressman on a tour of Wedtech. The tour came
at a time when it was seeking a contract to build small engines for
the Army.
   ``Congressman Courter was impressed with the facility and sent a
letter expressing those sentiments to the secretary of the Army and
expressing his support for a procurement contract,'' Sico said.
``The letter was routine and innocuous and no further follow-up
efforts were made.''
   Garcia, a 56-year-old Bronx congressman, and his wife, Jane Lee
Garcia, 48, are charged with conspiring to trade favors to Wedtech
in return for a diamond and emerald necklace for Mrs. Garcia and
$185,000 in checks and interest-free loans.
   The Garcias pleaded innocent to charges of extortion,
conspiracy, bribery and receipt of illegal gratuities. If convicted
of the most serious charge, extortion, they face up to 20 years in
prison.
   In his questioning of Moreno, Garcia's lawyer, Robert Morvillo,
argued that Garcia helped Wedtech because the military contractor
provided jobs to his poor, minority constituents.
   Moreno, the government's main witness, testified that Wedtech
approached Garcia for help in several areas.
   ``In all of these contacts was there anything you considered
improper done?'' Morvillo asked.
   ``I don't think so,'' Moreno said.
   Moreno testified that Wedtech also sought help from others,
including Rep. Mario Biaggi and E. Robert Wallach, a friend of
former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese. Biaggi and Wallach have
been convicted of racketeering charges stemming from the Wedtech
scandal.
   Moreno, who is serving an 18-month prison sentence, pleaded
guilty to bribe- and theft-related charges in 1987.
</TEXT>
