<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Hungary     09-27 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Hungary,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twenty-Four Nations Propose Aid To Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community's leadership is
proposing $648 million in new aid for Poland and Hungary, money it
says is urgently needed so that economic instability does not
threaten the countries' reforms.
   Wrapping up a daylong meeting of 24 major non-communist donor
nations on ways to encourage democratic reform in Eastern Europe,
senior EEC officials also urged that Poland and Hungary work out
agreements with the International Monetary Fund to reschedule their
foreign debts.
   Hungary's debt is the highest per capita in the East bloc at $18
billion and Poland owes a debilitating $39 billion.
   Tuesday marked the second time the 24 nations have met to
discuss aid to Eastern Europe and they are scheduled to meet again
in November. The first meeting was held Aug. 1.
   A communique issued at the end of the meeting noted that
non-communist nations have already pledged $271 million in food aid
to Poland and Hungary.
   Of the $648 million in aid for next year, half would be financed
by the 12 European Community member nations and the remainder by
the 12 other donor nations. All donor nations and the European
Parliament must approve the proposals.
   The U.S. delegation did not pledge more aid than the $169
million already promised but indicated it could find additional
funds. It also said the $648 million should be seen as a minimum
amount, not a ceiling.
   Sweden, Denmark, Norway, Finland and Austria promised
development projects and credits totaling about $133 million.
   Jacques Delors, president of the European Community's executive
commission and Frans Andriessen, the Community's external relations
commissioner, said the economic and political reforms in Poland and
Hungary were ``still very fragile.''
   In a statement, they said Poles and Hungarians ``could well find
their new freedoms threatened by economic disorders.''
   ``It would be unthinkable to allow such disorders, which could
be alleviated through rapid action, to undermine the prospects for
change in Eastern Europe,'' they said.
   The program proposed by the commission included:
   _ Supplying pesticides, farm machinery and food to the Polish
government.
   _ Improving market access for Polish and Hungarian goods.
   _ Granting both countries new loans.
   _ Providing training to prepare both nations for market-oriented
economies.
   _ Aiding the clean up of industrialized areas and preservation
of historical and cultural sites.
   The non-EC donor nations are the six members of the European
Free Trade Association _ Austria, Finland, Iceland, Norway, Sweden
and Switzerland _ Japan, the United States, Canada, Australia, New
Zealand and Turkey.
   European Community foreign ministers may approve the plan as
early as next week at a regularly-scheduled EC meeting in
Luxembourg.
</TEXT>
