<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-27 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges Against Yen, Stocks Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its plunge against the
Japanese yen today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index fell
after gaining for four consecutive trading days.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose in early
trading but ended up losing 74.25 points, or 0.21 percent, closing
at 35,370.57. On Tuesday, it had gained 484.11 points, the
second-largest one-day gain this year, reaching a high of 35,444.82.
   The index had gained 974.24 points over four trading days.
   The dollar closed at 141.35 yen, down 1.45 yen from Tuesday's
142.80-yen finish. It opened at 141.60 yen and moved between 140.95
yen and 141.62 yen.
   The dollar's close today was its lowest since 140.10 yen on Aug.
11.
   The U.S. currency now has fallen 3.65 yen in the three trading
days since seven major industrial nations agreed to cooperate in
checking the dollar's recent rise. The agreement was followed by
coordinated dollar selling by central banks, traders said.
   The Bank of Japan was selling dollars again today, but the
amount was unknown, said Masafumi Koyama, a Bank of Tokyo trader.
   The central bank does not comment on its exchange market
activities.
   Koyama said the dollar was unlikely to fall much below 140 yen,
since an excessive fall over a short period would be unfavorable
for the international economy.
   ``In addition, considering that the dollar's recent fall has
been mainly prompted by the central banks' coordinated
intervention, it will not last long because it's impossible for the
banks to keep selling the dollar every day forever,'' Koyama said.
   ``As soon as they stop the dollar-selling operation, the
currency will start rising back,'' he said.
   On the stock exchange, ``the major reason for the index's fall
today was too much gain yesterday,'' said Tomoyuki Morimoto, a
dealer with New Japan Securities Co. Ltd. He said investors sold to
take profits after Tuesday's substantial gains.
   ``The rumor that West Germany might raise its interest rate also
discouraged investors,'' he said.
   Construction, electrical and housing issues all declined today.
   Trading was active, with first section volume estimated at 1
billion shares, up from Tuesday's 900 million.
</TEXT>
