<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Shrimpers     09-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Shrimpers,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Weigh Future in Hurricane-Ravaged Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCLELLANVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shrimpers whose families have made a
living off the sea for generations are vowing to return, even
though Hurricane Hugo wiped out shrimp beds and tossed around their
trawlers like toys.
   ``I'm going to have to get my house straight and my boat
straight, and I reckon I'll have to go south for shrimping,'' said
Charles Sellers, 37, a shrimper for 14 years.
   But, he added, ``I'll be back.''
   Generations of families have made their livelihoods shrimping
the marshes and creeks of the Intracoastal Waterway. Hugo, with its
135 mph winds and 17-foot tidal surge, destroyed the shrimp beds in
this fishing village of 500 at the height of the season.
   Shrimpers said the harvest this year had been one of the best
before Hugo struck, with daily catches running at 300 pounds to 500
pounds, which is double last year's. The shrimping season runs from
May to November.
   Shrimping is a $30 million a year industry along the coast, and
the fishermen aren't the only ones to suffer.
   ``The biggest thing is people who buy the shrimp _ the packing
houses _ they're all wiped out. They're destroyed,'' said Jimmy
Scott, 45, a shrimper for the past 21 years. ``By the time they get
it built back, the season is over.''
   His 68-foot boat, the Mary Margaret, lay stranded on the main
approach to the dock. Its riggings were tangled with a battered oak
tree.
   Scott said he'll still live in McClellanville, but will have to
find another place to shrimp.
   ``I'm born and raised here. I've got to stay here,'' he said.
   The town, three miles from the ocean, was founded in the early
1800s by planters who wanted to escape the intense summertime heat.
It evolved into a quaint village of moss-draped oak trees and
narrow streets, with many of its residents making their living
catching shrimp, oysters and fish.
   Thomas Colleton and his family of nine weathered the storm in
their home two miles from the water. Colleton, 57, who works for
other shrimpers, said he was unsure when he would work again.
   Wayne Potter's 60-foot trawler was destroyed and he lost his
house in the storm. But Potter, who has been a shimper for 35 years
like his father and grandfather before him, cannot imagine a life
away from the sea.
   Nor can other shrimpers, he said.
   ``They're going to stick with it. As soon as they get their
boats back in shape, they're going to get right back into
business,'' Potter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0550EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CityHermits     09-27 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-City Hermits,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sister's Death Brings Two Brothers Out of an Urban Cave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Ring and his sister, Marie, were mostly
homebodies but they kept up appearances by dressing well, going to
church every Sunday and sending bouquets of flowers to neighbors
every Christmas and Easter.
   Only when Marie Ring died Friday of hardening of the arteries at
age 58 did their hermit-like existence become known.
   Inside their three-story row house, the reclusive siblings lived
in what had become a kind of urban cave, with two dozen cats. They
had no running water, electricity or heat.
   They also had a third sibling, 62-year-old Vincent, who
apparently never went outside.
   Police said they found Marie dead, and 59-year-old John and
Vincent in poor mental condition. The brothers refused to leave the
house, but were sent to Boston City Hospital for evaluation. A
hospital spokeswoman would say only that they were in stable
condition and that doctors had forbidden interviews.
   But in an interview with The Boston Globe in Tuesday's editions,
John Ring said, ``The cats took all our money. ... Cost us $60 a
week worth of cat food. That's why we couldn't fix the place up.
But we're gonna now.''
   The city, though, has boarded up and condemned the house.
   And the Animal Rescue League has taken the cats.
   Gerri Abban, the cashier at Bell's Market near the house, said
the Rings would not let anyone into their home. She asked city
counselors and priests to help them, but they told her the family
had a right to privacy.
   Ms. Abban said she and her bosses, Matthew Cohen and his son,
Alan, were able to provide some assistance.
   ``I sold them charcoal in the winter so they could heat the
house,'' Ms. Abban said. ``I sold them rubbing alcohol, five
bottles at a time, so they could cook. I sold them bottle after
bottle of Anacin because they'd get wicked headaches from the smell
in the house. Paper plates, paper cups, bottled water. It was
unbelievable.''
   Their toilets didn't flush. They used candles and flashlights.
And they cooked meals in a pan on an alcohol burner.
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said Matthew Ryan, a 72-year-old
retired union leader who has lived next door to the Rings for about
30 years. ``Who could get by today without electricity and gas and
water? ... I would have helped them, but they weren't people who
wanted you to get involved.''
   John Ring told the Globe that Vincent was wounded in World War
II and hadn't worked since 1953; Marie quit working in 1957 and
John hasn't had a job since 1961. They had lived in the house with
their parents, who died more than 10 years ago.
   Ryan said he thought Vincent had died until a fire broke out in
two nearby houses 15 years ago.
   He saw a man with a beard down to his belt and a blanket over
his head. ``I said, `Who is that?' And someone said, `That's
Vincent.' I never believed there was (a third person) in there.''
   Matthew Cohen, proprietor of Bell's since 1956, said the Rings
paid with personal checks that occasionally bounced. Cohen, who
gave them discounts, said the brothers received ``disability checks
or veterans checks or something.''
   He tried to send an electrician and a plumber to their house,
but the Rings wouldn't let them in. He knew John Ring was on
medication, and when he was off it.
   ``If John didn't take his medication, he went wild _ when he'd
come down to the store to buy, he'd stuff his pockets, he'd throw
things around and yell at people. We understood him. We did the
best we could. We got him home.''
   Cohen said Marie Ring, once an accountant, was ``a very fine
lady, always well-spoken. She seemed to be well-read and her whole
life was taking care of her two brothers. It's a mystery to me why,
but she did it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
