<FIRST>r i PM-Newspage-Baseball     09-27 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Baseball,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cubs Clinch Baseball Division Title; Giants Assured Tie</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor XSMTL1; LaserPhoto XSMTL3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Cubs became this year's first
baseball team to win a division title, beating Montreal, 3-2, to
clinch the National League East crown.
   Chicago will open the playoffs Wednesday night at Wrigley Field,
all but certainly against San Francisco. Despite losing Tuesday,
the Giants clinched a tie for the National League West title as
Cincinnati beat second-place San Diego, 5-3.
   In Montreal, a crowd of 11,615, bolstered by three tour groups
from Chicago, sat quiet for most of the night at Olympic Stadium.
   In the eighth inning, Cubs fans roared when Ryne Sandberg dashed
home with the winning run as right fielder Hubie Brooks bobbled a
single.
   The victory made Don Zimmer a champion for the first time in 11
years of managing. After the final out, the Cubs darted out of the
dugout and celebrated at the pitching mound.
   The Cubs have not been in the World Series since 1945 and have
not won it since 1908, but back in Chicago, fans were dreaming of a
world championship.
   ``This is a major, major thing,'' said 23-year-old Franci Nenko,
after watching the game on television with about 300 fans at the
Cubby Bear, across the street from Wrigley Field. ``We're going all
the way now!''
</TEXT>
