<HEAD>Fair Skies Cover Much of Nation; Cold Hit Midwest Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fair skies covered much of the nation early today, and
temperatures again dropped into the 30s and 40s from the northern
Plains to northern New England.
   Overnight temperatures were expected to drop into the 30s in
parts of Wisconsin, Michigan, Iowa, Illinois and Indiana. Frost and
freeze advisories were in effect for all of Michigan, and a frost
advisory was in effect in central and northern Indiana.
   Skies were fair to partly cloudy over most of the West, where
warmer temperatures prevailed, but moist southwest winds produced
some brief showers and thunderstorms in Utah late Tuesday and early
today.
   Thunderstorm winds gusted to 55 mph just south of Salt Lake
City's airport late Tuesday afternoon, and gusts elsewhere hit 40
mph.
   Miami set a new record high for the date Tuesday with 93
degrees, exceeding the old mark of 92 set in 1941.
   The nation's cold spot Tuesday was International Falls, Minn.,
with a low of 25 degrees.
   Other reports at 4 a.m. EDT:
