<FIRST>r a PM-GreenRiver     09-27 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green River Suspect Pleads Innocent to Weapons Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man under investigation in the Green
River serial slayings of up to 48 young women pleaded innocent to
possession of a firearm while a fugitive.
   William Jay Stevens II finished a sentence for burglary and
escape in Seattle on Monday and was brought here Tuesday by federal
marshals, said Deputy U.S. Marshal Marvin Lutes.
   Magistrate James Hovis entered a plea of innocent on behalf of
Stevens to the charge of being a felon and fugitive in possession
of a firearm.
   Roger Peven, a court-appointed defense attorney, said he would
move today for a bail hearing to win Stevens' release.
   The Green River Task Force has characterized Stevens as a
``viable suspect'' in its investigation into the deaths of 40 women
and the disappearances of eight others in the Northwest from
1982-84.
   Stevens has not been charged in any of the killings and has
denied he is the killer.
   A .45-caliber Colt handgun found in a house where Stevens was
arrested in January is the basis for the federal charge. He was
arrested for a 1981 escape from a work release center where he was
serving a burglary sentence.
   If convicted on the weapon possession charge, Stevens faces a
maximum 10 year prison term and $250,000 fine.
