<FIRST>r a PM-One-StudentSchool     09-27 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-One-Student School,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuttyhunk Hires Teacher for One Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSNOLD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This island town's one-room, one-pupil
school has hired its one teacher _ a former professor with a
doctorate in education.
   Eloise Seifert of Centerville, the former education coordinator
of schools in coastal Scituate, beat out a field of applicants from
around the country for the $24,000 job on the island, which has a
year-round population of 50 people.
   ``We got applications from people who didn't have any
credentials but figured we might get stuck, and people who just
decided it looked like a pleasant place to be for a year,'' said
Russell Latham, superintendent of the Berkley-Gosnold schools.
   Seifert, an owner of a Barnstable cleaning business who received
her doctorate from Boston University, also has been a university
professor in New York and a reading specialist in the Needham
public schools.
   ``It's assumed by some that it's a snap,'' Latham said. ``But
it's quite a job to offer a young man a chance to do some
independent work when there are only two of you in the room and to
plan interesting things all the time.''
   Island life also may be an adjustment. The only telephone is a
pay phone at the general store. And a ferry to the mainland runs
only on Tuesdays and Fridays in the winter.
   Gosnold is the only town on Cuttyhunk island, a popular summer
tourist spot about 15 miles southwest of Woods Hole. The town has
an inn-restaurant, a bakery and deli-style sandwich shop, the
general store, municipal offices and a library.
   In the 1930s, as many as 17 students were enrolled in Gosnold's
century-old school house. But this year, like last, only one
youngster is in school, and it may close in 1991 when the
13-year-old seventh grader attends high school on the mainland.
   ``The school probably will close unless some family presents a
child,'' Latham said.
</TEXT>
