<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0611EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     09-27 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Begins Cease-Fire, But Sinhalese Extremists Ignore It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops waging a campaign
against Sinhalese militants today began observing a three-day
cease-fire but extremists ignored the truce, killing at least two
people.
   The government had hoped the cease-fire would encourage members
of the militant People's Liberation Front to open peace talks with
the Sinhalese-dominated government.
   But less than four hours after the cease-fire began at 6 a.m.,
Sinhalese extremists shot and killed two bodyguards of Jayasinghe
Bandara, a member of the government's Provincial Council, military
officials said.
   The gunmen ambushed Bandara's car about 80 miles east of Colombo
but he escaped unharmed, said the officials, who cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   Sinhalese radicals also set fire to three government-owned buses
in central Sri Lanka, but there were no casualties, they said
   The cease-fire was ordered one week after Indian peacekeeping
soldiers suspended military operations against minority Tamil
rebels demanding a separate homeland in the northeast.
   Tamil separatists have so far honored a truce called for in the
agreement, under which the 42,000 remainingIndian troops are to be
out of the country by year's end.
   The decision to call the three-day cease-fire was made during a
meeting last week between President Ranasinghe Premadasa and the
five major opposition party leaders.
   ``It was agreed as an immediate step to call upon all armed
militant groups to desist from acts of violence and sabotage,''
officials said in a statement. ``If the armed militant groups
respond favorably to this call, ... This period of three days would
be extended.''
   The cease-fire was one of 10 proposals in an opposition-proposed
plan aimed at ending the campaign of strikes, assassinations and
terror inspired by the Sinhalese militants.
   The People's Liberation Front began its anti-government campaign
after Sri Lanka signed a peace accord in July 1987 aimed at ending
the Tamil insurgency. by offering the Tamils limited autonomy if
they would give up their weapons.
   Troops from neighboring India were invited in to supervise the
surrender.
   But the Sinhalese militants said the accord offered too many
concessions to the mainly Hindu Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of
Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   Tamils claim they are denied jobs and education by the
mostly-Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population
and dominate the government and military.
   Sinhalese militants also objected to the presence of Indian
peacekeeping troops, saying it threatened the country's sovereignty.
   More than 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian peacekeeping
troops, have been killed in the Tamil insurgency since it started
in 1983. More than 5,000 others have died in the Sinhalese backlash.
   More than 200,000 leaflets in the Sinhalese language were
dropped from airplanes by government troops Tuesday over remote
villages. The leaflets offered up to 20,000 rupees ($510) to
extremists who surrender.
   ``It is foolish to destroy young lives in this way. You are
destroying the future of the country's youth. Take advantage of
this opportunity and give yourselves up, you will be warmly
received and fully protected,'' the leaflets said.
   There were no reports of any surrender, but officials said it
was too early for reports to come in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0053 </DOCNO>
