<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-27 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold UP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened in early European trading
today, pounded by central bank intervention in earlier Asian
trading, currency dealers said.
   Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said confirmed dollar sales by the Bank
of Japan and West German Bundesbank and reported sales by the U.S.
Federal Reserve and the Bank of Canada in the Asian session added
to the market's nervousness after two days of staggered open-market
central bank interventions.
   Traders reported the Bank of England and central banks of Italy,
Belgium and Spain were selling dollars in early European trading.
   The size of central bank intervention since last weekend's
meeting of finance chiefs from the Group of Seven industrialized
nations remains unknown. But traders said it was the frequency of
sales rather than the size that was pushing down the dollar.
   ``The central banks are trying to show the market they're
insistent about a lower dollar,'' said one trader in Milan, Italy.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 1.45 yen to a closing 141.35 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 141.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   --1.8735 West German marks, down from 1.8885
   --1.6255 Swiss francs, down from 1.6390
   --6.3450 French francs, down from 6.3990
   --2.1268 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1480
   --1,355.00 Italian lire, down from 1,377.00
   --1.1753 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1750
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6225 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6215 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $368 a troy ounce, compared with late
Tuesday's $367.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $369.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $369, up from $367.75 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.09 to close at $369.92.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.30 a troy ounce, down from
Tuesday's $5.31.
</TEXT>
