<SECOND>PM-Israel-Activist,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Protester Abie Nathan Pleads Guilty To Meeting With PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace activist Abie Nathan pleaded guilty
today to breaking an Israeli law that bans contacts with the PL0,
but said he would keep defying such laws in his quest for peace
with the Arabs.
   Nathan, 63, who operates the pirate radio station ``Voice of
Peace,'' was indicted last year for meeting PLO Chief Yasser Arafat
and several of his aides in Tunisia and France in September 1988.
   ``I knew about the law and I know that it entailed punishment,
but I acted in order to save the lives of people and I am prepared
to break the law to acheive this,'' Nathan said in an emotional
plea to the court.
   ``I think I convinced our main enemy to grasp the olive
branch,'' Nathan said. ``I don't think I did any harm to Israel's
security.''
   The law forbids unauthorized contacts with ``terrorist groups''
and provides for a maximum three year jail sentence. The PLO is not
named in the law, but Israel considers the group a terrorist
organization.
   On Wednesday, the Jerusalem Post reported that two Palestinians
from the occupied West Bank met with Arafat abroad recently with
the knowledge of Israel's Defense Ministry.
   It quoted an Israeli source as saying the government does not
encourage such meetings but does not punish Palestinians for taking
part.
   Nathan's sentencing was scheduled for Tuesday.
   Prosecuting attorney Raanan Ben Yosef asked for a stiff
sentence, saying Nathan's meetings abroad harmed Israel's security
by ``legitimatizing terrorist organizations and serving to
de-demonize Arafat.''
   Nathan's radio station broacasts from a ship in the
Mediterranean. He is known for making a private peace mission to
Egypt when the country was at war with Israel in the 1960s and
staging a 45-day hunger strike in 1978 to protest the building of
Jewish settlements in the occupied lands.
</TEXT>
