<HEAD>Eds: Fixes typo in marijuana in lede. Pickup 2nd, `Michael...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who looked after
impounded drugs was charged today with stealing $16 million worth
of heroin, marijuana and cocaine from a narcotics storage facility.
   Michael Wallace allegedly siphoned off seized drugs and then
resold them, police told Sydney's Central Local Court.
   Wallace, 36, who worked at the Federal Drug Registry, was
arrested during early morning searches of his home and those of his
parents and brother.
   Police said they recovered 35 pounds of heroin, about 4.5 pounds
of cocaine, 22 pounds of hashish and a small quantity of marijuana
as well as $190,000 in cash.
   Wallace entered no plea to charges of possession of illegal
drugs and obtaining money illegally. He was ordered held in custody
until his next court appearance on Oct. 4.
   John Johnson, Deputy Commissioner of the Australian Federal
Police, said today that more police officers may be involved.
   ``In the ideal world, we would hope this would never occur,''
Johnson said. ``For it to take place in an organization like ours
is highly embarrassing and, of course, gives us no credit at all.''
   He said it was not the first time an officer had been charged
with stealing drugs from the registry, but the alleged amounts were
the largest.
