<FIRST>r a PM-TopfreeTen     09-27 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Topfree Ten,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Claim Constitutional Right To Bare Breasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state law that allows men to go
bare-chested in public but forbids women from doing the same is
unconstitutional, contends a group of women fighting for ``topfree
equality.''
   Ten women arrested June 24 for doffing their tops at a beach on
Lake Ontario argued Tuesday in court that a statute prohibiting
them from baring their breats is discriminatory.
   City Court Judge John Manning Regan will resume hearing
testimony in the case today.
   The statute denies the women their constitutionally guaranteed
right to equal protection under the law, said attorney Sharon Kelly
Sayers, who represents eight of the women.
   ``This statute is a tool for police officers to harass and
intimidate women,'' she said. ``It's a discriminatory law.''
   Assistant District Attorney Ann Chase said she does not plan to
address the constitutional issue.
   The women were charged under New York's exposure of person
statute for refusing to put shirts on when Monroe County sheriff's
deputies asked them to.
   ``They are here only because they are women, doing simple
everyday things that men are allowed to do everyday,'' said Jeffrey
Wicks, attorney for defendant Nina Leibowitz.
   Topfree Equality picnics have been held since 1986, when several
of the same women were arrested for going topless. Those charges
were dismissed when a judge ruled that the topless picnic had been
an expression of free speech.
   Women are allowed to expose their breasts while entertaining or
breast-feeding, said group organizer Mary Lou Schloss, who
represented herself at the trial.
   Those exemptions ``result in a patriarchal situation where a
woman is `allowed' to expose her breasts to feed a baby or to dance
provocatively to sexually arouse men, but may not for her own
comfort swim or sun topfree,'' she said.
   State law barred men from baring their chests until 1942,
Schloss said, when their protests provoked a change in the statute.
   ``Women must be allowed the same right that men have had for 50
years in New York state, the right to enjoy the sun, air and water
topless,'' she said.
</TEXT>
