<HEAD>President Lauds Hollywood, Bubbles Over Steve Martin</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS time element in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says Hollywood is owed thanks
for recent movies that have portrayed the ravages of drug addiction.
   ``I want to thank the film industry for helping stop this
terrible threat to our kids,'' the president told a star-studded
gala tribute to the American Film Institute Tuesday night. ``I
welcome your leadership.''
   Bush named ``Lean on Me,'' ``Clean and Sober'' and ``Dancing as
Fast as I Can,'' as motion pictures that have shown the
consequences of drug abuse.
   The president also had a ringside seat for an unusual
performance by comic Steve Martin, who performed as ``The Great
Flydini,'' a magician with an uncanny knack for pulling things out
of the open fly of his pants.
   Out came eggs, a telephone, a cocktail glass _ filled no less _
scarves, smoke from a cigarette and a hand puppet that gyrated and
sang Pagliacci. For an encore, Martin blew bubbles from the same
opening in his tuxedo.
   ``Imagine meeting Steve Martin, something I've always wanted to
do,'' Bush said with a straight face. ``Now I want to find the name
of his tailor.''
   Television host Phil Donahue offered a more barbed critique of
Martin's performance.
   ``Boy, it's been a while since I've seen the president of the
United States entertained by a guy with bubbles coming out of his
crotch,'' said Donahue.
   The dinner at the National Building Museum marked the 24th
anniversary of the Rose Garden ceremony at which President Lyndon
B. Johnson signed the legislation creating the National Endowment
for the Arts and its sister endowment for the humanities.
   Two years later, the NEA spawned the American Film Institute, a
private non-profit entity that works to preserve film and
television and to train young directors.
   The black-tie crowd included actors Charlton Heston, Douglas
Fairbanks Jr., John Travolta and Christopher Reeve and actresses
Marlo Thomas and Brooke Shields.
