<SECOND>PM-Budd Funeral,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zola Budd Skips Father's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOEMFONTEIN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Track star Zola Budd sent a
wreath but did not attend today's funeral for her father, who was
found shot to death in his farmhouse last week.
   South African news media reported that Frank Budd, 59, had said
in his will that his three daughters were not welcome at his
funeral.
   Two of the daughters, and Budd's only son, Quintus, did attend.
But Ms. Budd and her husband, liquor store owner Mike Pieterse,
were not there.
   Ms. Budd has been estranged from her father for several years.
He did not attend her April 15 wedding, saying he was not invited.
   Ms. Budd's mother, Tossie, also was not at the funeral. She was
divorced from Budd shortly after the athlete competed in the Los
Angeles Olympics in 1984 on a British passport.
   Zola Budd told South African newspapers after her father's death
that she believed his homosexuality was the cause of her parents'
divorce. But police have said they are not investigating any
connection between Budd's homosexuality and his death.
   Chris Botha Barnard, whose age has been given as 24 or 26, was
arrested Friday, hours after Budd's body was found in the bedroom
of a house he had built on a friend's farm.
   Police said Barnard had worked for Budd for a few days, doing
construction. Police said they found Budd's shotgun, which they
said was used to kill him, his pickup truck, and other belongings
after they arrested Barnard.
   Because of her father's British heritage, Zola Budd was able to
obtain a British passport quickly to compete in the 1984 Summer
Olympics. South Africans are barred from the Olympics and most
international track competitions because of the government's
apartheid policies of racial segregation.
   In the 3,000-meter run in Los Angeles, the barefoot Ms. Budd
collided with U.S. star Mary Decker, and the American was unable to
continue. Budd finished seventh amid a chorus of boos.
   She later set several world distance running records while
living and training in Britain. But she was constantly dogged by
anti-apartheid activists who said she should not be allowed to
compete because of her South African connections.
   Ms. Budd, 23, returned to South Africa in May 1988, and has
announced plans to forego international competition.
</TEXT>
