<SECOND>PM-Hand Severed,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mental Patient Cuts Off Hand Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man released from a mental hospital Aug.
28 cut off his left hand for the second time in seven months with a
circular saw, police said.
   The hand had been reattached the first time but could not be
saved again, doctors said.
   ``He said the hand was useless and he didn't want it anymore,''
said Waterford Township police Officer John McLain. ``He said he
wanted to kill himself, but was feeling OK now and didn't want to
anymore.''
   State mental health officials want to know why the unidentified
27-year-old Pontiac man was released from the state-run Clinton
Valley Center. He had been living in a group home with five other
mental patients since his release.
   ``There was every indication he was doing well'' before his
release, hospital Director Anthony Drabik said. ``It's tragic. We
feel very badly about this.''
   The man cut the hand off in February in an apparent suicide
attempt, police said. He apparently bought a circular saw, checked
into a motel Monday and severed his hand again, McLain said.
   The man's hand could not be reattached because it was a jagged
cut, said Dr. Robert Aranosian, chief of emergency medicine at
Pontiac Osteopathic Hospital.
   Thomas Watkins Jr., director of the state Department of Mental
Health, said a review of the placement agency, the hospital and the
home will be conducted to see if the incident could have been
prevented.
</TEXT>
