<HEAD>Bank Robber Takes Four Hostages, Runs Over Two</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank robber making a getaway took four
employees hostage, then ordered them to lie side by side in a field
and drove his car over two of them, killing one and seriously
injuring another, police said.
   The other hostages escaped without injury as the man shot at
them.
   A suspect, described as in his early 20s, was arrested Tuesday
at a roadblock between Kalamazoo and Battle Creek and awaited
arraignment today.
   His name was withheld pending the filing of formal charges.
   The gunman, wearing a hood, met the employees at the First
Federal Bank of Michigan branch in Perry as they arrived for work
and took an undisclosed amount of cash when the vault opened at 9
a.m., said State Police Lt. John Fiedler.
   He drove away after forcing the four into his car, but returned
to the scene minutes later. He ordered three of the employees to
get into a car and follow him, keeping one with him to ensure the
others followed, police said.
   The two cars pulled over north of Battle Creek, and the gunman
and his hostages drove in one car about three miles to Assyria
Township, police said.
   The man ordered all four employees to lie on the edge of a
field, then tried to back his car over them, hitting two, Fiedler
said. The others ran.
   Killed was Marilyn Parks, 55, of Owosso. Betty Green of Perry
was listed in serious but stable condition today at Ingham Medical
Center in Lansing.
   Cash and a handgun were found in the suspect's car, Fiedler said.
</TEXT>
