<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-PEN     09-27 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-PEN,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>PEN Says Rushdie Case Not Isolated Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie is not the only author vilified
for writing about topics that upset Moslems, the PEN international
writers association says.
   ``There is a new threat to freedom of expression,'' Alexander
Blokh, PEN's international secretary, said Tuesday.
   Iranian radical Moslem clerics offered a multimillion dollar
bounty for the death of Rushdie, whose book ``The Satanic Verses''
was thought by many Moslems to be blasphemous.
   While protesting the campaign waged against Rushdie, Blokh said
his group became aware of other writers living abroad who face
``pressures, intimidation, sometimes direct threats'' because of
their work.
   PEN, the International Association of Poets, Playwrights,
Editors and Novelists, is holding its world congress this week in
Toronto and Montreal. It recommended that its member chapters
invite writers in the Islamic community to discuss such situations,
their causes and the means to find a solution.
   ``We would ask them to come and very discreetly tell us their
story if they want to,'' Blokh said at a news conference that
concluded the Toronto portion of the conference.
   ``They are at certain moments in a state of terror,'' he said.
``He (a writer) can be in a very free city ... and yet he lives in
a very permanent state of terror, discreet terror.''
   Blokh, who lives in Paris, said he also learned of a similar
case in Moscow.
   ``I'm not going to tell you any concrete cases because they are
still quite secret,'' he said.
   Blokh said only the Rushdie case was known to have ``official
status,'' issued by a government, but other incidents of
``religious fanaticism'' certainly could be considered a new threat
to freedom of expression that came as a surprise at the end of the
20th century.
   He said the new form of censorship discovered only recently was
``something for which we're not prepared.''
   The threats were coming not from a government but from a ``very
hard to define'' community, he said.
   The group's recommendation on intolerance and fanaticism, as
translated by The Associated Press from a French copy, said the
Rushdie incident ``is not isolated and revealed many other
pressures, happily less grave, but equally as unacceptable for
freedom of expression.''
   It said the pressures might be exercised through diplomatic,
family, community, religious or terrorist routes ``by governmental
authorities or others in the name of Islam.''
   Blokh said the association wanted to be careful not to appear
racist in discussing the situation but wants its members ``to study
together our possible reaction and how we should face this new
threat to freedom of expression.''
   The association also recommended increased contacts between
writers from Western and Eastern European countries, with a first
session planned next year in Vienna, Austria, to work toward
exchanging information that may have been missed during the past 40
years of limited contacts.
   A new Russian Soviet chapter based in Moscow is attending the
conference for the first time. PEN had kept out the Soviet Union
for 65 years because of its persecution of writers and other
intellectuals, and Moscow had regarded the authors' group as
anti-Communist.
   PEN, founded in 1921, has 11,000 members in more than 90
chapters organized along language lines. The international
association of poets, playwrights, editors, essayists and novelists
campaigns actively to free writers who have been imprisoned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
