<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     09-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese `Boat People' Land in Southern Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAHA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 230 people arrived in southern
Japan today in a 50-ton wooden boat, many of them believed to be
Chinese seeking jobs, not asylum, in Asia's wealthiest nation.
   The boat people were the first to land in Japan since an
unprecedented influx forced the government two weeks ago to tighten
its policy on who will be accepted as refugees, officials said.
   The new arrivals, who appeared tired but healthy, were the fifth
group to be brought ashore in Okinawa, Japan's southernmost
prefecture, since August, said Kazuyoh Sameshima, a spokesman in
Naha for the Maritime Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard. It was
the largest group of refugees this year.
   Sameshima said 231 people were crowded aboard the boat, which a
coast guard ship escorted into port at Naha, Okinawa's capital,
1,000 miles from Tokyo.
   Though most were young men, about 12 children were aboard,
Sameshima said. Young mothers could be seen cradling babies as
immigration officials began herding them on to buses. Most refused
to answer reporters' questions.
   Sameshima refused to comment on whether they were Vietnamese.
But he said the boat originally had departed from Vietnam and
stopped in China because of typhoon damage. A new boat brought the
group from China to Japan.
   A Vietnamese interpreter who requested anonymity said that
although some of the passengers spoke Vietnamese, most appeared to
be Chinese.
   After being checked by immigration officials, the arrivals were
taken to a nearby university, where they were to spend the night on
a gymnasium floor. Officials said they would be transferred soon to
an immigration center that is already filled to three times its
normal capacity.
   So far this year, 2,950 Vietnamese boat people have arrived in
Japan, compared with 219 in all of 1988.
   On Sept. 13, Japan began a policy of screening boat people,
accepting those deemed to be fleeing political persecution but
refusing permission for economic migrants to stay.
   Today's arrivals were the first since then, said an official at
the Refugee Division of the Justice Ministry in Tokyo.
   He said if immigration authorities determine Indochinese among
the boat people had fled their homeland for economic reasons, they
would be detained until accepted back in their home country or in a
third country.
   If they are not Indochinese, they are not eligible for refugee
status and will be repatriated, the Foreign Ministry has said.
</TEXT>
