<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceLawsuit     09-27 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Lawsuit,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discrimination Suit Seeks `Level Playing Field'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven white policemen demanding ``a level
playing field'' are suing over a 1979 court-ordered affirmative
plan that they say unfairly promoted less-qualified minorities
ahead of them.
   It could be the first test of a recent U.S. Supreme Court ruling
that gives municipal employees the right to challenge
court-approved, preferential employment practices.
   The suit, filed Monday in Superior Court, claims the seven
officers are the victim of racial quotas. It maintains that the
city has violated a state civil rights law against the use of race
or sex in hiring and promotion.
   Robert Gyemant, the attorney for the officers, said his clients
should not be forced to pay the price to right wrongs carried out
before any of them were involved with the department.
   ``All we are saying is why make our clients pay for it,'' he
said.
   He said his clients only want ``a level playing field.''
   The suit seeks back pay, punitive damages and an end to the
alleged discrimination. The amount of damages sought was not
disclosed.
   Earlier this year, the U.S. Supreme Court decided that white
firefighters hired in Birmingham, Ala., after a consent decree was
approved could fight the preferential promotion of allegedly less
qualified black firefighters.
   In San Francisco, city figures show that when the court plan was
adopted in 1979 there were 1,590 officers, with 85.8 percent
non-minority, 14.2 percent minority, 95.8 percent male and 4.2
percent female.
   As of Sept. 12, there were 1,777 officers: 71.6 were
non-minority, 28.4 percent minority, 89.8 percent male and 10.2
percent female.
</TEXT>
