<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia 1stLd-Writethru   09-27 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0510,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Call for Postponement of Slovenian Constitutional Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 10th, `We are...' to UPDATE with rally,
background. Pickup 11th pvs, `Milan Kucan...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's deeply split
Communist leadership today asked Slovenia's legislature to postpone
a vote on constitutional changes that would spell out the
republic's right to secede.
   But Miran Potrc, president of Slovenia's parliament, said
Slovenians ``are determined'' to go ahead with the amendments and
media reports said lawmakers would almost certainly approve the
package.
   ``The Slovenian parliament is the only legal institution that
can decide on such crucial matters,'' Potrc said during a
legislative session today in the regional capital, Ljubljana.
   Besides declaring Slovenia's right to secede, the changes place
strict controls on the use of army units in the republic and
restrict imposition of martial law there by Yugoslavia's collective
eight-member presidency.
   But after a 17-hour debate that lasted into today, the country's
policy-setting Communist Party Central Committee voted 97-40 to
call on Slovenian Communists to ``postpone the adoption of the
amendments in question.''
   Delegates to the hurriedly convened Belgrade session said
passage of the amendments might lead to military intervention in
Slovenia, the richest and most Western-oriented of Yugoslavia's six
republics.
   And there were sharp exchanges between delegates from Slovenia
and Serbia, home to the national capital, Belgrade.
   Serbia, the largest of the republics, advocates transforming
Yugoslavia from a loose federation to a more unified nation by
limiting regional rights. Serbian delegates said that the changes
would open the way to eventual dissolution of the Yugoslav
federation.
   The Slovenian leadership said Tuesday, however, that the
amendments in no way contradict the federal constitution.
   ``We are convinced that the changes will only serve to
strengthen, and not to threaten, the concept of Yugoslavia as a
free, democratic and equitable community of peoples,'' Potrc said.
   As he spoke, 2,000 workers of a construction company in
Titograd, capital of the southern republic of Montenegro, went into
the streets today to protest ``the impending adoption of the
controversial amendments,'' the official Tanjug news agency
reported.
   Yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous
provinces, each with its own government and party structure. Serbia
is the largest republic and Kosovo and Vojvodina provinces are part
of it but not fully subject to its control.
   The decentralized system of government and collective federal
presidency were devised in 1974 to prevent one republic from
gaining sway over the others, but it has resulted in an ineffective
government by compromise.
   Milan Kucan, head of the Slovenian Communist Party, said the
Central Committee debate on the issue amounted to ``a restriction
of the sovereign will of the Slovenian people.''
   ``Slovenian communists will choose (to defend) the interests of
the Slovenian people (rather than) becoming quislings,'' Kucan said.
   Ivo Druzic, a Central Committee member from Croatia, warned that
should the military intervene to prevent the changes ``this would
mean the compromising of the army command which would (be seen as)
suspending the constitution instead of defending it.''
   But a military representative, Adm. Petar Simic, said, ``the
Yugoslav army was not a ... mercenary army that would allow anyone
to use it as they see fit.''
   Janez Kocijancic, a Slovenian businessman, referring to the June
military crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in China, asked
whether ``anyone wishes to expand Tiananmen Square to the gates of
Trieste,'' an Italian city on the Yugoslav border.
   Slovenia is the country's smallest but most economically
developed republic, accounting for more than 20 percent of the
national product and 30 percent of hard currency exports.
   Its population, however, represents just eight percent of the
country's total.
   Belgrade radio reported that Janez Drnovsek, a Slovene who
currently heads Yugoslavia's collective presidency, cut short his
visit to the United Nations and was expected back in Slovenia today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
