<FIRST>r a PM-Sergeants-Stress     09-27 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sergeants-Stress,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fort Benning Implementing Stress Management for Drill Sergeants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT BENNING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soldiers known for inflicting
stress on recruits often feel stress themselves, and Fort Benning
plans to make sure they can handle it.
   Drill sergeants will undergo a stress management program
designed to avoid trainee and spouse abuse.
   Officials at Fort Benning denied the program was prompted by a
February incident that left 39 basic-training soldiers hospitalized.
   The soldiers suffered from a breakdown of muscle associated with
physical exertion. The ailment can cause kidney failure. After the
incident, 27 officers were reassigned from the Infantry Center.
   ``Drill sergeant duty is a little bit different than other
duty,'' said Sgt. Maj. William Mayo of the Infantry Training Center
Command. ``They have long hours and their job is dealing with
people all the time _ and doing the same job all the time.''
   Mayo said the program has been implemented at Fort Sill, Okla.,
and Fort Leonard Wood, Mo., and has lowered the number of trainee
abuse cases there.
   He said the program will try to show the sergeants and their
wives the stresses of working 14 hours a day for the two years they
serve as drill sergeants. He noted that the wives seldom see their
husbands during that time.
</TEXT>
