<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees     09-27 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Refugees Flood Into Embassy Compound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and illnesses worsened the
plight of hundreds of East German refugees crowding the West German
Embassy compound, but more newcomers kept scaling the fence of the
mission's garden today.
   According to the refugees who talked to reporters, the number of
people thronging the compound had reached 1,500 by midday.
   Only 177 of them were said to have left Tuesday and today,
accepting an East German government offer of guaranteed emigration
within six months if they return home.
   In talks with the refugees Tuesday, East German emissary
Wolfgang Vogel, a confidant of Communist leader Erich Honecker,
said those willing to return could emigrate without facing
prosecution for ``flight from the republic'' and other offenses.
   The emissary was evidently seeking to persuade larger numbers of
refugees to accept the government offer, but the majority
apparently remained skeptical.
   Some of the refugees told reporters that the crowd inside
contained ``a lot of people with a criminal record, people who are
not politically motivated'' to emigrate from East Germany.
   In an effort to accommodate the swelling crowd, several hundred
beds today were made available by the West German army.
   Nevertheless, living conditions in the compound were getting
ever more precarious for the refugees, most of them housed in Red
Cross tents.
   Several of the more than 250 children were said to have fallen
ill with diarrhea and colds following heavy rain that set in during
the night.
   ``We are humans, not animals, aren't we? They cannot let us rot
away here, can they?'' a man asked Western reporters talking to him
through the fence.
   ``I don't accept the (East German) offer. I leave here only to
the West or in a coffin,'' said a mother of three.
   The number of East German refugees in Bonn's mission in Warsaw
was reported to have reached 400.
   After holding inconclusive talks with his Czechoslovak
counterpart, West German Foreign Minister Hans Dietrich Genscher
was to confer with his East German colleague Oskar Fischer at the
United Nations in New York.
   The East German flood to the West occurred after Hungary opened
its borders and allowed up to 20,000 East Germans in that country
to flee into Austria. East Germany and Czechoslovakia are hard-line
Communist bloc nations, unlike Hungary which is embracing liberal
reforms and closer ties to the West.
</TEXT>
