<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrug 1stLd-Writethru a0478 09-27 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Toxic Drug Block AIDS Virus In Lab Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `The drug ...' to CLARIFY.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inexpensive drug used to treat
bronchitis appeared to block production of the AIDS virus in
test-tube experiments, researchers said.
   The researchers cautioned against human use of the drug until
the outcome of further study.
   The drug is not a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
scientists at Stanford University said Tuesday in announcing
results of lab tests.
   But they said it could slow down the virus' assault on the
immune system, as well as prolong and improve the patient's quality
of life when used with AZT or other drugs approved for treating
AIDS.
   Unlike Compound Q, a sometimes toxic protein distilled from a
Chinese cucumber root, dextran sulfate from Japan or high-priced
AZT, the drug under study at Stanford is readily available and
relatively cheap and safe.
   ``I am really optimistic about this,'' said Dr. Leonore
Herzenberg, a professor of genetics at Stanford, who worked on the
research with her husband, geneticist Dr. Leonard Herzenberg.
   ``Looking at the scientific evidence for what this drug does,
and the scientific evidence for how AIDS works, our guess is that
treatment with this drug may be quite good. But until we get it
tested in patients, we won't know if it will work.''
   The drug, N-acetylcysteine (NAC), is used for treating chronic
bronchitis and other lung ailments, and as an antidote to overdoses
of acetaminophen, the ingredient in Tylenol and other
over-the-counter pain relievers. The drug is made by the Zambon
Group in Italy and is available in liquid form in the United States
and in tablet form in Europe. Bristol-Myers Co. makes a vaporized
formula with the drug called Mucomist.
   Mrs. Herzenberg warned that AIDS patients should not begin
taking the drug in any form before further experiments show whether
the drug works on AIDS in humans.
   ``We're moving as quickly as possible and we are now talking
with physicians about doing clinical tests,'' she said.
   Dr. Mervyn Silverman, president of the American Foundation for
AIDS Research, said the experiments sounded promising, but he also
urged caution.
   ``While I think this holds promise, we have to have ... tests on
humans before we know how effective it will be,'' Silverman said.
   NAC blocks the triggering of AIDS virus production by increasing
glutathione levels in blood cells affected by the virus, the
Herzenbergs said. Glutathione eliminates potentially harmful
oxidizing agents and is essential for energy generation and other
cell functions.
   The Herzenbergs are scheduled to report preliminary results of
the research today at an international conference exploring
research strategies on AIDS in Geneva.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
