<FIRST>r a PM-OperationRescue 1stLd-Writethru a0483 09-27 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Operation Rescue, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortionists Take Their Case to Prosecutor's House</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with trial resuming; PICKS UP 6th
graf pvs, `I will ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion foes demonstrated at the home of a city
solicitor, who called the protest an intimidation ploy that would
not stop him from prosecuting Operation Rescue's leader on
trespassing charges.
   About 15 people gathered Tuesday night outside the home of Chief
Assistant Solicitor General Robert Lee O'Brien Jr. Police reported
no arrests.
   ``People need to know he's protecting child killers,'' said one
demonstrator, Archie Bradley of Delaware.
   Randall Terry's trial resumed as scheduled this morning, and the
prosecutor was back in court as expected.
   ``This is obviously a definite attempt to influence the way I
handle the case, and it's not going to happen,'' O'Brien said
Tuesday. ``It kind of makes me a little angry that they would come
to my private residence and do this type of thing.
   ``I will not let it interfere with my job,'' he said. ``It's not
appropriate for them to try to intimidate a prosecutor who's trying
to do his job.''
   Tuesday night's demonstration followed the start of Terry's
trial, which stems from protests outside abortion clinics during
the 1988 Democratic National Convention.
   O'Brien objected in court when Terry told jurors that the
demonstrations were held last year to save children from abortion.
   Judge John Bruner ruled that Terry could not use justification
as a defense in his trial on criminal trespass and unlawful
assembly charges.
   Terry, who is representing himself, is among about 60
anti-abortion demonstrators scheduled for trial. Only a few are
expected to be tried in the next few weeks.
   If convicted, Terry could be sentenced to a one year in jail and
fined $1,000 on each misdemeanor charge.
   Terry told jurors that while prosecutors made it seem ``like
this is a fairly open and shut case ... I mean to show you ... we
had no intention to break the law. Our only intention was to save
children from abortion.''
   O'Brien objected, saying abortion was not the issue. With the
jury absent, he said justification is a proper defense only when a
person believes he must use force or threat to defend himself
against the use of force by another.
   ``He's trying to present his view that abortion is not right ...
(but) in this state, abortion is legal,'' the prosecutor said.
   Terry countered, ``I'm not talking about a justification defense
(but) what was in my mind.''
   Operation Rescue, based in Binghamton, N.Y., organized
anti-abortion demonstrations around the country.
   More than 1,200 arrests were made at about 20 protests at
Atlanta-area abortion clinics during the summer and fall of 1988.
</TEXT>
