<FIRST>r i PM-PuertoRico-Hugo 2ndLd-Writethru   09-27 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico-Hugo, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0427,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Back on in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with water restored, officials correcting
that child died of salmonella. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Water began flowing to the homes of
thousands of San Juan residents today for the first time since
Hurricane Hugo slammed into the island nine days ago.
   Officials had expressed concern that the prolonged shortage was
posing a serious health hazard.
   The Water and Sewer Authority said 90 percent of the homes in
the city of San Juan, where one-third of Puerto Rico's 3.3 million
people live, were receiving running water today. Spokeswoman
Lilliana Rivera said most of the rest of the island also had water.
   In a school shelter in the town of Yabucoa in eastern Puerto
Rico, health officials said a month-old girl died Sunday of
salmonella. At first it was believed the baby had died of
meningitis and 40 hurricane victims housed in the same school were
given antibiotics to ward off the contagious illness.
   Health officials were concerned disease might spread from
insects and rats feeding on the piles of garbage, which contain
rotting meats, vegetables and fruits that spoiled from lack of
refrigeration in the hurricane aftermath.
   Worst hit was the San Juan metropolitan area, home to more than
half of the island's population. Two-thirds were without water
after five motors at the Carraizo Dam were damaged by Hugo's 140
mph winds.
   Health officials, concerned about the spread of disease,
launched a campaign giving residents tips on how to survive the
shortage. Radio and television broadcasts periodically remind
people to boil their drinking water.
   ``The major problem is the lack of water,'' said Patricia
Perdue, a nurse with the Red Cross. ``That and the fact that trash
is not being picked up and people can't maintain proper hygiene.''
   She said the Red Cross and other health agencies were launching
a hygiene ``educational campaign'' at 120 shelters housing
thousands of hurricane victims.
   To bathe, people have dipped into swimming pools, dived into the
ocean and kneeled beside fire hydrants. They have caught rain water
in buckets or stood for hours behind National Guard and water tank
trucks to fill plastic containers.
   Two U.S. Navy destroyers distributed 20,000 gallons of fresh
water.
   At the ritzy El San Juan hotel and Condado Plaza Hotel &amp; Casino,
owners brought in five 10,000 gallon water trucks.
   ``When you don't have water, you can't wash your hands, which is
the best way to prevent disease. So just from there, the system
breaks up,'' said Jim Maze, a nurse with the Red Cross Disasters
Health Service.
   The water shortage provoked many complaints about the bathroom
facilities at the Luiz Munoz Marin International Airport.
   ``They are so filthy, maintenance personnel must make a special
effort to get near enough to clean them,'' read an editorial
Tuesday in The San Juan Star. ``Tourists and residents are aghast.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
