<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0545 09-27 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0545,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barco Signs Guerrilla Pact, Says Noose Closing on Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE that there is no date for turning
in weapons. Pickup 4th pvs, `There was...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and Colombia's most
notorious leftist guerrilla group have signed a peace accord, but
there will be no peace for the nation's cocaine cartels, President
Virgilio Barco said.
   Barco was to travel to the United States today to talk with
President Bush about Colombia's war against the drug traffickers.
   He announced the treaty late Tuesday night in a surprise
nationwide television and radio address, and said it calls for
pardons for members of the May 10 guerrilla movement and for them
to give up their weapons. The rebels also would be allowed to form
a political party under the agreement, reached after six months of
negotiations, Barco said.
   A deadline for the guerrillas to turn in their weapons will
presumably be set when the congress approves an amnesty. Colombia's
slow moving congress probably will not decide on that until at
least December.
   There was no immediate comment from M-19, one of six rebel
groups in Colombia. The Colombian congress must approve the accord.
   The guerrillas are urging the government to end its war against
the cocaine cartels, to pardon drug traffickers and to refuse to
extradite them to the United States.
   A statement by M-19 published in a full-page advertisement
Tuesday in El Tiempo, Colombia's largest newspaper, also urged
immediate negotiations between the government and drug barons.
   But bombings apparently by drug traffickers continued Tuesday,
and Barco said his government will press its 5-week-old crackdown
war on the cartels.
   One bomb exploded at a supermarket and seriously injured five
people and the other went off in the evening at a Catholic high
school. The school was closed, and there were no injuries there,
police said.
   Since the government crackdown began, there have been 112
bombings. Police say the bombs have killed eight people and wounded
137.
   Drug traffickers ``are trying to destroy the most precious thing
that Colombians have _ their democracy,'' Barco said in the speech.
   He said that since he declared war on the traffickers, security
forces have sezied 1,056 properties from the cocaine lords along
with 525 vehicles, 74 boats and 375 airplanes.
   More than 10,800 people have been arrested, and 535 of them have
been charged with crimes that link them to drug traffickers, Barco
said.
   The government claims that the drug lords and an estimated
10,000 guerrillas from six groups work together, with the cocaine
cartels providing money to the insurgents in exchange for armed
protection.
   M-19, believed to have about 2,000 members, is the only
guerrilla group negotiating with the government.
   M-19, or May 19, was formed in 1970 by dissidents who claimed a
presidential election that year was fraudulent.
   The group has waged a campaign of assassinations, kidnappings,
bombings and armed raids, but its actions in recent months have
been overshadowed by the battle between the government and drug
barons.
   In 1985, M-19 guerrillas seized the Palace of Justice in Bogota
and 95 people were killed during the army assault to recapture the
building.
   Barco said British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher had approved
an aid package for Colombia to help fight drug traffickers and that
aid also was coming from West Germany, France and Argentina. He did
not give details.
   The United States has approved $65 million in aid, and much of
it already has arrived in Colombia.
   Barco said he will appeal for help from more countries in an
address Friday before the United Nations General Assembly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
