<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Crack     09-27 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Crack,1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alleged Source of TV Drugs Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to ADD that teen was jailed after being charged. Picks
up 2nd graf pvs `Keith Jackson ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington teen-ager is being held without
bond after being charged with selling undercover agents the crack
cocaine that President Bush used as a prop on national television.
   Keith Jackson, 18, is a student at the District of Columbia's
Spingarn High School, which was honored as ``drug free'' in a White
House ceremony in June. He was arrested Monday after being indicted
earlier in the day on five drug-related counts.
   One alleged sale took place Sept. 1 in Lafayette Park across the
street from the White House, where Jackson was allegedly lured by
agents at the direction of White House officials.
   Bush displayed the clear plastic bag of crack in a Sept. 5
speech to demonstrate the extent of the drug problem in the
nation's capital, although he did not say that the alleged dealer
had been drawn to the park by agents. Lafayette Park is not the
site of routine drug sales.
   Bush last week defended the direction White House image-makers
gave the DEA, saying, ``The man went out there and sold drugs in
front of the White House ... I can't feel sorry for this fellow.
   Jackson's court-appointed lawyer, Alan Warner, said the alleged
sale across from the White House ``definitely puts a twist on this
case that you normally don't get.'' He did not discuss what defense
he might use.
   U.S. Magistrate Patrick Attridge ordered Jackson, who has no
criminal record, held without bond.
</TEXT>
