<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-27 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Attack Kills One, Wounds Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said 11 rockets slammed
into the western part of the capital Wednesday, killing one person
and wounding four.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said the rockets
hit near the government flour silos, where 50,000 tons of flour are
stored for winter. The silos are a frequent target of attacks by
U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas.
   Amani said the casualties occurred at a house hit by a rocket
fired from the surrounding hills.
   Kabul has come under almost daily rocket attacks since late
June. More than 350 people have been killed and 800 injured.
   The government accuses the guerrillas of firing the rockets at
random to spread panic and force residents to flee to
rebel-controlled areas.
   The Pakistani-based guerrillas say the government fires at its
own civilians.
   Guerrillas have been fighting 11 years to oust the communist
government.
</TEXT>
