<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Hugo 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 09-27 0952</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0977</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relief Workers Begin Handing Out Supplies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with details on distribution program,
Red Cross centers opened. PICKS UP 16th graf pvs, `In North ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CHT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relief workers today began handing out
bottled water, clothing, plywood, roofing nails and disposable
diapers to the tens of thousands left homeless in hurricane-ravaged
South Carolina.
   ``I'm looking for anything I can get _ food, clothes,
everything,'' said Nicole Jeremiah, whose first-floor apartment was
flooded when a tree fell on the building. She and her four children
are living in a motel.
   ``This is quite devastating. I'm heartbroken. It'll take a while
to pick up all the pieces,'' she added. A baby carriage at her side
was filled with clothes and bread, pork and beans, soup and baby
food.
   Ms. Jeremiah was given the supplies at The Citadel Mall, one of
12 points set up by the city to distribute goods donated by
individuals and companies such as Wal-Mart and Safeway after Mayor
Joseph P. Riley Jr. set up a hotline Monday and pleaded for aid.
   ``The interest and concern and compassion and generosity of the
citizens of our country is extraordinary,'' he said.
   The goods were loaded on tractor-trailers from a warehouse and
taken to distribution centers today. Officials expected to empty 20
to 30 trucks a day across the city.
   About 300,000 residences or buildings remained without power
throughout South Carolina. An estimated 50,000 of Charleston's
65,000 residents were still out of their homes, Riley said.
   Today he urged federal officials to cut red tape to get aid to
the state. He said the state's problems included difficulty in
obtaining generators.
   As of today, the Red Cross had opened 32 relief centers in three
South Carolina counties to distribute food and clothing and provide
shelter, with more centers planned in other counties.
   ``We need money and we need people,'' said David Giroux, a
spokesman for the Red Cross. ``This is a Level 5 disaster _ they
don't get any bigger than this.''
   College football fans at six Southern universities are being
asked to bring canned goods to games Saturday to help storm victims.
   ``It is my hope that we can combine two of the South's finest
traditions _ college football and a desire to help our fellow
man,'' said Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   In Cincinnati, the Procter &amp; Gamble Co. said it was sending 1.5
million disposable plastic diapers to South Carolina and Puerto
Rico through the Red Cross and the Salvation Army.
   Most of the national attention centered on this historic port
city, which took a direct hit from the storm Thursday, and
officials in outlying areas expressed concern that relief supplies
were not flowing to their communities.
   ``People are hungry. We are in desperate need of a whole lot of
help,'' said the Rev. Frank Maddox of Sumter.
   In North Carolina, preliminary damage estimates Tuesday stood at
$237 million for 23 counties, but state officials expected the
final total to be close to $500 million. In Charlotte, 155,000
customers were without power.
   Hugo smashed into South Carolina with 135 mph winds. At least 33
people were killed in the Caribbean; the mainland death toll rose
to 29 with a report today of a Kingstree, S.C., man who touched a
downed power line Monday night and was electrocuted.
   Residents of the barrier islands northeast of Charleston
continued to return to their homes by boat Tuesday, while the Army
Corps of Engineers began work on a temporary pontoon bridge to link
devastated Isle of Palms and Sullivan's Island to the mainland
again. The coastal resort of Garden City remained closed and
guarded by troops against looters.
   Power was extended to additional areas of the Charleston
historic district and traffic lights winked to life.
   However, schools remain closed indefinitely, a nighttime curfew
remained in effect and National Guardsmen continue to patrol the
streets.
   Charleston Harbor reopened to limited ship traffic Tuesday and
Navy ships, which rode out the storm off the coast, returned to
harbor.
   About 650 Department of Defense personnel were being sent to
assist in the relief effort, while the Mormon Church shipped water,
food, cooking stoves, power generators, propane fuel and tools.
   Ralston Purina Co. said it is sending three tons of dog food and
one ton of cat food from Atlanta to Charleston to replenish the
Humane Society's lost supply.
   President Bush on Tuesday expanded a disaster declaration to
five more South Carolina counties, bringing to 12 the number
eligible for federal money.
   Estimates of crop losses increased to $90 million, and were
expected to climb as more of the state's 5.3 million acres of
cropland is surveyed. Damage to South Carolina's forests was placed
at $1 billion, state officials said.
   The storm also has taken a toll on the $30 million a year
shrimping industry.
   Hugo struck in the middle of the May-to-November shrimping
season, wiping out shrimp beds and damaging related businesses.
   ``The biggest thing is people who buy the shrimp _ the packing
houses _ they're all wiped out. They're destroyed,'' said Jimmy
Scott, 45, a shrimper for the past 21 years. ``By the time they get
it built back, the season is over.''
   More trouble may be coming.
   High tides that come every 10 years when the moon reaches one of
its closest points to the Earth threaten more damage in mid-October
and mid-November.
   ``It's especially dangerous because an awful lot of habitable
structures are just barely sound. With a 7-foot tide, we could have
further beach erosion, further damage to structures,'' said Gered
Lennon, a geologist for the South Carolina Coastal Council.
</TEXT>
