<FIRST>u a PM-Thornburgh-Drugs     09-27 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Drugs,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funds From Drug Seizures to Be Used to Build Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh today
said $229 million seized from drug traffickers and organized crime
groups will be used to build more than 3,000 new federal prison
cells.
   The money, ordered transferred from the Justice Department's
Asset Forfeiture Fund to the Federal Bureau of Prisons, is a
downpayment on President Bush's proposed $1.5 billion in prison
construction, Thornburgh told an annual gathering of federal
prosecutors.
   ``This is one of the nicer ironies of our times,'' Thornburgh
said. ``We're now taking that money and turning it against those
criminals from whom it was so justly taken. Talk about poetic
justice _ this is that.''
   Since October 1988, agencies within the Justice Department
seized property valued at more than $1 billion. More than $500
million in forfeited and liquidated criminal property has been
deposited into the Asset Forfeiture Fund, Thornburgh said.
   About $150 million of that seized money has been shared with
local law enforcement agencies.
   ``It's, I think, satisfying to think that it's now possible for
a drug dealer to serve time in a forfeiture-financed prison after
being arrested by agents driving a forfeiture-provided automobile
while working in a forfeiture-funded sting operation,'' the
attorney general said to rousing applause from about 150 people.
   The Asset Forfeiture Fund has increased in yearly receipts from
$27.2 million in 1985 to more than $500 million so far this year,
according to Justice Department statistics.
   Thornburgh also said he will try to make the program more
efficient by creating an executive office for asset forfeiture in
the deputy attorney general's office to oversee the fund.
   The attorney general addressed the group under heavy security by
the FBI and U.S. marshals because of possible threats from
Colombian drug lords, authorities said.
</TEXT>
