<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-FHAInsurance     09-27 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FHA Insurance,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>About $4 Billion Needed to Rescue FHA Fund, Auditor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress probably will need to come up with
about $4 billion over the next few years to rescue the fund that
has helped millions of Americans buy houses with FHA loans, the
government's chief auditor said today.
   Charles A. Bowsher, head of the General Accounting Office, told
a Senate panel the taxpayer money will be needed because the
Federal Housing Administration sustained a $4.2 billion loss in
1988 that plunged the FHA insurance fund $2.9 billion into the red.
That is the first time the agency has been in the hole.
   The outgoing Reagan administration previously reported losses of
more than $800 million in the FHA fund in 1988, less than
one-fourth the amount GAO auditors calculated.
   Bowsher said further losses must be anticipated in the next few
years as homeowners who have taken out government-backed loans
recently in economically depressed regions of the country find
themselves unable to keep up their payments.
   The current losses, the GAO chief said, stem from a combination
of hard economic times in what he called ``oil patch'' states and
mismanagement at the Department of Housing and Urban Development,
which administers the FHA.
   ``Basic management weaknesses must be corrected if future losses
are to be brought under control,'' Bowsher said in a report to the
Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs housing subcommittee.
   In testimony accompanying the report, Bowsher told the panel he
believes new HUD management is moving to correct past problems,
which he blamed partially on inadequate congressional oversight.
   ``I don't think we're in a free fall,'' Bowsher said. ``What we
have here is a program in trouble.''
   He said his audit staff had received full cooperation from HUD
Assistant Secretary C. Austin Fitts, who appeared with him at the
subcommittee hearing.
   ``We acknowledge that FHA has incurred substantial losses,'' she
said. ``The bad news is out on the table. We believe the problems
are manageable and fixable.''
   She asked in advance for congressional support for some reforms
she said HUD Secretary Jack Kemp will be outlining soon for housing
programs and introduced two top assistants from Wall Street she
said she has recruited to help shore up management of the agency's
FHA programs.
   ``We can't wring our hands about the past,'' said Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., the subcommittee chairman.
   He complimented Ms. Fitts for her initial efforts and said, ``We
will pursue any legislative remedies that are necessary to make FHA
a strong and responsive institution that is able to serve the
housing needs of future generations in all parts of this country as
magnificently as it served the needs of the American people years
ago.''
   Bowsher outlined the basic problems with FHA for the same
subcommittee in August, but did not have specific loss figures in
that preliminary report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
