<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Giannini     09-27 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Giannini,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventor and Physicist Dead at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gabriel Maria Giannini, a
physicist, aerospace equipment manufacturer and inventor, has died
following a stroke. He was 83.
   He died Sept. 20 at Eisenhower Medical Clinic in this resort
city near Palm Springs.
   Giannini was born in Rome and received a doctorate in physics
from the University of Rome in 1929. He studied there with Enrico
Fermi when Fermi was working with nuclear fission in hopes of using
it a source of radium for cancer treatment.
   In 1931 Giannini came to the United States and worked as an
acoustical engineer. He later founded his own aircraft and missile
guidance manufacturing company, Giannini Controls Corp.
   Giannini left the company in 1961 to pursue other interests.
   He held more than 50 U.S. patents.
   He is survived by his wife, Olga, a son, two daughters, a
stepson and a stepdaughter, five grandchildren and two
great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
