<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Says She's Dressed For Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with morning remarks; PICKS UP
5th graf pvs, `During testimony ...'; DELETES last three grafs to CONFORM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor arrived at her
cop-slapping trial today in a black pantsuit and said she was
dressed for jail.
   Defense attorney William Graysen and Deputy District Attorney
Elden Fox were expected to give closing arguments today at the
3-week-old misdemeanor trial, which has cost taxpayers more than
$22,000.
   ``I don't know what's going to happen. I might go to jail, so
I'm dressed for it,'' the Hungarian-born actress told reporters.
   Miss Gabor could receive up to 18 months in jail if convicted of
misdemeanor battery on a police officer, disobeying an officer's
orders, driving with an expired license and having an open
container of alcohol in her car.
   She is accused of slapping a motorcyle cop who had pulled over
her Rolls-Royce on June 14. She said she hit Officer Paul Kramer in
self-defense because he forcibly removed her from the car.
   On Tuesday, she twice stalked out of the courtroom and branded
her accusers as liars.
   ``I can't take this,'' she muttered as she walked out the first
time Tuesday when Officer Scott Thompson was called to the stand
for rebuttal testimony. She left again when a longhaired young man
said he admired Kramer.
   During testimony, 18-year-old Amir Eslaminia said he has had his
share of run-ins with Kramer. But he spoke glowingly of the officer
and described Miss Gabor's earlier testimony as false.
   ``I really thought it to be ... all made up,'' the pony-tailed
teen-ager said.
   During a break outside court, Miss Gabor explained her
departures.
   ``Both of them lied about me,'' she said. ``I tell you why I
left when the little punk with a hairdo like a girl and the earring
said she lies. ... Who needs that?''
   At that point Eslaminia shouted over the heads of reporters,
``Is that why you're causing this ruckus, so you can get more TV
for yourself?''
   Eslaminia was one of three prosecution character witnesses.
   Alice Joseph of Beverly Hills testified that Kramer was kind to
her and her 3-year-old daughter when they stopped to chat with him.
   Mateo Guerrero, ticketed by Kramer in 1985 for jaywalking, said
the officer was one of the nicest policemen he had ever met.
   ``I was humbled, but at the same time I felt good because he was
such a nice guy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
