<HEAD>Juror Recognizes Defendant She Helped Convict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistrial was declared when a juror
realized she already had helped convict the defendant in an earlier
trial.
   ``I just had a funny feeling that I knew him from somewhere,''
Joyce Creekmore said Tuesday.
   ``After seven years, you have a tendency to kind of forget
somebody,'' she said. ``I think I recognized the look in his eyes
more than anything else.''
   James P. Johnson's trial opened Monday with two witnesses
testifying that residents of an apartment house tackled him June 23
after he tried to attack a resident.
   Johnson, 38, who acted as his own lawyer, is charged with
aggravated burglary and aggravated battery.
   His trial ended abruptly Tuesday when Ms. Creekmore told
officials that a jury she had been on in 1982 convicted Johnson of
attempted robbery.
   Court officials dug out the old records and learned that Ms.
Creekmore's memory was accurate. District Judge Paul Clark
rescheduled the case.
   Johnson was sentenced to nine to 30 years in prison after his
first trial but had been paroled.
