<FIRST>u a PM-ColumbiaPictures 2ndLd-Writethru a0573 09-27 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia Pictures, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0573,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Columbia Agrees to Buyout By Sony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with deal valued at $3.4 billion
sted $3 billion, Columbia confirmation, two executives planning to resign;
PICKS UP 10th graf pvs, `Columbia owns ...'; DELETES last two grafs to
conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. said today it has agreed to acquire
Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc., the huge movie and TV
production company, in a cash deal valued at $3.4 billion.
   Sony's U.S. subsidiary, Sony USA Inc., said a tender offer of
$27 a share had been approved by Columbia's board of directors
subject to certain conditions, but that it expected to complete the
acquisition by early November.
   Coca-Cola Co., Columbia's largest shareholder at 49 percent,
said it had signed an option agreement to tender its stake, subject
to ratification by the Coca-Cola board, which was expected at a
meeting next Monday.
   The deal had been widely rumored since Monday, when Columbia
disclosed it was in buyout talks with a third party that it refused
to identify.
   The buyout of Columbia, which began as a tiny studio in 1920 and
grew into a major Hollywood force, is the latest chapter in a wave
of consolidation that has swept through the entertainment industry.
   Columbia's Chairman, Donald R. Keough, said Sony was ``an ideal
buyer.''
   ``It has all the right characteristics and very importantly has
the ability to take the company to its next important step,'' he
said.
   Michael Schulhof, vice chairman of Sony Corp. of America, said
the purchase of a major film studio ``extends Sony's long-term
strategy of building a total entertainment business around the
synergy of audio and video hardware and software.''
   He said the electronics giant will place day-to-day operation
operation of Columbia in U.S. hands and ``keep it as independent as
possible as a full-fledged member of the U.S. film industry.''
   Columbia said Victor Kaufman, its president and chief executive,
and Lew Korman, chief operating officer, will resign once the deal
is completed.
   There were published reports today that Peter Guber was expected
to replace Kaufman. Guber, who co-produced ``Batman,'' ``Rainman''
and ``Flashdance,'' is considered one of Hollywood's top producers.
   Columbia owns two major film studios, Columbia Pictures and
Tri-Star Pictures, but its box-office results have been
disappointing in recent years. Among its recent releases are
``Ghostbusters II,'' ``The Karate Kid Part III'' and ``Casualties
of War.''
   It has been a more impressive force on television, where it has
produced or distributed 11 prime-time series, including five new
shows. Among its productions are ``Who's the Boss'' and ``Designing
Women.''
   Columbia also about 820 movie screens in 220 locations and a
library of more than 2,700 films and 23,000 TV episodes.
   In other media deals, MGM-UA accepted a $1.5 billion buyout
offer earlier this month from the Qintex Group of Australia.
   Time Warner Inc. is on the verge of completing its acquisition
of Warner Communications Inc., which owns the Warner Bros. movie
studio and the TV production company Lorimar.
   The giant media company News Corp. bought 20th Century Fox three
years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
