<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LoanFraud     09-27 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loan Fraud,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrift, Former Officials Face Student Loan Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thrift and two former executives have been
indicted on charges of faking defaults on $35 million worth of
federally guaranteed student loans to get reimbursed by the
government, prosecutors said today.
   The U.S. Department of Education paid Florida Federal Savings
Bank about half the money before the thrift was cut off, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Gregory Kehoe.
   ``The students never had an opportunity to repay the loans,'' he
said. ``There's no evidence the claims or proper documents were
ever sent to them.''
   The indictment alleges false claims for 17,000 students totaling
$35 million were submitted to the Education Department in 1986 and
1987.
   Indicted with the St. Petersburg thrift on conspiracy, theft and
fraud charges were former assistant vice presidents Robert O.
Harmas, 42, of Noblesville, and James J. LaMantia, 59, of Largo.
   They were arranging their surrender today.
   The federal student loan program makes low-interest college
loans. Banks and thrifts lend their own funds, and the government
or a guarantee agency insures them against default by students.
   At the time of the allegedly faked defaults, Florida Federal,
formerly Florida Federal Savings and Loan Association, was the
second-largest thrift in the Southeast and the third-largest
provider of guaranteed student loans in the country.
</TEXT>
