<FIRST>r a PM-LoanAgencyTrial     09-27 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loan Agency Trial,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Student Loan Agency Cleared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Pennsylvania's student loan
agency was acquitted today of taking kickbacks from a company
awarded a contract to collect delinquent loans. His chief aide was
found guilty on eight charges.
   Kenneth R. Reeher, executive director of the Pennsylvania Higher
Education Assistance Agency, was cleared on all counts. Harry P.
Casoni, his former aide, was found guilty of charges including
conspiracy, bribery and mail fraud.
   Acting U.S. Attorney James West said Casoni faces up to 40 years
in jail and $2 million in fines.
   Reeher, 67, had been on a leave of absence without pay. He said
he has no intention of retiring. ``We're very, very elated,''
Reeher said. ``We always had faith it would work out. ... It's been
two difficult years.''
   Casoni's attorney, Arthur Goldberg, said Casoni will appeal.
   The jury began deliberating Monday.
   In 1986, Reeher awarded a $1.76 million contract to Gabler
Educational Management Services of Libertyville, Ill., to collect
defaulted loans.
   In return, prosecutors said, he demanded 50 percent ownership of
the company for himself and Casoni and half the fees PHEAA paid to
Gabler, and negotiated a $130,000-a-year job for Casoni.
   Casoni resigned from PHEAA and took the job, giving Reeher money
from his paychecks along with air conditioners and a van,
prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
