<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1523EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CrafoordPrize     09-27 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crafoord Prize,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Van Allen Receives Prize from Swedish King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHAN NASSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran U.S. space researcher James A.
Van Allen received the prestigious Crafoord Prize from Swedish King
Carl XVI Gustaf on Wednesday for his pioneering exploration of
space.
   Sweden's Royal Academy of Sciences, which also awards the Nobel
science prizes, in particular cited Van Allen's discovery in 1958
of the earth's high-energy radiation belts that were named after
him.
   Van Allen, 74, of the University of Iowa, developed new rockets
and space instruments used in launching the first U.S. satellites
and in discovering the magnetic fields shrouding other planets, the
academy said.
   Van Allen, who brought 15 family members, including his five
children and five grandchildren to Stockholm, said receiving the
Crafoord Prize was the biggest thrill of his long scientific career.
   ``Absolutely, there's no doubt about it,'' Van Allen said.
``It's the highest award one can possibly get in this field.''
   ``The biggest surprise was the selection of this field as
subject matter for this award,'' said Van Allen, who received the
prize from the king at a ceremony in the Royal Academy of Sciences
building.
   Van Allen said he had planned to come to Stockholm anyway,
having been invited to a symposium before the prize was announced
and awarded. About 75 of the world's leading space scientists and
officials from several big space projects will participate in the
Sept. 28-29 symposium at the Royal Academy of Sciences.
   The Crafoord Prize has been awarded since 1982 to supplement the
Nobel sciences, which were limited under Alfred Nobel's will to
chemistry, physics and medicine. Americans have won or shared the
prestigious Crafoord Prize every year since the inauguration.
   The prize was worth $252,000 this year.
   Van Allen is the so-called ``principal investigator'' on the
Pioneer 1 and 11 missions, both of which are continuing and in
which he is actively working. He is also an interdisciplinary
scientist on the forthcoming Galileo mission to Jupiter.
   Van Allen was cited for providing the first instruments ever
carried to another planet, those aboard the 1963 mission to Venus
by Mariner II.
   His instruments also were on the Pioneer space probes to
Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune, measuring the magnetic fields
around those planets that trap belts of particles similar to those
around the earth.
   His 1958 discovery of what were later named the Van Allen Belts
disclosed the existence of broad bands of highly energetic
particles surrounding the earth.
   Born in Mount Pleasant, Iowa, Van Allen studied at the
University of Iowa, where he returned in the 1960s to establish the
leading space science institute in the United States, producing
many of today's leaders in space research.
   In 1981, Van Allen was elected to the Royal Swedish Academy of
Sciences as one of its 150 foreign members. The Academy has 360
Swedish members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
