<FIRST>r a AM-ConfederateFlag     09-27 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Confederate Flag,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Fans Can Wave Confederate Flag _ But Not as School Symbol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forrest Hill High School won't stop anyone
from waving Confederate battle flags at school events, but the
school board is adopting another flag as the official one.
   On Tuesday, the Jackson School Board voted 2-1 to approve a plan
recommended by a committee of parents, students and teachers to
select a new flag, which will be unveiled before the Oct. 19
football game.
   Many students and parents had opposed a plan to stop using the
Confederate flag as the school flag after some said they found it
racially offensive.
   About 200 parents and students packed Tuesday's meeting room and
spilled outside, where members of the Jackson Association of
Concerned Parents paraded and waved large Rebel flags.
   Earlier this month, Forest Hill officials notified students that
the Rebel flag wouldn't be allowed on campus or at any school
event. When several students carried flags to an on-campus football
game, administrators confiscated them and made the students leave.
   That won't be done in the future, however.
   ``We're not going to be collecting any more flags because that's
interfering with somebody's constitutional right, but we're going
to discourage students from waving it,'' Deputy Superintendent Dan
Merritt said.
   ``The Jackson School Board should be commended for no longer
remaining thunderingly silent on the issue of the Confederate
flag,'' said state Rep. Aaron Henry of Clarksdale, state president
of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
``To those of you who wave the flag, you're doing a good job of
causing a negative feeling within the black community.''
</TEXT>
