<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1509EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-KidnapThreat     09-27 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Kidnap Threat,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Not Deterred by Threats; Security Increased for Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Wednesday that he won't be
``deterred by rumors'' that Colombian drug lords have made threats
against his five children, but he confirmed that security had been
increased for his family.
   ``I have confidence in the Secret Service and their ability to
do their job,'' Bush told a group of reporters in the Oval Office.
   The president was skeptical of a published report that drug
lords had threatened to kidnap one of his children if U.S. and
Colombian governments don't grant them amnesty. Bush has pledged an
all-out war against Colombian drug traffickers.
   The story, in Wednesday's editions of New York Newsday, quoted
unidentified Washington intelligence sources.
   However, Bush said intelligence officials never mentioned such a
threat to him, ``and I have a feeling that that matter is of enough
interest to me that it would have been brought to my attention.''
   ``I don't mean to be complacent, but I have confidence in our
intelligence community,'' Bush said.
   Although heightened security had been noticed recently around
Bush's family, it was the first time anyone in the government had
confirmed it publicly.
   There had been earlier reports of possible threats by Colombian
drug figures against the president's family and U.S. officials.
That icluded congressional testimony earlier this month from a
former drug dealer who suggested hit squads already might be in
this country.
   ``To the degree security has been stepped up in accordance with
the law and the Bush kids, it is not because of a specific, hard
piece of intelligence, hard threat. I'm confident of that,'' Bush
said.
   ``So, I don't live in fear of anything like this. ... I can't do
my job if I get deterred by rumors,'' he said.
   Newsday quoted the intelligence sources as saying they believed
the most vulnerable to a kidnapping was Bush's youngest child,
Dorothy LeBlond, 30, a Portland, Maine, businesswoman.
   The Bushes also have four sons: George, John, Neil and Marvin.
   The sources told the newspaper the kidnap threat also applied to
top U.S. officials involved in anti-drug efforts.
   Secret Service spokesman Richard Abrams would neither confirm
nor deny that protection for the Bush family was increased.
   ``Security is always tight, as you know,'' Abrams said.
   Initially the Bush children had resisted extra security, but all
finally agreed to an increased Secret Service presence, Newsday
reported.
   Adding fuel to speculation of Colombian hit squads was the
arrest in New Brunswick, Canada, earlier this month of five men
with an arsenal of weapons, Venezuelan papers and links with
Colombian suspects in a drug-trafficking case.
   Canadian officials said there was a link between the arrested
men and a hearing for two Colombians suspected of cocaine
trafficking, although they denied that any U.S. or Canadian
official was in danger.
   However, the men were carrying maps of New Brunswick and
neighboring Maine, where Bush's daughter lives and where he has a
family vacation home in Kennebunkport.
   Police said several locations were highlighted on the maps, but
refused to say what they were.
</TEXT>
