<DOCNO> AP890927-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     09-27 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationwide Strike Against Austerity Measures Shuts Down Haiti</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Almost all businesses were closed
and public transportation was halted Wednesday in a nationwide
strike called to protest the military government's austerity
measures.
   The hugely successful 24-hour strike was called by 32 different
groups representing farmers, workers, opposition parties and
others. Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, the military ruler, had predicted
the strike would fail.
   Police offered free rides in government trucks but, unlike
during previous strikes, there were no long lines of residents
waiting for them.
   The normally crowded and bustling downtown sidewalks were empty
as all street vendors stayed home. The outdoor market also was
empty in the wealthy suburb of Petionville, which usually does not
heed strike calls.
   Almost all factories at the industrial park on the north side of
this city of 1 million were closed.
   The strike was called to protest last month's austerity
measures, which include an increase in tariffs on imports and a
lowering of the ceiling on taxable businesses to include those that
earn as little as $25,000 a year. Other measures included a price
hike for some staple foods.
   Avril's government said the measures would allow Haiti, one of
the world's poorest nations, to qualify for aid from several
lending institutions, including a $26.5 million loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
   The strike was one of the most successful since dictator
Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in France in February 1986.
Unions as well as management appeared to back it. In previous
strikes, factory owners kept plants open for any employee who
wanted to work.
   ``For the first time since (Duvalier's departure) everybody has
unanimously rejected the socio-economic policy of the government,''
opposition leader Hubert De Ronceray told The Associated Press.
   The strike shut down all provincial towns, though in the north
coast city of Cap Haitien a few businesses opened, radio stations
said.
   ``The government has decreed tax measures in an underhanded,
dictatorial way, harmful to the majority of the people,'' said
Jean-Claude Roy, head of the Union of Haitian Constitutionalists
party.
   The groups backing the strike included Haiti's biggest union,
the Autonomous Central of Haitian Workers; the communist party, the
center-leftist Congress of Democratic Movements party; and the
Papaye Peasants Movement, the largest farmers group in Haiti.
   The Chamber of Commerce and the Haitian Association of
Industrialists have strongly criticized the austerity measures,
saying they will cause a ``social explosion.'' Though they did not
formally back the strike, they appeared to tacitly support it since
virtually all businesses and factories were closed.
   Avril told The Associated Press on Monday the strike would fail.
He came to power in a soldiers' coup in September 1988, ousting Lt.
Gen. Henri Namphy, who assumed power when Duvalier left.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
