<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1543EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Ravenel     09-27 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Ravenel,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Who Rode Out Hugo Said House Vibrated Like It Was Electrified</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Arthur Ravenel, whose
congressional district bore the brunt of Hurricane Hugo, said he
wore a life jacket and huddled in a back bedroom as he rode out the
storm in his harborfront home.
   ``It was like a 10-ton truck that ran into the side of the
house,'' Ravenel said from his Washington office Tuesday.
   The Republican lawmaker said the first part of the storm, which
packed 135 mph winds, wasn't too bad as he sat in his Mount
Pleasant home, across the harbor from Charleston. The area was not
under a mandatory evacuation order.
   ``Then the eye crossed,'' the congressman said. ``The pictures
started thumping off of the walls and crashing on the floor. I have
a tin roof and the roof started ripping off the house. The house
just started to vibrate like it contained electricity.
   ``I thought for a few minutes it was going to collapse,'' he
said. ``I retreated to the back of the house and put on a life
preserver.''
   Ravenel said he started to sit in the bathtub, but decided not
to when he saw that the bathroom window was too small to escape
through. He then stayed in a small bedroom in the back of the house.
   ``When I woke in the morning, I could not believe the
devastation,'' he said. Part of the roof of his cedar-shingled
house was missing, windows were blown out, his dock and small
fishing boat swept away, and ``big magnificent oaks were torn to
shreds.''
   The congressman said he's been working with his staff to help
constituents apply for assistance as soon as the Federal Emergency
Management Agency opens offices.
   About 300,000 residences or buildings remained without power
throughout South Carolina Wednesday. An estimated 50,000 of
Charleston's 65,000 residents were still out of their homes, Mayor
Joseph P. Riley Jr. said.
</TEXT>
