<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Drugs     09-27 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Shooting Galleries Help Explain Racial Difference in AIDS
Infection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of ghetto shooting galleries to share
needles may help explain why AIDS infections are more common among
black and Hispanic drug addicts than among white users, a study
concludes.
   The study, conducted in a methadone treatment program in New
York City, found that use of shooting galleries was the single most
important difference between those who got infected and those who
did not.
   Blacks and Hispanics were more likely than whites to go to
shooting galleries, places where drug abusers buy or rent needles
to inject drugs.
   ``It is clear that the social milieu in which drugs are
injected, not just the number of injections, is a powerful
predictor of the transmission of HIV,'' the AIDS virus, the
researchers wrote.
   The study was conducted by Dr. Ellie E. Schoenbaum and
colleagues at Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx. It was
published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine.
   Among the 452 people who took part in the study, the AIDS
infection rate was 49 percent in blacks, 42 percent in Hispanics
and 17 percent in non-Hispanic whites.
   While the blacks and Hispanics were more likely to frequent
shooting galleries, the whites were more apt to share needles with
friends and relatives.
   ``Shooting galleries are particularly well suited for the
transmission of HIV, since used needles are usually rented and then
reused by strangers or acquaintances,'' they wrote. ``In our study,
drug users who shared needles with strangers or acquaintances were
at high risk for HIV infection, whereas those who shared with close
friends or relatives were at lower risk.''
   Two-thirds of those took more than 25 percent of their drug
injections in shooting galleries were infected, compared with less
than one-third of those who never went there.
   The study also found that the risk of AIDS infection increased
by 24 percent with each sex partner who used intravenous drugs.
</TEXT>
