<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1546EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     09-27 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves New Political Freedom of Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Wednesday adopted a law
giving people the right to express opinions or advocate political
and social change, further expanding freedom of speech before
multiparty elections next year.
   The bill and a related amendment of the criminal procedure law
are part of a package of legislation designed to bring Hungary's
laws in line with moves toward a pluralistic system and with
international covenants on human rights.
   Under the penal code amendment, which takes effect immediately,
expressing one's private opinion or advocating political or social
change can no longer be considered crimes.
   Hungary's rapid liberalization has allowed a degree of free
expression that would have been difficult even one year ago.
Opposition leaders can have their say in the official media, and in
most cases people are permitted to demonstrate freely on a wide
range of issues, including such sensitive topics as the withdrawal
of Soviet troops.
   The draft legislation before Parliament must ``create the legal
preconditions for the transition leading to a new constitutional
order and eliminate obstacles in the path of the transformation''
to a multiparty system, Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar said.
   The penal code amendment was designed only to deal with urgent
matters, and a comprehensive penal code reform is under way,
Kulcsar said.
   Jozsef Debreczeni, one of four new members of Parliament who
belong to the opposition and received the majority vote in recent
by-elections _ the first in which Hungarians had a genuine choice
of candidates under communist rule _ said a reformed penal code is
needed immediately.
   Under the current legislation, he said, ``the new opposition
parties could be legally charged with conspiracy to overthrow the
established constitutional order.''
   Parliament is drafting a new constitution that is to ensure
separation of powers, guarantee human rights and remove all
references to a one-party state. But it is not to be formally
adopted until after elections, due by June, when the new Parliament
has begun work.
   Hungary's Communist Party has agreed to relinquish its leading
role and to enter into free elections with independent parties,
even pledging to go into opposition if it loses.
   On Tuesday, Parliament adopted new emigration and travel laws
that will allow unprecedented freedom of movement to Hungarians and
allow those who emigrated for personal, or even for political
reasons, to return home if they wish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
