<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Plane     09-27 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Plane,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC-9 Aborts Takeoff After Wind Shear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian DC-9 jetliner rolled off a
runway Wednesday after its takeoff was aborted because of suddenly
shifting winds, airline officials said. No serious injuries were
reported.
   The ATI airline jet, carrying 102 people, was taking off from
Palermo's Punta Raisi Airport for a flight to Milan when it
experienced the condition known as wind shear, said airport
director Ignazio Bonaccorsio.
   ``As a consequence, the airplane, while maintaining power, lost
speed and altitude, retouching the ground. At this point, action of
the flight crew was masterful. Even on a runway drenched with rain
they did not lose control of the aircraft,'' he said.
   Wind shear is a dangerous downdraft associated with severe
thunderstorms that has been known to cause aircraft accidents.
   Airline officials said a man with a heart condition was
hospitalized for observation as a precaution and a women was
treated for a cut caused by a beverage cart that broke loose during
the landing.
   The DC-9 Super 80 of the domestic airline was on a scheduled
flight to Milan with 98 passengers and a crew of four when the
pilot aborted the takeoff at about 3:30 p.m., an airline official
said.
   The company issued a statement that did not mention wind shear.
It said only that the pilot made the decision to abort because of a
sudden change in the weather and because he still had time to abort
the takeoff safely.
   The aircraft suffered no apparent damage when it touched down on
the runway and rolled off.
</TEXT>
