<SECOND>AM-Forest Payments,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Getting First Payments of $248 Million from Forest Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary payments totaling $248 million are
going out to states as their share of national forest sales
receipts collected this fiscal year, the Agriculture Department
said Wednesday.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said total state
shares for the fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, are expected to be
more than $331 million, up from $318 million last year.
   By law, 25 percent of the revenues collected by the agency for
the sale of timber and other uses of national forest resources must
be returned to the states where the forests are located. The states
are required to use the money for schools and roads.
   The 10 largest preliminary payments will go to Oregon, $118
million; California, $39 million; Washington, $33 million; Idaho,
$7 million; Arkansas, $6.2 million; Montana, $5.4 million; Arizona,
$5.3 million; Alaska, $3.2 million; Pennsylvania, $2.8 million; and
Mississippi, $2.6 million.
