<FIRST>b a PM-CanyonCrash 7thLd-Writethru a0669 09-27 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canyon Crash, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0669,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sightseeing Plane Crashes Near Grand Canyon; 10 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with officials saying 21 sted 19 aboard and
11 seriously injured. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSAYAN, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sightseeing plane crashed on a wooded
hill a half-mile from a runway at the Grand Canyon airport today,
killing at least 10 people and seriously injuring the 11 others
aboard, authorities said.
   The twin-engine Grand Canyon Airlines plane went down at 9:49
a.m. MST, said Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman Elly
Brekke. There were conflicting reports on whether the plane was
landing or taking off.
   Mitch Strohman, a reporter for Flagstaff radio station KAFF,
said the wreckage lay on a heavily wooded hill and did not catch
fire. The airport is five miles from the Grand Canyon.
   Sheriff's Capt. Sam Whitted said the 11 survivors were being
taken to hospitals.
   Ms. Brekke said the plane hit trees, flipped over and crashed
after veering on its landing approach. Elizabeth Seibold, owner of
Grand Canyon Airlines, said the plane was on a sightseeing flight
and was coming in for a landing.
   However, Lt. Jim Driscoll said the plane crashed on takeoff.
   ``We don't know if lost power or what. ... It started banking to
the east and then went down,'' he said. He said it hit a power line.
   The FAA spokeswoman said the National Transportation Safety
Board would send an investigation team.
   In 1986, a Grand Canyon Airlines plane collided with a
sightseeing helicopter inside the canyon, killing 25 people. In
1956, a TWA plane and a United aircraft collided over the canyon
and 128 were killed.
</TEXT>
