<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     09-27 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Dismiss Allegations of Blunders Before Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday
dismissed as ``pure speculation'' a British TV report alleging West
German investigators committed major blunders before the Pan Am
bombing over Scotland in December.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. current affairs program
``Panorama'' earlier this week said one blunder allegedly made by
the West Germans was the release of the suspected bomb maker two
months before the jet was blown up.
   ``This (report) is pure speculation,'' chief government
spokesman Hans Klein told reporters in Bonn.
   Another high-ranking government official said that nine months
after Pan Am Flight 103 blew up over Lockerbie, U.S., British and
West German investigators still have ``no clear knowledge'' about
who was responsible for the bombing.
   All 259 people aboard Flight 103 from Frankfurt to New York via
London were killed in the Dec. 21 attack, along with 11 people on
the ground in Lockerbie.
   Hans Neusel, the No. 2 official in the Interior Ministry,
repeated West German doubts that the bomb had been loaded onto the
flight in Frankfurt.
   There was no evidence on whether the bomb was placed aboard the
plane in Frankfurt or London and investigators remained in the dark
about the kind of detonator used, Neusel said.
   In an interview with Deutschlandfunk radio station, Neusel said
West German investigators have found no links between members of a
radical Palestinian group arrested in West Germany in October 1988
and the Pan Am bombing two months later.
   West German authorities arrested 16 suspected members of the
Syrian-backed Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, but quickly released 14 of them, citing a lack of evidence.
   Among those released was a Jordanian, Marwan Khreesat. The
``Panorama'' program said Khreesat is a known bomb maker and is
widely believed by British and U.S. investigators to have made the
Lockerbie bomb and several others.
   The program said Khreesat was in hiding in Jordan and that the
West Germans apparently released him because he was a double agent
who was also working for Jordanian intelligence.
   Two of those seized in October remain in custody on other
bombing charges, including Hafez Kassem Dalkamoni, a top aide to
PFLP-GC leader Ahmed Jabril.
   In a U.S. television interview in April, Jabril denied that his
group had any role in the Pan Am bombing. But he said Dalkamoni
often built and used the type of bomb that blew up Flight 103.
   The BBC program said that investigators were convinced that
PFLP-GC masterminded the attack. The group has long been the prime
suspect.
   In a statement distributed in Britain and Bonn, Lord Fraser,
chief legal officer of Scotland, said he found the ``Panorama''
program ``extremely interesting and clearly it was the product of
considerable work.''
   Lord Fraser said his legal position prevented him from
commenting on any specific allegations.
</TEXT>
