<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-27 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All roads once were said to lead to Rome, but
the Automobile Club of New York seems to think they all now grind
to a halt in midtown Manhattan.
   In an attempt to list the 10 most congested roads in the
metropolitan area, the club said Wednesday that every street
between 34th and 59th streets in Manhattan should qualify as a
motorist's nightmare and lumped them together as one.
   It blamed double parking, heavy pedestrian volume, lack of
traffic signal coordination and lack of off-street parking and
loading zones for stifling congestion, ``virtually any day, any
time.''
   One other of the nine roads winning the dubious gridlock honors
was in Manhattan _ Chambers Street, a main crosstown route from the
Brooklyn Bridge to the West Side. The rest of the roads were in the
city's other boroughs and suburbs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT BENNING, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boot camp veterans may think of drill
sergeants as people who cause rather than suffer anxiety, but the
Army is planning stress management programs for the sergeants, and
for their wives.
   The training already has been implemented at Fort Sill, Okla.,
and Fort Leonard Wood, Mo.
   The program will highlight pressures facing drill sergeants and
offer ways to deal with that stress, said Sgt. Maj. William Mayo of
Fort Benning's Infantry Training Center Command. And it is designed
to show the sergeants' wives what their husbands go through, he
said.
   The 13-week program, to be offered every four months, will
``give the drill sergeants a release to talk about their anxiety,''
Mayo said. ``The wives, too, because they spend a lot of time
alone. The husband can see what the wives are going through and
maybe we can provide a better understanding of what's really on the
mind of soldiers and their wives.''
   He said drill sergeants work 14 hours a day during a two-year
tour and the wives seldom see their husbands during that time. Mayo
said studies have shown that drill sergeants experience the most
stress during the first nine to 12 months of their duty tour.
</TEXT>
