<FIRST>r i AM-Suzman 1stLd-Writethru a0590 09-27 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suzman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0590,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Campaigner Helen Suzman Gets Honorary Title</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, `Mrs. Suzman ...' with her reaction.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II honored veteran anti-apartheid
canesday by giving her the honorary
title of Dame Commander of the British Empire.
   The award ``recognizes the distinguished contribution which Mrs.
Suzman has made toward fostering relations between this country and
South Africa and in the struggle against apartheid,'' the Foreign
Office said.
   ``Mrs. Suzman has championed the cause of human rights for all
the people of South Africa for more than 40 years,'' it said in a
statement announcing the award.
   Mrs. Suzman, 71, was first elected to South Africa's Parliament
in December 1952 and for many years was the lone representative of
the white liberal Progressive Federal Party. The party, now part of
a new group, is a major opposition party in the present white South
African Parliament.
   Mrs. Suzman, staying with friends in London, said she was
``thrilled and honored ... This is recognition of my stand against
apartheid and my work in keeping alive liberal values which are
shared in Great Britain and elsewhere in the world.''
   Her title is the female equivalent of a knighthood, but since it
is honorary, she cannot call herself Dame Helen, a privilege
reserved for Britons. The award carries much prestige, however, and
entitles Mrs. Suzman to use the initials CBE after her name.
   Britain also plans to set up a new scholarship program for black
South Africans to be called the Helen Suzman Awards, the Foreign
Office said. No details were announced.
</TEXT>
