<SECOND>AM-Lover's Quarrel,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Candidate Blames Incarceration on Love</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A City Council candidate who landed in
jail because of unrequited love believes he can win over voters
from his cell even if he couldn't woo his girlfriend back with his
aerial antics.
   Mark Roddam was free on $5,000 bond on a burglary charge filed
by his girlfriend and under court order not to see her when he
rented a small airplane Sept. 9 and flew it over the Birmingham
Race Course, where the woman works.
   Jefferson County Judge Robert Cahill didn't take kindly to
Roddam's ignoring his order and put the candidate under a $500,000
bond on a felony charge of burglary, two misdemeanor charges of
rendering a false alarm and wreckless operation of an aircraft.
   The judge said Wednesday that a preliminary hearing will be held
for Roddam on Oct. 18. Roddam, 33, is trying to unseat Bill Myers,
59, a veteran council member and former Birmingham police chief.
The election is Oct. 10.
   ``I do have a chance to win,'' Roddam said this week. ``But with
me in here it kind of puts a damper on things.''
   Although the felony count carries the most serious penalty, up
to 20 years in jail, it was the aircraft misdemeanor that landed
Roddam behind bars.
   Roddam said he wasn't flying exceptionally low, but news cameras
captured the plane buzzing the race course.
   ``Then the judge got mad at me for breaking the order of not
going near her and he gave me the half a million bond. I couldn't
pay that so here I am in jail,'' Roddam said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration also revoked Roddam's flying
license. Roddam, who is a used-car salesman, said he believes he
can win because he has name recognition.
   ``I'll do a better job than Bill Myers ever did,'' Roddam said.
``I know I've got a better personality. And it's obvious I'm better
looking and I'm a whole lot younger.''
</TEXT>
