<FIRST>u i AM-Sakharov-Environment     09-27 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov-Environment,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Says Soviet Union is Mostly an `Environmental Catastrophe'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet physicist Andrei Sakharov, the 1975
Nobel Peace Prize winner, said Wednesday that a ``very big part of
Soviet territory is an environmental catastrophe area.''
   Sakharov, an activist once held in the Soviet closed city of
Gorky, made his comments during ceremonies at Claude Bernard
University where he was awarded an honorary doctorate.
   The Soviet academician, 68, said the ``catastrophe has never
happened anywhere else as it has in the Soviet Union,'' adding that
it is the ``heritage of Stalinism.''
   Over the past several years, a number of Soviet officials and
newspaper reports have outlined significant problems of air, water
and soil pollution. Experts also cite radiation and health problems
stemming from the 1986 disaster at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant in the Soviet Ukraine.
   Fyodor Morgun, head of the State Committee for the Protection of
Nature, has said that pollution levels in 102 Soviet cities
affecting more than 50 million people are often 10 times higher
than Soviet laws permit.
   According to U.N. estimates, the Soviet Union is the world's
leading source of sulpher dioxide. And, the Soviet political
journal Novymir reported, the bed of the Neva River in Leningrad
has oil sludge in some areas 25 feet deep and pesticide use in the
Moldavian Republic bordering Romania has poisoned fruit, vegetables
and wine there.
</TEXT>
