<HEAD>Cable Station Stands by Show Despite Sponsor Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stroh Brewery Co., Exxon Corp., Citicorp and
other companies withdrew as sponsors of a cable TV special on
forest destruction after a timber and mining group objected to the
program.
   Cable station TBS aired the show Sunday without sponsorship, and
a station official said it will be broadcast again without paid
commercials despite pressure from interest groups.
   The show, produced by the National Audubon Society, was the
first in a four-part series called ``World of Audubon.'' The
segment, ``Ancient Forests: Rage Over Trees,'' is about the
destruction of Pacific Northwest forests.
   Chris Palmer, executive producer of the program, said the show
has a pro-conservation slant but also presents other viewpoints.
   Palmer said Stroh asked him to change the show but he would not.
Stroh was the program's chief sponsor and withdrew $600,000 in
production money, he said.
   ``We did hear from the logging industry. They were asking for us
to ensure the content was accurate,'' Stroh spokeswoman Lacey Logan
said.
   Robert SanGeorge, a spokesman for the National Audubon Society,
said opposition to the program was expressed by the Western States
Land Coalition, which represents mining and timber interests.
   Gerry Hogan, president of entertainment networks for TBS, would
not say how much ad revenue the station lost.
   Other sponsors that pulled out were Sears, Ford, Michelin and
New York Life.
