<FIRST>r w AM-SteelPlan     09-27 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Plan,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bush Steel Plan As U.S.-Japan Talks Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's proposal to extend steel
import restraints for 2{ years was swiftly approved by a House
panel Wednesday, as negotations continued with Japan and other
trading partners to carry out its provisions.
   Trade representatives from Japan, South Korea, the European
Community, Mexico, Venezuela and Romania are all in Washington this
week for negotiations with the Bush administration on new
product-by-product steel trade restrictions.
   The old restraints, which took effect in 1984, expire on
Saturday.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills expects to report on the
progress of the talks in a statement on Monday, according to her
spokeswoman, Christina McCown.
   Meanwhile, the House Ways and Means Committee approved on a
voice vote a bill carrying out Bush's program to extend the
restrictions with 29 countries until March 31, 1992.
   The administration hopes that 2{ years will be long enough to
negotiate an end to foreign government subsidies on steel and other
trade practices that the American industry considers unfair.
   The earlier agreements were negotiated by the Reagan
administration in 1984 to give U.S. steelmakers breathing space
from foreign competition and allow them to modernize. At the time,
American firms had been filing trade litigation charging overseas
competitors with employing unfair subsidies and selling imported
steel at less than fair market value.
   The American industry had sought a full five-year extension. But
many steel-using manufacturers argued that the quotas had driven up
prices and caused steel product shortages.
   Bush's plan, announced July 25, was intended as a compromise.
The extension will allow some countries' market shares to rise by 1
percentage point per year until quotas are phased out entirely.
Hills said the yearly increase will be allocated to countries that
exhibit the most willingness to stop subsidizing their domestic
industry.
   The Senate has not yet acted on the plan, which must first be
considered by its Finance Committee. But even opponents who wanted
a longer or shorter extension concede there is little they can do
to stop the Bush program now.
   In 1984, the United States had particular difficulty negotiating
an agreement with Japan, its largest steel trading partner. Japan
finally agreed to cap its share of the American steel market at 5.8
percent, but not before complaining that it was being
``strait-jacketed'' by U.S. demands.
</TEXT>
