<FIRST>r a AM-Thornburgh-Drugs     09-27 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Drugs,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funds From Drug Seizures to Be Used for Prison Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh unveiled
a plan Wednesday to use $229 million seized from drug traffickers
and organized crime rings for construction of more than 3,000
federal prison cells.
   ``We're now taking that money and turning it against those
criminals from whom it was so justly taken. Talk about poetic
justice _ this is that,'' Thornburgh said in a speech to U.S.
attorneys.
   He described the money transfer to the Federal Bureau of Prisons
as a ``down payment'' on President Bush's $1.5 billion proposed
prison expansion.
   Justice Department agencies have seized property worth more than
$1 billion since October 1988, and more than $500 million in
forfeited and liquidated criminal property has been placed in the
Asset Forfeiture Fund, Thornburgh said.
   Of that money, about $150 million was shared with local law
enforcement agencies.
   ``It's, I think, satisfying to think that it's now possible for
a drug dealer to serve time in a forfeiture-financed prison after
being arrested by agents driving a forfeiture-provided automobile
while working in a forfeiture-funded sting operation,'' Thornburgh
said, drawing applause from about 150 prosecutors.
   Recent changes in federal laws have helped in the seizure of
criminals' property, Thornburgh said. The forfeiture fund has grown
in yearly receipts from $27.2 million in 1985 to more than $500
million this year, according to Justice Department statistics.
   Thornburgh also said he will create an executive office for
asset forfeiture to better coordinate the fund.
   ``Our focus as prosecutors has to be attacking these
organizations where it hurts,'' he said of drug traffickers.
``They're only in business for one purpose, and that's to make
money.''
</TEXT>
