<FIRST>u a AM-EducationSummit-Cavazos     09-27 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Summit-Cavazos,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos: School Choice Is Cornerstone for Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Education Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restructuring the nation's
educational system should begin with allowing parents to decide
where to send their children to school, Education Secretary Lauro
Cavazos said Wednesday.
   Cavazos, in an interview shortly before the official opening of
the nation's first education summit, said President Bush and other
administration officials would not pressure governors to support
the concept of ``parental choice,'' but would still recommend it.
   ``I don't think that we're going to be selling an idea to these
governors,'' Cavazos said. ``I think what we need to do is put an
idea out and say this is a mechanism that's very, very important.
I've called (choice) the cornerstone for restructuring.''
   While Bush has been a staunch advocate of the idea, making it
the centerpiece of his education initiative, Cavazos initially was
lukewarm. He has since strongly endorsed it.
   Conservatives had hoped the administration would showcase the
idea at the summit and try to get commitments from governors to
support the concept in their states.
   The most controversial form of school choice allows parents to
send their children to schools outside the districts where they
live. So far this year, Arkansas, Iowa and Nebraska have joined
Minnesota in calling for open enrollment options for their citizen.
   Minnesota's open enrollment plan went into effect the past
school year.
   Shortly after the summit, in mid-October, Cavazos is slated to
begin a whirlwind ``choice'' tour that will take him to Minnesota,
North Carolina, Colorado and California. His plans include daytime
hearings and nighttime sessions with working parents.
   ``We're not really selling the program,'' said Cavazos. ``We
simply are taking it out there. People are going to consider it.''
   As with most of the education programs being discussed at the
summit, finding money to implement choice programs may be a problem.
   Cavazos admitted, ``There's no way in the world that we can fund
that kind of program.'' Transportation costs are one of the most
expensive aspects of the concept.
</TEXT>
