<FIRST>u w AM-HugoHelp     09-27 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo Help,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Ask up to $1.1 Billion for Hurricane's Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina's senators said Wednesday they
would try to win congressional approval this week for up to $1.1
billion to aid residents of areas stricken by Hurricane Hugo.
   Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., said he would seek $400 million for
victims in South Carolina, North Carolina, Puerto Rico and the
Virgin Islands. Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said he has asked for
$1.1 billion and has the support of Hollings and Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C.
   Hollings said the money would be requested as part of a
continuing resolution aimed at keeping the government in business
when the new government fiscal year begins Sunday.
   The House passed such a measure on Tuesday in anticipation of
the Senate being unable to pass all the appropriations bills by the
end of the week. The Senate now has the measure.
   Thurmond spokesman Christopher Simpson said the continuing
resolution was the most likely vehicle for obtaining the money
quickly.
   Thurmond said that the Bush administration supports his request.
   In a related matter, Hollings sharply criticized the Federal
Emergency Management Agency for its response to the Hugo emergency.
   He said he was angered in particular about the failure of FEMA
to order provide emergency generators immediately when Hollings
called acting administrator Robert Morris on Saturday.
   FEMA spokesman Bill McAda said the agency has answered the
state's request for generators, which was made this week. He said
the Red Cross, national guard and state-based authorities make the
first responses and the state governors must request FEMA
intervention.
   Meanwhile, the Agriculture Department said it has approved the
emergency release of food to help residents in six South Carolina
counties.
   Deputy Secretary Jack C. Parnell said the food was approved for
Charleston, Berkeley, Sumter, Dorchester and Georgetown counties,
and parts of Orangeburg County.
   Food was issued to families in Dorchester, Sumter and Orangeburg
counties Tuesday, he said. The other three counties may wait for
emergency food stamps rather than take food commodities.
   Parnell said South Carolina's request Tuesday for emergency food
stamps for the hardest hit counties was approved immediately and
that nearly $33 million worth of stamps are being sent for
emergency distribution later this week when retail grocery stores
are operating again.
   South Carolina officials estimated 100,000 households in the
state are in need of emergency food aid.
</TEXT>
