<FIRST>r w AM-FarmBill     09-27 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Bill,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Agriculture Chairman Says Farm Bill Will Not Wait For Trade
Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, said Wednesday
that new farm legislation will not be held up so trade negotiations
can proceed ``in Geneva or any other place.''
   In fact, he said, there will be a push for farm bill completion
by next spring, with or without a proposal from the Bush
administration.
   De la Garza, chairman of the House Agriculture Committee,
reacted to recent comments by Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter
who has indicated that only minor work might be necessary on
current farm law until substantive progress is made in the Uruguay
Round of talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The current law, the Food Security Act of 1985, will expire at
the end of next year, and Congress is just getting started on a
1990 bill.
   Much of the nuts and bolts of the legislation will bear directly
or indirectly on GATT trade policies and whether the United States
will be successful in its bid to scale back _ and eventually
eliminate _ trade barriers and subsidies that distort agricultural
trade.
   Yeutter said earlier this week in Minneapolis, Minn., that he
expected only minor changes in the commodity portions of the 1985
farm law and that major modification could come in 1991 after GATT
negotiations are completed.
   De la Garza said it is the responsibility of Congress to
legislate and decide how long a farm law shall be in effect.
   ``The Congress will decide whether or not to accept or reject
any agreement made by the administration in Geneva or any other
place,'' he said in a statement.
   ``We will cooperate to the extent possible with the
administration, but it is my firm intention to continue with our
stated goal of concluding the most extensive set of farm bill
hearings in history by the end of this calendar year,'' de la Garza
added.
   Further, he said, ``it is my intention to begin the markup of a
farm bill early in 1990,'' with or without a proposal by the Bush
administration.
   Yeutter has said he expects the administration will send its
1990 farm bill to Congress by the end of this year.
   De la Garza said it is his intention to have a five-year farm
billl completed and on the president's desk by the end of May.
</TEXT>
