<FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureNominee     09-27 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Nominee,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leahy Fears `James Watt Clone' in New Ag Department Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick
Leahy said Wednesday ``we don't need a James Watt clone'' as he
opened confirmation hearings on President Bush's nominee for
assistant secretary of agriculture for natural resources and the
environment.
   ``I expressed serious reservations when the Bush administration
announced the nomination of Mr. James Cason,'' the Vermont Democrat
said.
   He said he delayed the hearings to give the committee time to
review the questions that had been raised about Cason, who has been
a high-ranking official at the Interior Department since 1982.
   ``Mr. Cason's background and alleged actions while at the
Department of Interior concern me,'' Leahy said.
   He said Cason, 35, has no professional training in forest
land-use stewardship or soil and water conservation, which would be
his responsibilities as assistant agriculture secretary.
   The nominee also has been accused of advocating positions at the
Interior Department that ``reduce the returns to taxpayers from our
federal resources and undermine sound protection of the
environment,'' Leahy said.
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., asked Cason to compare himself to
Watt, the former Interior secretary whose pro-development policies
were considered by environmentalists to be destructive to public
lands.
   Cason said he and Watt worked under the same mandate to provide
public lands for multiple uses, including private and public
interests.
   But, he said, ``I don't know Jim Watt that well.''
   In his opening statement, Leahy said, ``We are at a time when a
strong and heightened awareness of the environment is needed in the
Department of Agriculture _ a spirit of cooperation among all
interests has to prevail.
   ``We do not need a James Watt clone in this position.''
   Cason, whose parents were migrant farm workers, graduated magna
cum laude from Pacific University in Forest Grove, Ore., with a
bachelor's degree in business administration.
   ``His was a world of hard work and hard living,'' said Sen. Mark
Hatfield, R-Ore., in a special appearance before the committee.
   Though his remarks about Cason were laudatory and he admonished
the committee to ``separate fact from fiction'' when reviewing
Cason's record, Hatfield never said explicitly that Cason should be
approved for the agriculture job.
   Cason was employed in real estate and development before joining
the Interior Department as special assistant to the director of the
Bureau Land Management in 1982 when Watt was Interior secretary.
   Since 1985, Cason has been principal deputy assistant secretary
for land and minerals management at Interior.
   Cason's detractors believe that in 1986 he tried to prevent a
report from becoming public that said the spotted owl's existence
could be endangered by the harvesting of old growth forest in the
Pacific northwest.
   Under questioning from Leahy, Cason denied that he tried to hide
the report, saying that changes needed to be made and he was
holding it only until ``it was cleaned up.''
   When asked by Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., if he approved selling
timber from national forests at below market cost, Cason said
factors other than the cost must be considered, such as local
economic concerns and rural development opportunities.
</TEXT>
