<FIRST>u w AM-PolishVisit     09-27 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polish Visit,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Educated Polish Leader Seeks Western Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month after rocketing from economics
professor to deputy prime minister of Poland, Solidarity activist
Leszek Balcerowicz was holding round-the-clock meetings Wednesday
with Western leaders to find the means for his government's
survival.
   ``We face a great threat, and to reduce the threat we see aid
from foreign nations not as a substitute for our own efforts but as
a condition that could reduce the risk and could ensure a
reasonable degree of success,'' Balcerowicz said during a pause in
his hectic schedule.
   Balcerowicz, 42, the senior Polish leader to visit Washington
since the Solidarity-led government came to power Aug. 24, holds
the twin titles of deputy prime minister and finance minister,
making him the senior Solidarity backer in the cabinet after Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   Mazowiecki heads the first non-Communist government in the
Soviet bloc.
   Balcerowicz may have been chosen not only because of his loyalty
to Solidarity and knowledge of economics, but because of his past
affiliation with the United States.
   He speaks English with an American accent he picked up along
with a masters' degree in business administration from St. John's
University in Queens, New York. He earned a doctorate at the Warsaw
Main School of Planning and Social Statistics, where he taught
until this summer.
   Balcerowicz supported the independent Solidarity trade union
during its 1980-81 legal existence. After the martial law crackdown
against the union Dec. 13, 1981, he quit the Polish United Workers
Party, the Communist party.
   Visiting Washington for a session of the 152-nation
International Monetary Fund, Balcerowicz has met with the finance
ministers of six of the seven major Western industrialized nations,
including U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady.
   Poland wants at least $1.5 billion over the next few months to
ensure a steady supply of essential goods and to stabilize the
faltering Polish currency, he said.
   ``There are no good precedents for what we have to do,''
Balcerowicz said at a news conference.
   ``We had quite numerous and quite productive meetings, at least
in terms of numbers. The atmosphere was warm and I would hope
results would be forthcoming quite quickly.''
   Earlier Wednesday, President Bush told the IMF that ``we must do
more'' to help Poland, urging the international lending
organization and its sister agency the World Bank to help Poland
restructure its economy.
   Balcerowicz said he welcomed both Bush's comments and approval
by the European Economic Community of a $660 million aid package
for Poland and Hungary, which is also moving quickly on the path of
democratic reforms.
   Balcerowicz said he had ``heard about 100 ideas'' for the West
to aid Poland, and that he would welcome the idea of forming Polish
and Western groups to coordinate the aid program.
   ``I would see the need for coordination on the Western side and
we are taking coordinating measures on our side,'' he said.
</TEXT>
