<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0623 09-27 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0623,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Refuse to Leave Embassy, Despite Harsh Conditions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE figure to 22,000 sted 20,000, Warsaw
embassy situation. DELETES soccer game reference pending developments.
No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PRA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of East Germans ignored
spreading illness and pouring rain Wednesday as they crowded into
the West German Embassy compound to press their demands to emigrate
to the West.
   ``I leave here only to the West or in a coffin,'' said one woman.
   Newcomers scaled the fence of the embassy garden, and refugees
told reporters that about 1,500 were inside the embassy compound.
   The East German government Tuesday offered them guaranteed
emigration with impunity within six months if they would return
home, but only 177 people accepted the offer.
   The East Germans are hoping they will have the same luck as
hundreds of East Germans who crowded the West German Embassy in
Budapest, Hungary, in hopes of winning permission to leave their
hard-line communist homeland. The refugees had been drawn to
Hungary since May, when the reformist nation began dismantling its
barriers along the western border.
   In West Germany, border officials said more than 500 East
Germans arrived overnight from Hungary via Austria. Since Hungary
decided on Sept. 10 to allow East Germans free passage to the West,
more than 22,000 refugees have arrived in West Germany, where they
are given automatic citizenship.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans Dietrich Genscher arranged to
meet East German Foreign Minister Oskar Fischer at the United
Nations in New York on Wednesday night, with the refugee situation
high on their agenda.
   Genscher told the U.N. General Assembly on Wednesday that
reforms in East Germany would open new prospects and encourage
people to stay there.
   Hundreds of beds were made available Wednesday to accommodate
the swelling crowd in the Prague embassy. Conditions were
deteriorating for the East Germans, housed mainly in Red Cross
tents.
   Several of the more than 250 children were said to have fallen
ill with diarrhea and colds following heavy rain that began during
the night. The embassy was dubbed ``Leipziger Hof,'' or hotel, by
the refugees, after the East German city of Leipzig.
   ``We are humans, not animals, aren't we? They cannot let us rot
away here, can they?'' a man told a Western reporter talking to him
through the fence.
   Some refugees said the crowd included many people with criminal
records who were not trying to emigrate for political reasons.
   The Czechoslovak Communist Party newspaper Rude Pravo said
providing the would-be emigrants with food and accommodations was
getting more difficult.
   It said the situation could be resolved only through discussions
between East and West Germany. East Germany has responded harshly
to Hungary's decision to let the East Germans leave.
   The refugees in Prague said they were given three days to accept
the offer by Wolfgang Vogel, an East German lawyer who is acting as
a negotiator for the East German government.
   Vogel left Prague for Warsaw Wednesday to discuss the fate of
about 400 East German refugees in the West German Embassy in the
Polish capital.
   He is expected to meet with Walter Priesnitz and Juergen
Sudhoff, two West German Foreign Ministry officials who negotiated
with Vogel in Prague.
   Vogel is expected to make a similar offer to East German
refugees in Poland as he did to those in Prague.
   Negotiations are ``on the right path'' for resolving the fate of
the East German refugees in Warsaw, Stefan Staniszewski, a
spokesman for the Polish Foreign Ministry, said Wednesday.
   ``Both German countries ... seem to be approaching an agreement
that would take into account the standpoints of the interested
sides, as well as a humane approach to the matter,'' Staniszewski
told a news conference.
   He would not elaborate on the course of the negotiations except
to say, ``The solution of this difficult question is on the right
path.''
</TEXT>
