<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1738EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Prisoners     09-27 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Prisoners,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Hold 39 Guardsmen Until Contras Comply With Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will not free the final
39 jailed former Somoza national guardsmen until Contra rebels
comply with a Central American peace accord and disband from camps
in Honduras, an official said Wednesday.
   The guardsmen remained jailed after the government freed 1,894
others in March. The government said a special commission of the
Organization of American States recommended the 39, generally
officers of higher rank, not be freed.
   All were arrested in July 1979 after the Sandinistas overthrew
dictator Anastasio Somoza and ended the 42-year Somoza family
dynasty.
   Carlos Nunez, president of the National Assembly, said no
general amnesty was possible in Nicaragua until there were
``concrete, clear signals'' from the insurgents that they would
comply with the peace agreement by demobilizing and relocating from
Honduran camps to Nicaragua or third countries by Dec. 8.
   In exchange for disbanding of the U.S.-backed rebels, Nicaragua
agreed to make democratic reforms, including more freedom for the
opposition leading up to February 1990 elections. Ortega and four
other Central American presidents signed the agreement Aug. 7 in
Tela, Honduras.
   Meanwhile the assembly on Wednesday approved a pardon for 457
civilian prisoners who had been jailed for violations of security
laws. It included more than 200 prisoners who were released by
President Daniel Ortega a month ago in the northern part of the
country.
</TEXT>
