<FIRST>u a AM-EducationSummit-Unions     09-27 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Summit-Unions,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Unions Uninvited Guests at Education Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Education Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<UNK>AP Education Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teacher unions were not invited to
the two-day education summit that opened Wednesday between
President Bush and the nation's governors. In fact, no education
groups were.
   But leaders and staff of the National Education Association and
the American Federation of Teachers were nonetheless very much in
evidence here, determined to play a behind-the-scenes role at the
historic gathering that could determine the future directionn of
school reform.
   Keith Geiger, president of the 2 million-member NEA, spent
Wednesday meeting with Govs. Booth Gardner of Washington, James
Blanchard of Michigan and Garrey Carruthers of New Mexico, pressing
the union's agenda that includes increased funding for federal
programs. Geiger said he planned to meet with about 10 governors
before the meeting adjourned Thursday.
   Albert Shanker, president of the 710,000-member AFT, said he
planned to arrive at the summit Thursday with about 10 other union
officials.
   ``Essentially we're going in order to be in a central position
to comment,'' said Shanker, reached by telephone in Washington.
   Both Shanker and Geiger denied any anger or bitterness at not
being invited.
   ``When the education summit was first discussed, we wondered how
in the world you could have it without groups like the NEA and
other educational organizations. But it's now a moot point. Had it
been opened up to a select group of organizations, and if we
weren't among them, then we'd have been upset,'' Geiger said.
   ``But as it turned out, the summit consists of a very defined
group of people. On that basis, we're comfortable,'' he said.
   ``I was invited to the White House before the summit, and we
spent considerable time talking with governors,'' said Shanker, who
added that he took no offense at not being invited to the summit.
   ``It's a big country,'' he said. ``There are 16,000 school
boards and many other constituencies. You have to draw the line
somewhere.''
   The three top officers of the NEA and six staff members were on
the scene, many of them in the press area in the University of
Virginia gymnasium. ``With somewhere around 1,000 reporters here,
we wanted them to have the NEA's perspective,'' Geiger said.
</TEXT>
