<FIRST>r w AM-AutoSafety 1stLd-Writethru a0668 09-27 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Safety, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Advocates, Insurers Join Forces on Auto Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs `There's no ... ' to UPDATE
with Nader comments. Makes minor editing changes throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer advocates and insurers who have
clashed in the past joined forces Wednesday to push for legislation
such as mandated autosafety features and a return to the 55 mph
speed limit on all interstate highways.
   The Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety will pursue ``a
balanced and aggressive approach'' to reduce highway deaths and
injuries and the high cost of automibile accidents, said executive
director Judith Lee Stone.
   Insurers hope improved auto safety will help stem rising auto
insurance costs, said Gerald L. Maatman, president of Kemper
National Property and Casualty Cos., one of several major insurance
firms joining the coalition.
   Researchers say auto accidents kill 48,000 Americans a year and
cost an estimated $74 billion.
   In the past, the insurance industry has come under fire from
consumer advocate groups over the cost of premiums.
   Maatman said reform movements like one in California, where
voters passed a referendum mandating reduced rates, helped prompt
the industry to join the coalition. The referendum was promoted by
consumer advocate Ralph Nader.
   ``There's no doubt (the California referendum) has heightened in
the minds of our industry the fact that the public is now expecting
an increased amount of effort in participation on problems,''
Maatman said.
   In a telephone interview, Nader said the insurance industry had
taken a first step toward fulfilling ``its neglected responsibility
in loss prevention.''
   Nader said that without the California referendum, insurance
companies ``never would have done this.''
   Insurance companies and groups representing 40 percent of the
American automobile insurance market have pledged $1.5 million for
the organization's efforts in the first year, Stone said.
   At the federal leval, the group backs a Senate bill to extend
current auto safety features to trucks and vans. It also adds
features to protect against impact from side collisions and require
motorcycle helmet usage, anti-lock brakes and passenger side air
bags.
   The group also wants a return to the 55 mph speed limit on all
interstate highways. In 1987, Congress allowed states to raise the
speed limit to 65 mph on rural stretches of interstates.
   At the state and local level, the group plans to push issues
such as drunken driving, safety belts and child seats.
   Insurance discounts for using safety devices are not among the
group's priorities.
   ``We will work hard to make this marriage work and we'll worry
about whether we have any children later,'' Maatman said of
divisive issues that might come up later.
   Consumer advocate groups that will be part of the coalition
include Public Citizen, a Nader-founded group. In addition, safety
and medical experts will also be on the group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
