<FIRST>u i AM-Angola-Crash     09-27 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Crash,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of Portuguese President Seriously Injured in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>By GREG MYRE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joao Soares, the son of
Portugal's president, was seriously injured in a plane crash near a
guerrilla base in southeastern Angola, officials said Wednesday.
   The four other people in the plane, including two members of the
Portuguese Parliament, suffered less severe injuries, officials
said. All five were flown to South Africa and admitted to a
hospital in Pretoria.
   The accident occurred Tuesday night when one of the engines on a
small Cessna aircraft failed during takeoff from the airstrip at
Jamba, headquarters for the rebels of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), officials said.
   Soares, a Socialist Party member of Parliament and son of
President Mario Soares, and fellow parlimentarians Jose Nogueira de
Brito and Rui Gomes da Silva were being treated at H.F. Verwoerd
Hospital in Pretoria, said Joao Camara, secretary of the Portuguese
Embassy in South Africa.
   Rainer Geppelt, a German journalist, and pilot Joaquim Agusto,
also were hurt, according to a statement from South African Foreign
Minister Pik Botha.
   Botha described Joao Soares' injuries as serious, saying he had
suffered head and lung injuries, extensive internal bleeding, a
broken jaw and fractured pelvis.
   Botha said a commercial aircraft was sent from South Africa to
pick up the injured people after the intervention of President
Soares.
   South Africa says it stopped military assistance to the Angolan
rebels as part of a regional peace accord signed last December that
also calls for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban soldiers from Angola.
   Journalists and government officials from numerous countries
continue to visit the rebel headquarters on planes departing from
South Africa.
   President Soares was to leave as planned for Budapest, Hungary,
on an official visit, officials in Lisbon said. However, his wife
Maria Barroso, decided not to join him so she could visit her
injured son Thursday in South Africa, officials added.
   Portugal ruled Angola until 1975, when the colony gained
independence under the leadership of the Marxist government.
</TEXT>
