<HEAD>Bush Salutes Teachers, Including Wife Barbara</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Education Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush raised a toast at his
education summit Wednesday night to America's teachers ``who
enlighten our young people and inspire them to excellence.''
   He commented in remarks prepared for a banquet at Monticello for
the governors who are meeting with him at the summit.
   Among the teachers he saluted he numbered six members of his
Cabinet, 13 governors and even his wife Barbara. While she ``has
never held a teaching position,'' he included her, he said, because
she's been ``a leader in the fight against illiteracy.''
   ``I toast those who have heard the call and followed it _ those
who have sacrificed so much in order that America might enjoy a
sure foundation of freedom and happiness,'' Bush said.
   ``I toast our teachers _ those who taught us, and teach our
children, and those among us who have been members of this proud
profession.
   ``We have come to the home of Thomas Jefferson to build upon his
dream of a strong system of education for all. But without our
teachers _ without their vision and their dedication _ the dream
would be lost. I ask you to join me in saluting the teachers of
America.''
