<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Political Parties Battle in Namibia Township</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shots were fired and bottles hurled as
supporters of two rival political factions battled in Windhoek's
black townwship Wednesday. Hospital officials said 20 people were
injured.
   The fracas began as the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance drove a
United Nations-monitored motorcade through a neighborhood that
supports the guerrilla-backed South-West Africa People's
Organization, called SWAPO.
   Residents of the neighborhood accused alliance supporters of
stoning houses that flew SWAPO flags.
   One rock struck the head of a 2-year-old boy standing in the
doorway of his home, said residents. He was hospitalized in serious
condition, they said.
   A 20-year-old man was hospitalized with multiple cuts on his
head, and 15 to 20 other people were treated for cuts and bruises,
hospital officials said.
   No arrests were reported.
   The United Nations is monitoring the campaign leading to
independence elections Nov. 7-11. Observers were present when the
violence began, but their job was to monitor the police, said U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard.
   U.N. Special Representative Martti Ahtisaari has requested a
meeting with territorial administrator Louis Pienaar to discuss
``how law enforcement authorities came to allow such a situation to
arise,'' Eckhard said.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, whose guerrilla
wing fought a largely unsuccessful 23-year war against South
African rule of the territory, is favored to win most votes in the
election. Its chief opponent is the Democratic Turnhalle Alliance,
a multiracial party that participated in a transitional government
backed by South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
