<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with new material and editing. No
pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Slovenian parli
the federal parliament earlier Wednesday asked Slovenia to postpone
adoption of the changes.
   Western-style democracy is generally opposed in Yugoslavia's
other regions.
   Commenting on the vote, Joze Smole, head of the Slovenian
Socialist Alliance, a communist-led umbrella organization, told the
AP that ``we must now calm the passions aroused by this in
Yugoslavia.''
   ``It is a gross lie that Slovenia wishes to withdraw from
Yugoslavia,'' Smole said, dismissing protests against the changes
as ``irrational acts.''
   Authorities in Slovenia have never actually proposed that the
republic withdraw from the Yugoslav federation.
   Slovenia's 2 million inhabitants make up 8 percent of
Yugoslavia's population and speak a different language from the
Serbo-Croat used by three-quarters of the federation's inhabitants.
   They have traditionally safeguarded their autonomy since the
region was incorporated into Yugoslavia in 1918.
   The leadership of Serbia, Slovenia's main political foe,
advocates strengthening the role of the loose federation by
granting greater powers to the federal government, limiting local
autonomy.
   Serbian lawmakers repeatedly charged that the amendments would
open the door to the eventual breakup of the Yugoslav federation.
   Federal authorities, including the country's 8-member
presidency, repeatedly demanded that some proposed amendments be
dropped because they ``conflict with the federal constitution.''
   The armed forces came out openly Wednesday in support of the
Serbian position in the longstanding political feud between
liberals and conservatives.
   ``The consequences which could arise from these amendments are
extremely serious, and we must warn the (Slovenian) authorities
about this,'' said Adm. Stane Brovet, a Central Committee member.
   But Milan Kucan, head of the Slovenian party, told the session,
``Slovenian communists will choose (to defend) the interests of the
Slovenian people rather than become quislings.''
