<FIRST>u i AM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru   09-27 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0749,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Reaffirms Support For Israeli Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 4: ``There is,'' further Arens quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP DIplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, opening a
round of talks with Mideast leaders, Wednesday offered assurances
to Israel of full U.S. support for its proposal for Palestinian
negotiations.
   Baker met for 45 minutes with Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens. Afterward, Arens and a senior U.S. official said Baker had
not asked Israel to adopt a formula for negotiations sponsored by
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
   ``We have wholehearted American acceptance of the Israeli peace
initiative and nothing has changed on that,'' Arens told reporters.
   ``There is no alternate initiative to ours. There is only one
peace initiative on the table and it is the one that was formulated
by Mr. Shamir,'' he said.
   ``We didn't discuss any new formula,'' the foreign minister said.
   Mubarak's 10-point formula includes at least two elements
rejected by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir _ that
negotiations should be based on an Israeli commitment to yield
territory for peace and should include Palestinians from outside
the West Bank and Gaza as participants in the talks.
   Two prominent Labor Party members of the Israeli Cabinet, Deputy
Prime Minister Shimon Peres and Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin,
have approved of Mubarak's approach.
   But Labor is in the minority in the coalition government. Shamir
and Arens are from the dominant Likud coalition.
   A senior U.S. official said Baker had told Arens that he did not
view Mubarak's 10 points as a proposal or as a plan.
   ``We are not asking them (the Israelis) to accept the 10
points,'' this official said at a briefing for reporters conducted
under ground rules that prohibit identification.
   ``The 10 points are not a basis for negotiations,'' describing
them instead as a ``vehicle for a dialogue.
   Baker will continue the discussions at a three-way meeting on
Thursday with Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmet Abdul-Meguid and
Arens.
   On Friday, Arens meets with Mubarak, who is in New York to
address the special session of the U.N. General Assembly.
   Next Wednesday, the principal members of the Israeli Cabinet
will meet for a formal decision on the Egyptian leader's formula.
   Shamir's proposal is to hold elections among the 1.4 million
Palestinian Arabs who live on the West Bank and Gaza to chose
negotiatiors.
   They would work out a five-year program of local self-rule with
Israel. This would be followed by negotiations on an overall
settement with Egypt and Jordan as well.
   Egypt formerly controlled the Gaza Strip and Jordan the West
Bank. Israel conquered the territories in a 1967 war against many
of the country's Arab neighbors.
</TEXT>
