<FIRST>r a AM-USAirProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0706 09-27 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir Probe, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir, NTSB Discount Report of Crew Drinking</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with seven grafs to UPDATE with investigator's report
on rudder. Picks up 5th graf, `Two people....'. SUBS 11th graf prvs, `The
NTSB...' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir and federal investigators Wednesday
dismissed a report the pilots of a jetliner that skidded into the
East River last week had been drinking for five hours before
getting into the cockpit.
   Meanwhile, investigators said a device that holds the rudder
steady for the pilot during takeoff was wrongly set in the full
left position, which could account for the drift the pilot reported
led him to abort the takeoff.
   ``That would tend to want to move the plane to the left if he
didn't do other things to compensate for it,'' said Ted
Lopatkiewicz, a National Transportation Safety Board spokesman in
Washington.
   Peter Baron, who heads the National Center for Air Traffic
Safety, a consumer advocacy group, said the rudder trim ``clearly
could have been one of the factors that led to the crash.'' He said
it would not have become apparent until the plane had built up
speed during takeoff.
   Responding to the drinking report, USAir spokesman David Shipley
in Arlington, Va., said the cockpit crew had only about two hours
between the time they arrived at LaGuardia Airport on Sept. 20 and
the time they reported to the gate for the ill-fated flight.
   ``That's documented,'' he said.
   In addition, the NTSB said the co-pilot was on the plane for
most if not all of that time, while the captain went to USAir
offices at LaGuardia.
   Two passengers were killed after the Boeing 737-400 aborted
takeoff and skidded into the water.
   Federal Aviation Administration regulations prohibit drinking up
to eight hours before a flight.
   Drug and alcohol tests on the pilot and co-pilot came out
negative, but the urine samples were taken 48 hours after the
accident, making them virtually useless for alcohol testing.
   The New York Post reported Wednesday that a detective close to
the investigation said the crew may have spent as many as five
hours in bars near the airport.
   It said that a passenger, Ken Trendel, the husband of a USAir
employee, told authorities immediately after the crash he had been
out ``bouncing'' with the captain and the co-pilot. Investigators
said they believed he meant ``drinking'' or ``bar hopping.''
   Trendel said he, the two pilots and a fourth man had been at a
bar in the nearby Marriott Hotel between 7:30 p.m. and 9:30 p.m. on
Sept. 20. The plane crashed at 11:29 p.m.
   The NTSB has turned up no suggestion that the pilots were
drinking, Lopatkiewicz said. ``No one has volunteered that kind of
information,'' he said.
   In addition, Shipley said Capt. Michael W. Martin and co-pilot
Constantine Kleissas did not arrive at LaGuardia until 8:40 p.m.
They flew in from Baltimore.
   They were then assigned to Flight 5050, which was scheduled to
depart at 10:30 p.m. The plane left the gate at 10:52 p.m. and was
held on the ground until about 11:20 p.m., Lopatkiewicz said.
   ``The New York Post story and this other gentleman's allegations
just don't jibe with the facts,'' Shipley said.
   Lopatkiewicz said Kleissas ``basically stayed with the plane
most of the time.''
   Martin went to the USAir operations center ``to get weather
information and fill out some paperwork. He also had a meeting with
some people in USAir's ground control office,'' Lopatkiewicz said.
   The Post said Trendel may be subpoenaed to testify before the
grand jury investigating the crash.
   The pilots' lawyer, Frederick Hafetz, did not return telephone
calls Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
