<DOCNO> AP890927-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1923EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SavannahRiver     09-27 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah River,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Orders Further Tests on Key Weapons Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move that could further delay the
production of a scarce gas needed for nuclear warheads, Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins on Wednesday ordered additional testing
of the government's tritium reactors before they are restarted.
   In a brief announcement, Watkins said all three
tritium-producing reactors at the Savannah River plant near Aiken,
S.C. would undergo ultrasonic testing for cracks before they are
restarted.
   Watkins provided no details. His spokeswoman, Christina Sankey,
later said the decision was a change from earlier acceptance of a
recommendation by the plant operator, Westinghouse Corp., that
ultrasonic testing need not be completed before the first reactor
is restarted.
   Ms. Sankey said it was ``too early to tell'' whether the
additional testing would mean a further delay in restarting the
first reactor, designated K reactor.
   Watkins announced Sept. 7 that low-power testing of the reactor
would begin late next summer and that production would be resumed
sometime in the October-December quarter of 1990.
   He said he would review the timetable next April.
   Tritium is a rare radioactive isotope of hydrogen used to boost
the destructive power of nuclear warheads, and to provide most of
the power of thermonuclear warheads. About 5.5 percent of any
amount decays in the course of a year, which means that warheads in
service must periodically receive new supplies of the gas.
   All three reactors have been closed for more than a year for
repairs and safety improvements.
   Recent ultrasonic testing on the P reactor vessel at Savannah
River had discovered ``a potential indication'' of a crack ``in
excess of nine inches'' in the area of a welded seam, Watkins said.
   This finding is still being studied and further tests are being
performed, Watkins said. Ms. Sankey said later, ``We're quite
confident there is no crack'' in the vessel.
   Ms. Sankey said there was ``no technical reason'' to condition a
K reactor restart on completion of the ultrasonic testing, but that
Watkins chose to impose the condition in order to ``instill greater
public confidence in the restart program.''
   In ultrasonic testing, high-frequency sound waves are passed
through the reactor vessel walls, and any abnormalities show up as
breaks in the waves. The Energy Department last year had said it
would require the completion of ultrasonic testing of the three
reactors before any were restarted, but the requirement was dropped
after Westinghouse took over from E.I. du Pont de Nemours &amp; Co. as
operator of the plant last April.
   James Moore, president of the Westinghouse unit that is running
the Savannah River complex, said in an interview last spring that
ultrasonic testing for cracks would be ``just an added burden''
that would not enhance safety.
   Ms. Sankey said Watkins decided this week to overrule the
Westinghouse recommendation after it was roundly cricitized by some
of his own advisers. Environmental groups opposed to operation of
the reactors also had criticized the plan.
   A leak from a crack in the vessel of another Savannah River
reactor, known as C reactor, was discovered in 1984. That led to
its permanent shutdown a year later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
