<FIRST>r w AM-MilitarySpending 1stLd-Writethru a0667 09-27 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Rejection Seen as Blow to Star Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cheney-Soviets, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs, bgng, `Work on,' with voice
vote approval of amendment on radar jammer and introduction of narcotics
strike force; edits 9th graf pvs for transition; picks up 10th graf pvs,
bgng: The Senate Appropriations ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate rejection of a $300 million addition to
President Bush's Star Wars proposal reflects an increasing
congressional sentiment to limit the program, Majority Leader
George Mitchell said Wednesday.
   The Senate, as part of its work on a $288 billion military
spending bill, refused a day earlier to restore funds for Star Wars
to a level closer to the $4.5 billion it approved last month in
authorization legislation.
   The overwhelming vote of 66-34 was perceived by some lawmakers
as a blow to the program.
   ``I think there is a growing recognition ... that we have to
reduce our expectations and level of resources committed to it,''
Mitchell, D-Maine, told reporters. The Senate vote was ``a strong
indication of concern in that regard,'' he said.
   President Reagan proposed Star Wars, formally known as the
Strategic Defense Initiative, six years ago, hailing it as a
nuclear-age antidote to a strike against the United States.
   But Vice President Dan Quayle's recent comment that the Reagan
administration's SDI ``astrodome'' approach to protect the United
States was ``political jargon,'' and the Soviet Union's decision to
separate Star Wars from a strategic arms reduction treaty have
undercut support for the program.
   ``SDI has now been cut loose,'' Sen. John Warner of Virginia,
ranking Republican on the Armed Services Committee, said Tuesday.
   Work on the military spending bill was put aside Wednesday as
the Senate took up a $9.4 billion compromise plan to pay for the
Bush administration's war on drugs. That plan was approved 97-2.
   Later in the day, however, the Senate did briefly take up the
bill and passed by voice vote an amendment limiting production of
the airborne self-protection jammer until further testing is
completed. In addition, a non-binding resolution was introduced
calling for U.S. participation in a multinational anti-drug strike
force.
   The Senate will vote on that measure Thursday when it is
expected to complete the appropriations bill. A handful of
amendments on anti-satellite weapons, U.S. troop levels in Europe
and Star Wars are still pending.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee, in adopting the spending
legislation, approved on a 16-11 vote a measure requiring that $820
million of the $3.7 billion for Star Wars be used for research on
lasers and particle beams.
   Proponents of the amendment expressed concerns that the
administration will sacrifice long-term research on directed energy
weapons such as lasers and particle beams in favor of a ``quick fix
or a Phase 1 deployment'' that would favor the so-called
``Brilliant Pebbles'' scheme favored by many in the administration.
   The funding level for Star Wars adopted in the appropriations
bill totals about $4.1 billion _ $3.7 billion for the Pentagon's
program and $355 million in Energy Department and military
construction money. That falls $900 million short of what Bush
requested for the program in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   Among the other amendments are:
   _A measure to bar funds for anti-satellite weapons tests unless
the administration could certify that the Soviets had engaged in
tests of their own, had refused to bargain in good faith in
limitations and had blocked international verification efforts.
   _A proposal calling for either a reduction of 30,000 American
troops stationed in Europe or a requirement that U.S. allies foot
the bill for those personnel if NATO and the Warsaw Pact nations
fail to reach a conventional arms agreement by Oct. 1, 1990.
</TEXT>
