<FIRST>r a AM-US-Czechoslovakia     09-27 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Czechoslovakia,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Pushes Human Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia agreed Wednesday to consider a
U.S. request for holding periodic talks on human rights in the
Central European country.
   A senior U.S. official said Secretary of State James A. Baker
III made the request in a meeting with Foreign Minister Jaromir
Johanes.
   Baker also asked the Czechoslovakian official to review the
cases of a handful of jailed demonstrators.
   The meeting was the first bewteen a U.S. secretary of state and
a Czechoslovakian foreign minister in 11 years.
   Baker proposed to the foreign minister setting up a so-called
``working group'' of American and Czechoslovakian diplomats to meet
periodicially on human rights cases, a U.S. official said.
   Working groups have been instrumental in settling scores of
human rights cases in the Soviet Union. Johanes said his government
would consider the proposal. He also told Baker that laws bearing
on human rights were being revised, said the U.S. official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The foreign minister outlined some economic reforms under way in
Prague. But Baker emphasized that they should be accompanied by
political reform.
</TEXT>
