<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique-Portugal     09-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique-Portugal,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portuguese Leader Pays Homage to War Heroes, Meets Chissano</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portuguese Prime Minister Anibal
Cavaco Silva laid a wreath Wednesday at the tomb of Mozambicans who
died fighting for independence from Portugal, then discussed
improving relations with the former colony.
   At a meeting with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano, Cavaco
Silva said the traumas of the past are over.
   ``We must have a spirit of construction,'' he said.
   The two men met on the second day of the Portuguese leader's
five-day visit.
   ``We want to consolidate the existing relations between Portugal
and Mozambique that have been forged over centuries,'' Chissano
said.
   Cooperation between the two governments should ``bring mutual
benefits, despite the unequal levels of development,'' he said in
apparent reference to the lack of infrastructure and trained
professionals in Mozambique when Portuguese colonialism ended.
   Chissano invited Portuguese companies to help increase food
production in Mozambique, where nearly half the 14 million people
need partial or complete food aid. He also suggested Portugal's
membership in the European Community could be used to the benefit
of Mozambique and other African countries.
   The Portuguese leader appeared to agree.
   ``The tendency just to look eastwards (in Europe), leaving
Africa aside, should be avoided,'' he said.
   Mozambique's economy has been drained by a civil war that has
continued since independence in 1975. Rebels of the right-leaning
Mozambique National Resistance presently are engaged in peace talks
with Mozambican church leaders representing the Marxist government.
   Cavaco Silva earlier had laid a wreath at the star-shaped white
marble Monument of Heroes, the burial place of several prominent
members of the Front for the Liberation of Mozambique who died in
the revolution that led to independence. Among them are Samora
Machel, Mozambique's first president, and Eduardo Mondlane, the
first nationalist leader whom most Mozambicans believe was killed
by Portuguese secret police. Machel died in an October 1986 plane
crash that officials here blame on South Africa _ a charge Pretoria
denies.
</TEXT>
