<FIRST>r w AM-WeaponsPlants     09-27 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Plants,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Luken: Perpetrators Off The Hook For `Environmental Scandal
Of Century'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government employees in charge of America's
bomb factories and the contractors who run the plants ``have been
let off the hook for the biggest environmental scandal of the
century,'' Rep. Thomas Luken complained Wednesday.
   Luken, D-Ohio, heads a House subcommittee that's been probing
problems at the nation's nuclear weapons plants, which are so
contaminated that the Energy Department expects cleanup costs to
exceed $90 billion.
   Luken made public a letter in which the Justice Department said
neither Environmental Protection Agency nor Federal Bureau of
Investigation had ever sought prosecution of environmental crimes
at weapons plants. Just one case has ever been referred to
prosecutors, involving a 1983 incident in Tennessee, but no charges
were brought, the congressman's staff said.
   ``The unprecedented radioactive and hazardous waste pollution at
DOE's weapons plants results directly from the failure to hold
anyone accountable,'' Luken said in a statement.
   ``Until environmental crimes at the weapons plants lead to jail
sentences, and until DOE holds its contractors' feet to the fire,
DOE will continue to pollute faster than it is cleaning up,'' said
Luken, repeating his contention that someone should be put behind
bars as punishment for the years of radioactive and hazardous waste
contamination.
   ``Incredibly, the Department of Justice and the DOE inspector
general are now telling us that DOE's contractors and their
employees have been let off the hook for the biggest environmental
scandal of the century,'' he said.
   On Tuesday, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, put into the Senate record
a DOE inspector general report urging changes in the way the
government handles weapons-plant contracts.
   ``The lessons of the past tell us that to a major extent the
enormous and costly problems facing the DOE`s nuclear program are
due to a basic failure to adopt normal practices of
accountability,'' Glenn said.
   The report, prepared at Glenn's request, said the government's
been forced to pay obviously fraudulent expenses and is barred from
ordering the firing of incompetent weapons plant workers because of
the way its contracts are written.
   Deputy Energy Secretary Henson Moore said the department would
demand stronger contracts when they come up for renewal.
</TEXT>
