<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     09-27 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel, Soviet Union Agree to Cooperate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli and Soviet officials agreed Wednesday to an
exchange of chambers of commerce and a framework to establish
``direct economic relations,'' an Israeli official said.
   Moscow broke diplomatic relations with Israel following the 1967
Middle East war and the two countries have virtually no economic
ties.
   ``This is not a political agreement, but one purely of economic
cooperation between our two countries,'' the official told
reporters on condition of anonymity.
   He said the accord calls for the opening of an Israeli chamber
of commerce in Moscow and a Soviet one in Tel Aviv before the end
of the year.
   Official approval of the agreement is to take place in Tel Aviv
in November, he said.
   At meetings Tuesday and Wednesday, the delegations also agreed
to a framework for broad cooperation in economic, technological and
scientific domains, he said.
   They agreed that cooperation between the non-political chambers
of commerce was the best way for the two countries to re-establish
economic ties.
   The only East bloc nation to have diplomatic relations with
Israel is Hungary, which re-established ties Sept. 18, 1988.
   The Israeli official said the agreement provides an
institutional framework for collaboration, but did not describe
specific projects.
   Israel's delegation was led by Danny Gillerman, president of the
Federation of the Israeli Chamber of Commerce, and Yaacov Cohen,
director-general of the Industry Ministry.
   Vladimir Golanov, first vice-president of the Chamber of
Commerce and Industry led the Soviet delegation.
</TEXT>
