<FIRST>r w AM-IMF-China     09-27 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-China,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>With US-Finance Meeting,370</HEAD>
<HEAD>China Says Economic Reform Will Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0788 to restore keyword line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China told the global financial community
Wednesday that despite setbacks and problems its policy of economic
reform and opening to the outside world ``shall never be altered.''
   Economic liberalization in the past decade has generated
prosperity, vitality and ``genuine benefits,'' and has become
``popular and deep-rooted among the Chinese people,'' Li Guixian,
state councillor and governor of the People's Bank of China, told
the annual meeting of the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund.
   ``No matter what setbacks and difficulties may arise on our way
forward, the determination of the Chinese government and its people
in continuing the reform and opening policy shall never be
altered,'' Li said.
   The speech, regarded as an important statement of policy in the
wake of China's upheaval the past summer, was silent on the issue
of political liberalization.
   It left delegates from 151 other countries wondering if Li was
including Beijing's leadership shakeup, imposition of martial law
and the killing and arrests of democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen
Square when he said reform and opening to world are ``by no means
easy for a complex country like China ... and at times we will
encounter difficulties and setbacks.''
   But he assured his audience of hundreds of government officials
and bankers that China intends to improve its attractiveness for
foreign investment and to pay its debts.
   ``We have been continung our efforts to improve the ... climate
in order to attract foreign investors ... the Chinese government
places high priority on creditworthiness and enjoys sufficient
capacity to service its debts,'' he said.
   ``We respect all foreign governments and friends who would like
to develop relations with us on equal terms, and it is our
intention to further develop and expand our friendly relations with
them,'' Li said.
   Western governments and businesses scaled down their relations
with China after the June crackdown. Numerous foreign companies are
in the process of deciding whether to pursue their investments in
China. The World Bank, on whose board of governors Li Guixian has a
seat, in June held up $780 million worth of loans for projects in
China to await economic and political developments there.
</TEXT>
