<FIRST>u a AM-Summit-Bennett     09-27 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Bennett,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Education Secretary Pans `Pap' At Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William Bennett, a bit
player in President Bush's education summit with the governors,
stole a scene Tuesday night with a stinging review of one of the
closed-door discussions.
   The truculent former Reagan administration secretary of
education moderated one of the sessions and had some ``feisty''
exchanges with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and other Democrats over
defense spending.
   But in summarizing the talks afterward for reporters, Bennett
gave what was in effect a pox on both their houses, Democrats and
Republicans alike.
   Bennett, a onetime philosophy professor, said, ``There was pap;
standard Democratic pap. There was standard Republican pap, and
there was stuff that rhymes with pap on both sides, too.''
   There were ``a couple of good exchanges, an occasional outburst
of candor ... attempts to suppress it, but a few people persisted
in candor so we got a few points made,'' said Bennett.
   ``Much of the discussion took part in total absence of any
knowledge of what works or what's effective in the actual
experience of school,'' said Bennett, who published a series of
``What Works'' guides when he ran the Department of Education from
1985 to 1988.
   Several governors, including Mississippi's Ray Mabus, spoke to
the importance of federal programs to help feed and nurture infants
and pre-school children, including Head Start.
   But Bennett felt the emphasis on pre-school development was
being ballyhooed.
   ``There was a lot of talk about early childhood. Everyone likes
small children and wants to do better by them,'' he said.
   But, he added, ``you can't fix American education simply by
focusing on early childhood because if you give kids good early
education but you mess it up after that when they go into regular
schools, you haven't done anything more than just spend more
money.''
   He said everyone liked the idea of national performance goals
for education.
   One governor ``suggested that his fanny would be out if he
didn't reach his accountability goals, which I thought was
encouraging and candid,'' said Bennett.
   Bennett said sardonically, ``There is progress in one part of
America's curriculum, and that is the self-esteem curriculum. We
are doing worse, but feeling much better about it.''
   In a recent international comparison, American students scored
last in math and Koreans first, he said, but when asked if they
were good at math, 68 percent of the U.S. youths said yes compared
to only 23 percent of the Koreans.
   ``That is a sort of drug-induced curriculum,'' said Bennett.
``People feel good on drugs while not doing good at all.''
   Asked why he felt much of the discussion was uninformed, Bennett
replied, ``Some people were saying things that other people had
written for them, and they were reading them out of books and
reading them off cards, and that's fine but what we were hoping for
was a candid discussion.''
   ``Some people really talked; some people didn't,'' said Bennett.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
