<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-27 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Air Blasts Upper Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A blast of cold air hit the upper Great Lakes on Wednesday and
most of the nation had sunny skies, except for light snow in Maine
and rain in some parts of the South and the West.
   In Michigan, Grand Rapids had a reading of 29 degrees, breaking
the Sept. 27, 1947, low of 30 degrees. Muskegon's temperature
dropped to 27, breaking the record of 30 set in 1947, and Sault
Ste. Marie recorded a 26-degree reading, 2 degrees under a
14-year-old record.
   A record low of 36 degrees for the date was set in Mansfield,
Ohio.
   Colder temperatures were expected to move across the northern
Appalachians by Thursday morning. Overnight warnings for frost or
freezing temperatures were posted in southern Vermont, southern New
England, parts of New York, northeast Pennsylvania and portions of
eastern West Virginia.
   Skies were sunny over much of the nation Wednesday afternoon
except for northern Maine, which had snow showers. Also, rain and
thunderstorms reached from southern Georgia across the Florida
Peninsula, along the lower Texas Gulf Coast, and from Utah into
western Wyoming.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.33 inches at the Naval Air Station near Jacksonville,
Fla.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43 degrees at Caribou,
Maine, to 101 degrees at Yuma, Ariz. Low temperature for the Lower
48 states was 21 degrees at Houghton Lake and Pellston, Mich.
</TEXT>
