<FIRST>r a AM-BakkerTrial     09-27 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bakker Trial,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stream of Bakker Witnesses Stand Behind Their Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker's attorney and the judge
hearing the fraud and conspiracy case against the deposed
television evangelist clashed Wednesday over the number of
character witnesses called by the defense.
   ``We're not going to sit here the next two or three days and
hear the same thing over and over,'' U.S. District Court Judge
Robert Potter told lawyer Harold Bender.
   Wednesday's testimony was similar to that presented Tuesday,
with ardent supporters of Bakker testifying that they thought he
was a fine man who was underpaid and unjustly accused. The defense
was in its fifth day of trial, with an interruption Friday by
Hurricane Hugo.
   Arnold Santjer, who owns a ship-loading business in Bradenton,
Fla., was the 18th ``Lifetime Partner'' in the PTL ministry to
testify. He created a stir in the courtroom when he said he owned
76 lifetime partnerships costing a total of $76,000. Each $1,000
unit entitled the owner to rights to three nights yearly lodging at
the hotel at the PTL theme park.
   Asked whether he had any regrets, Santjer said, ``I'm not
unhappy. The Lord gave me the money to start with. It was his in
the beginning.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jerry Miller pressed Santjer on cross
examination about his confidence in Bakker's claims that he would
limit the number of partnerships to 25,000. The indictment charges
he sold more than 66,000.
   The 6-foot-3, 220-pound Miller pointed to a water pitcher on a
table and asked Santjer: ``If Mr. Bakker said he could fit me
inside that pitcher, do you believe he could do it?''
   ``If he thinks he could, yes,'' Santjer replied.
   Bakker is accused of defrauding followers by diverting more than
$3.7 million in PTL money to fund his lavish living. He faces up to
120 years in prison and more than $5 million in fines if convicted
on all 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy.
   Special prosecutor Deborah Smith asked the judge to limit the
number of character witnesses. After Wednesday's testimony, Ms.
Smith said 37 character witnesses had been called.
   Potter said his policy is to limit lawyers to five character
witnesses in a trial.
   Bender, however, disagreed that he was calling character
witnesses.
   ``We have not put up anyone for the purpose of specifically
being a character witness,'' Bender told Potter. ``These are the
partners, judge. People who have put their money into this
ministry.''
   Potter said the defense was ``invited to put on whatever defense
you feel is appropriate.'' But he issued the warning: ``I'm not
going to sit here forever.''
   Samuel Sandifer of Wilson said he bought a partnership in 1985.
   Ms. Smith asked if he objected to the use of $265,000 in
partnership money to pay church secretary Jessica Hahn for her
silence about a sexual tryst with Bakker in 1980.
   ``I have no problem if it was spent on the Heritage Grand,
Jessica Hahn or unwed mothers,'' he said. ``It's their money to
spend the way they see fit.''
</TEXT>
