<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Arrests     09-27 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Arrests,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Military Raid Opposition Printshop; Arrest 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Forces troops raided an
opposition printshop and an advertising agency Wednesday and
arrested eight people, witnesses and opposition leaders said.
   Opposition leader Ricardo Arias Calderon said in a telephone
interview that seven people, including three women, were arrested
when soldiers raided the Sigma printing plant.
   Witnesses, who asked anonymity for fear of reprisals, said the
troops loaded printing presses and other equipment onto two trucks
and carted them away.
   Another opposition source, who insisted on anonymity, said
Valerio Arauz, owner of the Cosmos advertising agency, was also
arrested in another Defense Forces raid but gave no details.
   Both companies were doing propaganda work for the Civil
Democratic Alliance, a coalition of political parties, labor unions
and other groups opposed to Panama's military dominated government.
   The alliance, popularly known by its Spanish initials as ADOC,
is engaged in a campaign to induce people not to pay taxes,
telephone or light bills, buy lottery tickets or gamble in casinos
to pressure the government into turning power over to civilians.
   Running water and virtually all the country's other public
utilities are government-owned, and so is the lottery and gambling
casinos and the government depends heavily on them for revenue.
   Guillermo Endara, ADOC's presidential candidate, has been on a
hunger strike for the past eight days as part of the campaign.
   According to international observers, both Endara and running
mate Arias Calderon won the elections May 7, which the government
annulled a few days later claiming the opposition had committed
fraud.
   Opposition leaders have been demanding that the government
respect the May 7 election and that Gen. Antonio Noriega step down
as the Defense Forces chief and cease his de facto rule of the
country.
   Noriega was indicted February 1988 by federal grand juries in
Florida of drug trafficking and money laundering charges and the
United States has been exerting pressure, including trade and other
economic sanctions on Panama, in an effort to force him out.
   So far Noriega has refused to budge, but the sanctions have left
the government short of funds.
</TEXT>
