<FIRST>u i AM-Papandreou-Scandal 1stLd-Writethru a0811 09-27 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Papandreou-Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0811,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0811 to clear garble in header</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Greek Premier Indicted in Bank Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs of minor editing. Picks up 7th graf, `Four
of ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament indicted former Premier Andreas
Papandreou early Thursday, ordering him to stand trial before a
special court on charges he was involved in the $210 million Bank
of Crete embezzlement scandal.
   The 300-member unicameral chamber also decided four of
Papandreou's former senior Cabinet members must stand trial with
him for complicity in the scandal.
   Parliament's decision by secret ballot ended a two-day debate on
evidence presented by a parliamentary commission of inquiry that
recommended the five men be prosecuted.
   The vote was 166 for, 121 against, with two blank ballots and
six that were ruled invalid. Five deputies, including Papandreou,
were not present.
   Papandreou, 70, and the former ministers from his Panhellenic
Socialist Movement (PASOK) are accused of involvement in the
embezzlement of the bank along with its chairman, George Koskotas.
The investigative parliamentary committee alleged that during their
eight years in office, they skimmed off interest from money
deposited by state-controlled organizations.
   The indicted former ministers are Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas, who
was deputy premier and justice minister; Giorgos Petsos of
Transport and Communications; Dimitris Tsovolas of Finance, and
Panayiotis Roumeliotis of the Ministry of National Economy.
   Four of the accused appeared in Parliament to defend themselves
during the debate while Roumeliotis, a deputy of the European
parliament, sent a memorandum.
   The accused face a minimum of five years imprisonment each if
found guilty of the charges.
   The debate began in a numbed atmosphere on Tuesday morning,
hours after terrorist gunmen killed lawmaker Pavlos Bakoyannis, a
member of the conservative New Democracy party led by his
father-in-law, Constantine Mitsotakis.
   Bakoyannis' acknowledged killers, the elusive November 17
organization, charged in a proclamation that he acted as a front
when Koskotas, the bank scandal's central figure, set up a
publishing company prior to buying the Bank of Crete in 1982.
   Making one of his rare appearances in Parliament, Papandreou
told the packed chamber Wednesday that, ``I have come not to
respond to the transparent charges nor to my slanderers but to
restore the truth.''
   He pointed out that accusations he accepted bribes from Koskotas
and that he authorized the embezzlement scheme were based solely on
Koskotas' testimony.
   Papandreou accused ``local and foreign interests'' of being
behind what he called his defamation, a charge that he has made
repeatedly since the Bank of Crete scandal officially broke last
October.
   Before walking out of Parliament for ``reasons of personal
sensitivity,'' Papapandreou said he could accept political
responsibility for the scandal but not criminal charges.
   Petsos, who was not a candidate in the June election, told
Parliament Tuesday that Papandreou was responsible for accusations
he _ Petsos _ had accepted bribes from Koskotas in return for
ordering state companies to deposit funds in his bank when it began
encountering cash flow problems.
   Tsovolas also addressed Parliament on Tuesday. He claimed the
charges against him were a frameup because he refused to bow to
pressure exerted by foreign and Greek special interest groups.
   Koutsogiorgas, who was dropped by the party as a candidate in
the last election, told the lawmakers shortly before they voted
that he had not committed any wrongdoing and denied taking a $2
million bribe from Koskotas reportedly desposited in a Swiss bank
account.
   Papandreou's socialist administration was succeeded by a
conservative-leftist coalition government after national elections
in June resulted in a hung Parliament. The government has vowed to
send those involved in scandals to special courts before holding
new elections by Nov. 5.
   With the governing coalition controlling 173 seats it appeared
certain when the debate started that the accused would be indicted.
   This is the second indictment against Papandreou, who was
referred to a special court last week for allegedly instigating
widespread illegal wiretapping of friends and political opponents
while in office.
   It was the first time in Greece's history that a political
civilian leader was ordered to stand trial for alleged wrongdoing
in office.
   The special court is not expected to hear the two cases until
mid-November. This raises the possibility that Papandreou will be
running for office in the next election while under indictment.
   Koskotas fled to the United States last November after a central
bank audit at the Bank of Crete uncovered the embezzlement scheme.
   The 35-year-old fugitive, in interviews from his Salem, Mass.,
prison cell where he is fighting extradition to Greece, claimed
Papandreou blackmailed him into embezzling funds for the benefit of
his party.
   According to a constitutional amendment passed by the 1967-74
military dictatorship, government officials can only be tried by a
13-member special tribunal made up of Supreme Court judges and
Appeals Court presidents.
   The indictments must be made by Parliament, acting on the
recommendation of an inquiry conducted by deputies, in the
parliamentary period immediately following the one in which the
crimes were allegedly committed.
</TEXT>
