<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 2224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CanyonCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0799 09-27 0885</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canyon Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0799,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sightseeing Plane Crashes Near Grand Canyon; Ten Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to UPDATE with eight critical, include name of
county. SUBS grafs 9-12, `All 19...,' with three grafs to UPDATE with two
of dead identified as Modesto, Calif, councilman and wife and transport
of injured completed, details on injured. Picks up 13th graf, `Warren said...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FLS1, PN1, PN2, PN3, PN4; LaserColor PN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSAYAN, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sightseeing plane making its final
approach for landing veered into a wooded hill near the Grand
Canyon Airport on Wednesday, killing 10 people and injuring the
other 11 people aboard, eight critically.
   The aircraft's wings were sheared off by tall Ponderosa pines
but some passengers survived because the fuselage of the de
Havilland DHC-6 Twin Otter remained largely intact, said Coconino
County Sheriff Joe Richards. The two crew members were killed, he
said.
   National Park Service Ranger Paul Crawford, who was among the
first to reach the wreckage, said some of the passengers were
walking around when he arrived at the scene on a small ridge about
300 yards east of a runway.
   ``They were shellshocked. They had that empty, dazed look,'' he
said.
   The twin-engine Grand Canyon Airlines plane was on its second
flight of the day and making its final approach to the airport when
the accident occurred, said Ronald L. Warren, the airline's vice
president and general manager. He said it was cleared for landing.
   ``Preliminary reports indicate the aircraft touched down
normally on the runway, became airborne again, and veered to the
east side of the airport,'' he said.
   Federal Aviation Administration spokeswoman Elly Brekke said the
plane was about 1,500 feet down the 9,000-foot runway when it
veered to the right, then to the left and into an open space where
it descended into trees and crashed, flipping over.
   Warren said the plane had left the airport at 9 a.m. for the
one-hour scenic flight, which covers about 100 miles, and was on
schedule for its arrival when it crashed at about 9:55 a.m.
   All 19 passengers were Americans, he said. Several were from
California and many were from the East Coast. Two of the dead were
Modesto, Calif., City Councilman John Sutton and his wife, Donna,
said Modesto Mayor Carol Whiteside.
   The airport is located about five miles south of the Grand
Canyon. Ten of the injured were taken by ambulance, airplane and
helicopter to the Flagstaff Medical Center about 75 miles away.
   The injured suffered fractures, lacerations and head wounds,
said hospital spokeswoman Ann Hartman-Kolacky. Eight were listed in
critical condition and two were stable. The 11th person wasn't
brought to the hospital, apparently because the injuries weren't
that bad, she said.
   Warren said the pilot was in his mid-40s and had worked for the
airline for 4{ years. He said the pilot was also a training officer
and ``accustomed to handling unusual occurances, unusual events.
That was his job, and to teach others to handle them.''
   The co-pilot was in his mid-20s and in his first season with the
airline, Warren said. Both crew members were from Tusayan.
   The sheriff's office was to release additional information on
passengers pending notification of relatives.
   Larry Nickey, a Grand Canyon National Park Fire Department
captain, said there was fuel in the plane's cockpit area but the
wreckage did not catch fire. ``It's just good luck that we didn't
have a fire,'' Richards said.
   Nickey said firefighters cut out the plane's bottom to free a
man and a woman. He said they were the only two still alive in the
plane when he arrived.
   A National Transportation Safety Board investigation team was
not expected to reach the airport until late Wednesday. Richards
said the plane ``possibly had a power failure or may have struck a
power line.''
   A small brushfire was caused by a downed power line but it was
not known if the plane hit the line as it crashed.
   Warren said the craft, manufactured in 1975, had been owned and
operated by the airline for two years. He said the aircraft had no
history of any kind of problems.
   No cockpit voice recorder or flight data recorder was onboard
because the devices aren't required or even manufactured for that
type of aircraft, he said.
   At the time of the crash, winds were calm and visibility was not
a problem although the sky was partly cloudy, Richards said.
   Gary Mucho, NTSB regional director, said the plane normally is
configured to carry 19 passengers and two crew members.
   In 1986, a Grand Canyon Airlines plane collided with a
sightseeing helicopter inside the canyon, killing 25 people. In
August 1983, 10 people died when a sightseeing charter plan from
Las Vegas smashed into a cliff near the canyon's South Rim. A
crash-investigation report said the pilot encountered rough weather
and could not climb out of the canyon.
   In Washington, NTSB spokesman Mike Benson said the de Havilland
Twin Otter is a popular commuter plane that carries 20 passengers.
   He said the model has been involved in 77 accidents since 1962,
including 25 that killed a total of 135 people. Over the same
period, the board lists 89 accidents at the Grand Canyon, including
28 that resulted in 105 fatalities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
