<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Debate     09-27 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Debate,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settler Leaders Boycott Rabbi, Clash with Leftists in TV Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leftists and Jewish settlers wrangled
over the Palestinian issue in a nationally televised debate
Wednesday during which settlers shunned one of their rabbis for
meeting a Palestinian activist.
   The debate, on Israel Television's Moked (Focus) program, was
broadcast from Kfar Etzion in the occupied West Bank after another
settlement refused to act as host for Rabbi Menachem Froman, the
television said.
   Several settler leaders refused to sit next to Froman during the
hourlong show to show their wrath over his Sept. 19 meeting with
Feisal Husseini, a Palestinian jailed twice during the 21-month-old
Arab uprising.
   ``Husseini is responsible for the bloodshed taking place today
in the land of Israel. It's improper to shake his hand,'' said
Hanan Porat, a National Religious Party legislator.
   Israeli leftists often meet moderate Palestinians. But Froman,
of Tekoah settlement in the West Bank, is the first settler leader
to meet a Palestinian activist.
   Froman advocates a grass-roots dialogue led by religious
figures. His ideas include a state run by Israelis and Palestinians
together.
   His five-hour secret conversation with Husseini has split the
70,000-strong settler community, which mainly supports annexation
of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Militant settlers have demanded Froman be removed from his post
at Tekoah, which he has held for 11 years, or even jailed. But some
settler moderates said his initiative reflects a growing readiness
to compromise.
   ``We should fight our enemies,'' said Froman, ``but we should
make an effort to explore the possibility of this enemy ceasing to
be an enemy.''
   But some settlers accused Froman of fueling the uprising by
meeting Husseini, who they said was a rebellion organizer. At least
574 Arabs and 40 Israelis have died in the violence.
   ``After all those years ... we have some opening,'' left-wing
writer and journalist Hanoch Bartov complained, ``and people don't
want to hear, don't want to talk, don't want anything.''
   Yohanan Ben-Yakov recalled the history of his Kfar Etzion
settlement, now a religious communal settlement 10 miles southwest
of Jerusalem that first was founded in 1932 and was destroyed in
the Arab riots of 1936.
   Re-established in 1943, Kfar Etzion was besieged and destroyed
again during Israel's 1948 War of Independence, but was founded
anew in 1967.
   ``The road you walk ... leads to a binational state now and to
an Arab state tomorrow,'' insisted Bartov, who had been a guard for
Jewish convoys that brought supplies and ammunition to the area in
1948.
   ``We now have 2 million Arabs and don't know what to do about
them, and even you are seeking a way for coexistence because the
present situation is unbearable,'' he said.
   A settler in the audience countered to applause:
   ``You oppose the idea of transferring Arabs, but support
transfer of people from here and Tekoah, uprooting them from their
place, from the land.''
   Left-wing activist Avishai Grossman intervened:
   ``If we choose life and not death and suicide, we should reach
an agreement, divide the land and give the Palestinians a
possibility of national expression.''
   Israelis called in during the show to complain people like
Grossman were ready to ``present this beautiful state ... to the
Arabs on a silver plate,'' and a Palestinian phoned from Gaza to
offer a territory-for-peace exchange.
   ``I only see Jews who want peace and a state that wants peace,''
noted an Israeli woman calling from Jerusalem. ``But I don't see
the Palestinian side, so there is no point in this debate.''
</TEXT>
