<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     09-27 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0761</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A renewed fight over the teaching of
evolution and creationism in California will have a crucial test
this week in a battle that has national implications.
   The focal point is the upcoming adoption of a new science
curriculum framework, a detailed statement of what should be taught
in California and how it should be taught.
   The framework doesn't mandate course content, which is
determined by the state's 1,030 local school boards, but it sets
standards and goals that historically have been nearly as effective
as mandates.
   In 1985, California education authorities drew national
attention by successfully demanding that publishers devote more
space to evolution. The revised textbooks are now being used in
schools across the nation.
   The new proposal would strengthen the teaching of evolution.
   If adopted, it would be a ``national victory for science over
dogma,'' said Michael Hudson, western states director for the
Washington-based People for the American Way, a 270,000-member
advocacy group for civil and constitutional liberty issues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze has hailed President Bush's call for the superpowers
to destroy most of their chemical weapons, but says Washington
should go further and agree to stop making all types of poison gas.
   In his speech Tuesday to the General Assembly, Shevardnadze also
challenged the United States to join the Soviets in halting all
nuclear tests and ending the production of weapons-grade plutonium
and uranium.
   Shevardnadze's address was a rapid reply to Bush's offer, in a
speech to the assembly on Monday, to cut U.S. chemical weapons
stockpiles by 80 percent if the Soviets reduce their arsenal to the
same level.
   The Soviet envoy said Moscow is ready to join the United States
and ``radically reduce or completely destroy'' all its chemical
weapons even before an international treaty is adopted.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle called
today for talks on U.S. military bases, which many Filipinos want
removed, and said the murder of two Americans would not ``drive a
wedge'' between Washington and Manila.
   Quayle spoke a day after suspected Communist guerrillas ambushed
and killed two American civilians who were working near a U.S. base
north of the capital.
   In response, U.S. officials today banned non-essential travel
between bases by the 40,000 American troops, civilian employees and
military dependents in the Philippines.
   The attack occurred shortly before Quayle arrived to discuss
extending the leases of the six U.S. military installations, among
the largest such bases outside the continental United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A genetic abnormality that appears to play a
role in many common cancers has been solidly linked to lung cancer,
raising hopes of improved diagnosis and treatment, scientists say.
   Researchers examining lung cancer tumors discovered a series of
abnormalities in the so-called p53 anti-cancer gene, according to a
report Tuesday by Dr. John Minna of the National Cancer
Institute-Navy Medical Oncology Branch in Bethesda, Md.
   Defects in the gene also have been linked to colon cancer, to an
uncommon bone cancer called osteogenic sarcoma and to chronic
myelogenous leukemia, Minna said.
   ``Obviously, everybody is going to be looking for it in
everything else,'' Minna said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest sales spree at many leading department stores is
taking place in the boardroom rather than at the counters as some
of the nation's premier retailing names are up for grabs.
   Swanky Saks Fifth Avenue and venerable Marshall Field's became
the latest to go on the block when their parent company, BAT
Industries PLC, announced a major realignment Tuesday.
   The British conglomerate will sacrifice its American retail
holdings and hold on to its lucrative tobacco and financial
services businesses as part of a plan to defend itself from a $22
billion takeover charge led by Anglo-French financier Sir James
Goldsmith.
   Trend-setting Bloomingdale's has been on the market for several
weeks due to the financial difficulties of its debt-encumbered
owner, Campeau Corp. The Canadian holding company also might be
forced to part with other pieces of its vast retail store
collection.
   If high-fashion isn't to everyone's tastes, May Department
Stores Co. wants to sell its Caldor and Venture discount chains.
   And if this wasn't a big enough selection, several U.S. stores
owned by Australia's troubled Hooker Corp. are on the market,
including the B. Altman &amp; Co. and Bonwit Teller chains.
