<FIRST>a i PM-Monterrey-Pollution Adv06   09-27 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Monterrey-Pollution, Adv 06,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs Oct. 6 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Once-Beautiful Monterrey Attempts to Fight Pollution</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are breathing a bit
easier here in Mexico's third largest city, even though noxious
gases still spew from buses, industrial smoke stains the sky,
rivers foam with waste and bulldozers uproot trees to make room for
mansions.
   In the past months authorities in the state of Nuevo Leon have
taken the most serious steps toward preserving the eroding
environment since 1939, when the 600,000-acre Cumbres de Monterrey
National Park was established in an arc west and south of the city.
   ``Ecology protection appears to be coming into vogue in
Mexico,'' said Roberto Ortiz, a member of the Monterrey Ecology
Movement. ``There's more civic awareness and the interest of the
authorities, even by the president of Mexico, is more notable.''
   To start, the state expropriated nearly 4,500 acres of land on a
pine-covered ridge called Chipinque and turned it over to the
public. It was land that already supposedly belonged to the
national park but had been parceled out to private buyers anyway.
   Then, on Aug. 25, Nuevo Leon's first ecology preservation law
went into effect.
   The law, one of only three state environmental protection acts
in the country, promises to fine or close down polluting
industries, take polluting cars and buses off the road, create
waste dumps, improve drainage and start environmental awareness
programs.
   Local authorities were motivated by fears that Monterrey's
ecological problems could reach the proportions of Mexico City, one
of the most crowded and polluted cities in the world, said Elida
Rizzo, state ecology director.
   ``The environment just can't be ignored any longer,'' she said.
``We have do do something now or never.''
   But the sticking point for anti-pollution laws in Mexico,
however well-intended, has usually been enforcement.
   ``If the ecology law is applied with the spirit in which it was
written than there's hope,'' said Luis Sepulveda, a member of the
environmental group Long Live Chipinque. ``But if it's compromised
by politics then it'll end up like all the other laws in Mexico
that were made to be violated.''
   A chief problem is Mexico's poverty: anti-pollution efforts are
not the top priority for officials focused on creating jobs and
restarting an economy that has been stagnant for six years.
   ``We don't want there to be a witch hunt against us,'' said
Armando Rodriguez, legal director for the Monterrey Chamber of
Industry. ``If the government acts drastically it could close maybe
50 percent of the plants in Monterrey.''
   About 150 miles south of Texas' Rio Grande Valley, Monterrey is
northern Mexico's largest, most industrialized and wealthiest city.
Nearly 3 million people live in the metropolitan area, about 75
percent of Nuevo Leon's population.
   At one time it also was one of the north's most beautiful
communities, nestled in the shadows of 7,500-foot peaks and
bisected by the rippling Santa Catarina River.
   But rapid industrialization and urbanization _ Monterrey had
just 130,000 residents in 1930 _ helped turn the Santa Catarina
into a dusty channel as demands for its water increased.
   Ecology director Rizzo said Monterrey households create nearly
900,000 tons of garbage a year. Industry produces 1.5 million tons
of waste annually, much of it toxic, but the state got its first
industrial waste dump just last year.
   Mexico has had several federal environmental protection laws,
the newest 7 months old, and President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
has promised a serious fight against the problem. In Mexico City,
new rules requiring that vehicles stay off the road one working day
in five are due to go into effect Nov. 1.
   But while lead emissions are a major cause of air pollution in
the cities, cars still use leaded gasoline.
   Ecologists lauded the seizure of Chipinque.
   ``The expropriation indicates that at least an effort is being
made to save what nature gave us,'' said Sepulveda.
   The Nuevo Leon law, said Rizzo, ``gives us more power and allows
us to take quicker action.''
   The new law gives the state the power to levy fines of up to
20,000 times the daily minimum wage, now about $3.50 a day, and
prison terms of up to five years. So far no enforcement action has
been taken as the state organizes an environmental commission and
prepares impact studies.
   Two major polluters _ an oil refinery and the power authority _
are owned by the federal government, but Rizzo promises the state
law will be enforced ``against all polluters'' and will show
positive results ``within five years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Oct. 6</NOTE>
