<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-China-40Years-Mao Adv01   09-27 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-40 Years-Mao, Adv 01,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Oct. 1, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mao Tse-tung, Father of Communist China, Is Fading Into History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-China-40 Years, b0687-b0688</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mao Tse-tung, the revolutionary forefather of a
Communist China that now craves stability rather than revolution,
has become a figure of the past.
   Mao's portrait still hangs imposingly from Tiananmen Gate, just
below the rostrum from where he declared the birth of a New China
40 years ago.
   On the opposite side of Tiananmen Square his preserved body has
been viewed by more than 50 million people since the mausoleum
opened 12 years ago. Mao died Sept. 9, 1976.
   A few Mao statues still stand in provincial capitals, although a
four-story landmark at Beijing University was torn down last year.
Weathered photos of the Great Helmsman, as he was called,
occasionally adorn the walls of peasants' homes.
   But for most Chinese, Mao has little relevance in a country that
has undergone vast changes over the past 40 years.
   Under Deng Xiaoping, a prominent victim of Mao's purges, Chinese
historians have judged Mao a revolutionary hero who in his later
years made serious mistakes.
   His Great Leap Forward, the disastrous 1958 plunge into rapid
industrialization, and 1966-76 Cultural Revolution are high on a
list of blunders now attributed to him.
   The Communist Party's History Research Center concluded last
year that Mao's ideological system ``is basically divorced from the
realities in China and is thus incorrect.''
   Mao buttons appeared during democracy demonstrations this past
spring in some cities, and marching workers carried portraits of
Mao. But these gestures appeared to be more a slam at corruption
among today's bureaucrats, unlike the old revolutionaries who took
pride in their honesty and simple lives.
   More in evidence are portraits and references to the late
Premier Chou En-lai, who remains universally beloved among Chinese.
   The conservatives in power since the June crackdown on dissent
have stressed the importance of Mao's thought, as well as the ideas
of Marx and Lenin, but no attempt has been made to reappraise Mao's
role in history.
   A new movie of Mao's revolutionary exploits has come out in time
for the celebrations of the 40th anniversary of the Communist
takeover of China, but it is unlikely to inspire many to dig out
their ``Little Red Books'' of Mao quotations, as people did during
the Cultural Revolution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
