<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0142EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-27 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0834</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Andersen &amp; Co. and Price Waterhouse,
citing regulatory concerns and other problems, scrapped plans for a
merger that would have created the world's biggest accounting firm.
   A Price Waterhouse official, who asked not to be identified,
said Tuesday the key stumbling block was ``concern over the
regulatory environment,'' because the two firms represent so many
competing companies.
   However, another source close to the talks, who asked not to be
named, confirmed published reports that differences over funding of
retirement plans, the name of the combined firm and other issues
hurt the talks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. said its
board will reconvene today and may act on a buyout offer from an
unidentified suitor, widely believed to be Japan's Sony Corp.
   Trading in Columbia stock was active Tuesday for the second
consecutive session on reports that Sony had offered about $3
billion for the film and television producer. The rumored deal also
boosted the prices of stocks of other entertainment companies.
   Columbia, Sony and Coca-Cola Co., which owns 49 percent of
Columbia's stock, each declined to comment on the reported deal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC proposed the sale of its U.S.
retailing businesses as part of a restructuring the conglomerate
hoped would defeat Hoylake Investments Ltd.'s $22 billion hostile
takeover bid.
   The planned restructuring was intended to enhance the value of
BAT's stock, company chairman Patrick Sheehy said Tuesday in a
statement.
   Sir James Goldsmith, the Anglo-French financier who leads
Hoylake, said he welcomed BAT's proposal as a first step toward his
plans for breaking up the conglomerate. But Goldsmith said he would
not give up his takeover attempt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goods
accelerated 3.8 percent last month, riding brisk automobile sales
to the biggest gain since December, the government said.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday demand for durable goods,
items expected to last more than three years, totaled a seasonally
adjusted $126.7 billion after declining 2.5 percent in July. The
July figure was revised from a 1.9 percent drop reported earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers stepped up bargaining in a
last-ditch effort to increase the oil cartel's production ceiling
above 19.5 million barrels a day for the rest of 1989 without
sending prices into a freefall.
   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
twice postponed on Tuesday what was expected to be a final round of
talks to consider a new Iranian proposal. Talks were to resume
today.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Citizens and Southern Corp. and Sovran
Financial Corp. agreed on a $4.7 billion merger that will create
the nation's 14th-largest bank.
   C&amp;S, based in Atlanta, and Sovran, based in Norfolk, Va., will
have total assets of $47 billion and almost 1,000 offices in eight
states from Maryland to Florida under the agreement announced
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the World Bank, responding to
longstanding criticism, pledged that his agency would make
protection of the earth's resources a top priority in the 1990s.
   ``In the coming decade, it will be impossible to improve the
quality of life in developing and industrial countries alike unless
we do much more to conserve our global environment,'' World Bank
President Barber Conable said in his opening address Tuesday to the
annual meetings of the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Venezuela has retreated from
its demand for a 50 percent reduction in its $21 billion debt,
hoping to rejuvenate stalled negotiations with commercial banks,
officials said.
   Instead, Venezuela will offer banks ``a broad menu of options''
that will include lesser discounts in exchange for weaker
guarantees of remaining debt, Venezuelan Planning Minister Miguel
Rodriguez Fandeo, who is in charge of his country's debt-reduction
effort, said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cosmetics industry must have the option of
testing its products on animals while trying to develop alternative
methods to ensure those products are safe for consumers, an
industry spokesman said.
   Edward Kavanaugh, president of the Cosmetic, Toiletry and
Fragrance Association, said Tuesday the industry regards ``the
safety of (its) consumers as their primary responsibility and
highest priority.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished slightly higher Tuesday after a strong
rally fizzled in the final hour of trading. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials ended with a gain of 4.75 points at 2,663.94.
   The dollar declined only modestly against most currencies and
rose against Japan's yen in New York trading despite dollar-selling
by central banks.
   Bond prices finished higher.
   Wheat futures prices moved higher, while soybean prices tumbled
and corn futures were mostly lower; feeder cattle prices rose; live
hog futures gained, precious metals fell and energy prices were
mixed.
</TEXT>
