<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Milken     09-27 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milken,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Will Not File New Charges By October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will not file expanded charges
against indicted bond financier Michael Milken by the beginning of
October as it had planned, a federal prosecutor said.
   ``It will be a matter of weeks, not months,'' Assistant U.S.
Attorney John Carroll said Tuesday at a pretrial hearing in U.S.
District Court.
   Carroll had previously said charges would be filed by next week
adding to a 98-count indictment that names Milken, his brother,
Lowell, and former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader Bruce L.
Newberg.
   All three men have pleaded innocent to the indictment, which was
handed up March 29 and contains racketeering and fraud charges
stemming from Milken's activities at Drexel.
   Milken, the former head of Drexel's junk-bond division, resigned
in June after the firm agreed to plead guilty to six counts of
securities-law violations and pay a record $650 million in fines
and penalties.
   The trial of Milken and his co-defendants is scheduled to begin
in March before U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood.
</TEXT>
