<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0102EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-BAT Bjt   09-27 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Restructuring Won't Deter Bid, Goldsmith Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith says
the defensive restructuring proposed by BAT Industries PLC is
welcome but won't deter his hostile $22 billion bid for the British
conglomerate.
   BAT on Tuesday announced plans to sell its U.S. retailing
businesses, spin off other operations and buy back 10 percent of
its stock to enhance the value of its shares.
   Later in the day, Goldsmith characterized BAT's plan a ``first
step'' to the ``unbundling'' plan he has proposed through his
Hoylake Investments Ltd. takeover bid. He said Hoylake would vote
its shares in favor of it.
   The restructuring wouldn't mean he would be willing to give up
the takeover bid, which has been suspended while it overcomes U.S.
regulatory hurdles, he said.
   Analysts said BAT's proposal would enhance the British
conglomerate's stock price and was likely to be approved by
shareholders. But they said Hoylake could come back later and bid
for what is left of BAT.
   BAT said it would reshape itself to concentrate on its tobacco
business, which is a steady cash generator, and its fast-growing
financial services operations. This would be a significant
departure from its previous strategy of gradually diversifying away
from tobacco.
   Hoylake, consisting of Goldsmith, British merchant banker Jacob
Rothschild, Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer and other
investors, has proposed restructuring BAT by selling off all its
non-tobacco interests.
   BAT said the businesses it would retain were expected to account
for 80 percent of its forecast 1989 pre-tax profit of $3.2 billion.
   The U.S. retailing operations that would be sold include 46 Saks
Fifth Avenue stores and 24 Marshall Field's stores. The two chains
have combined annual sales of $2 billion.
   These and other planned, smaller disposals could fetch $2.4
billion, analysts said.
   BAT said it would create two new publicly held companies by
giving its existing stockholders shares in its British retailing
company Argos, as well as shares in a combination of its paper
companies Wiggins Teape and Appleton.
   BAT said it would buy back 10 percent of its shares, which would
cost the equivalent of $2 billion at Tuesday's closing price.
   It also pledged to ``significantly increase'' its dividends. The
total dividend for 1989 could go as high as the equivalent of 48
cents, a 49 percent increase over the previous year, BAT said.
   ``It's a useful start,'' Nigel Utley, an analyst with Laing and
Cruickshank, said of BAT's plan. ``It will enhance shareholder
value, but not necessarily enough to defeat a serious bid.''
   Andrew Mitchell, an analyst with the London investment firm
Smith New Court PLC, said, ``It does seem likely that they
(shareholders) would approve these proposals because it gives them
a bird in the hand.''
   BAT called a special Oct. 19 shareholders meeting to vote on the
measures.
   BAT shares rose the equivalent of 3 cents to close Tueday at
$13.17 on London's Stock Exchange. They were up more than 81 cents
earlier in the day.
   Hoylake has suspended its offer of $14.14 in debt securities for
each BAT share while U.S. state insurance commissioners review its
proposed change of ownership of BAT's Farmers Insurance Group Inc.
of Los Angeles.
   In a telephone interview with AP-Dow Jones News Service,
Goldsmith said, ``The point is that they've (BAT) made a first
step'' in the direction of realizing a higher share value, which is
the basis of the Hoylake argument.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
