<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChickenFight Bjt   09-27 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicken Fight, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church's-Popeyes Merger Steps Up Heat in War With The Colonel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the colonel's troops are leading
in the fried chicken war, newly merged Church's and Popeyes are
banking on marketing and franchising tactics to gain ground in the
$9 billion industry.
   Church's Fried Chicken Inc. and Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and
Biscuits _ second and third before the merger among chicken chains
behind Kentucky Fried Chicken _ will keep their names.
   But Church's old business plan _ small restaurants catering to
inner city clientele _ is undergoing a change as flashier decor,
new menu items and some price increases are in store for customers
accustomed to small orange and green buildings offering basic,
inexpensive chicken.
   The merger was completed Wednesday with a shareholders meeting
in Metarie, La., ending a process begun last year when Al Copeland,
owner of New Orleans-based Popeyes, launched an unsolicited tender
offer for San Antonio-based Church's.
   Under a February agreement, Copeland bought 86 percent of
Church's stock for $331 million, with fees and other expenses
estimated at $150 million. Church's and Popeyes will operate under
Al Copeland Enterprises with offices in New Orleans and San Antonio.
   Paul Hargett, senior vice president of finance for the merged
companies, said chicken lovers will continue to have a choice
between Church's and Popeyes, although ``there will be areas of the
country where we will have conversions'' from one chain to the
other.
   A total of 150 Church's stores were closed and are being sold
for real estate value, Hargett said.
   In an attempt to wipe away some of Church's red ink, the company
plans to emphasize franchised stores rather than company-owned
stores within the Church's division.
   ``The real crux of the matter is we have half a billion dollars
worth of debt,'' said Hargett, who was with Church's and is staying
on after the merger.
   Church's had 1,107 company stores and 361 franchises, compared
with 101 Popeyes company stores and 618 Popeyes franchises.
   By year's end, the company aims to operate 801 Church's company
stores and have 371 franchises, while running 150 Popeyes company
stores and 643 franchises.
   Church's stores averaged an annual sales volume of $420,000
each, far short of the $750,000 annual sales volume averaged by
Popeyes stores.
   ``So we are concentrating a lot on these stores that fit the
demographics of the Popeyes profile,'' Hargett said.
   What is that profile?
   A proxy statement to shareholders says, ``Popeyes restaurants
have experienced significantly higher per unit sales in suburban
and middle-income urban locations than have Church's restaurants.''
   Meanwhile, Church's has targeted ``primarily urban blue collar
customers, including those in the ethnic and minority segments of
the population,'' the proxy states.
   The company is experimenting with a new Church's look that
includes more space and brighter colors. Menu changes also are in
order. Church's already has introduced a new type of biscuit and
will be selling a ``new Southern-style fried chicken.''
   Also, according to the proxy statement, the past Church's policy
of ``big pieces, little prices'' was ineffective, contributing to a
decline in revenue. Consumers can expect a backing away from that
strategy as Church's stops buying larger chickens and tries to
reduce its per-piece cost. It also plans to raise some prices.
   Not everyone is predicting a smooth ride for Church's and
Popeyes.
   Ernie Renaud, former president and chief executive officer of
Church's, said placating Popeyes franchisees will be the biggest
obstacle.
   ``You expect to be given 110 percent by the franchiser to help
make sure you succeed,'' Renaud said. ``It's like going to a doctor
and finding out he's got too many patients and can't do right by
you ... How he (Copeland) handles his franchisees is going to be
the key to his success.''
   Howard Hansen, an analyst with Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. who follows
the fast-food industry, said that while Church's and Popeyes are
settling in to their new relationship, arch-rival Kentucky Fried
Chicken will continue opening stores.
   Catching Kentucky Fried Chicken, a unit of Pepsico Inc., will be
a long race for Copeland Enterprises, Hansen said. ``It's like
Burger King trying to catch up with McDonald's.''
   Greg Reynolds, KFC's vice president for public affairs, said he
is hesitant to criticize competitors but proclaims that his company
plans to stay on top.
   Kentucky Fried Chicken feels a bigger threat from more
mainstream fast-food companies, such as McDonald's, which are
introducing new chicken dishes, he said.
   ``Clearly the market for chicken is out there.''
</TEXT>
