<FIRST>r f PM-BAT-MarshallField     09-27 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT-Marshall Field,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Management Buyout Offer Planned for Chicago Retailer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The management of Marshall Field and Co. will bid
to buy the department store chain, which would be sold under a
major restructuring proposed by its British parent, the chain's
chairman said.
   Philip B. Miller said Tuesday that management intends to make
``an aggressive buyout offer'' in response to the announcement by
London-based BAT Industries PLC that it will sell its U.S.
retailing operations in an effort to fight a hostile takeover by
financier Sir James Goldsmith.
   Field's chairman and chief executive officer said in a statement
that management will make a ``competitive offer which will meet the
fiduciary requirements of BAT's board, ensuring fair value to BAT
shareholders.'' He did not place a dollar value on it.
   Marshall Field has 24 stores in Illinois, Ohio, Wisconsin and
Texas that employ 13,000 people. The chain opened its flagship
store in Chicago in 1856 as one of the nation's first and most
successful department stores.
   The company is projecting record sales and earnings for 1989,
Miller said in a statement.
   He said the chain posted its first $1 billion sales year in in
1988 with a profit of $83 million.
   Under a management buyout, Miller said the company ``would
continue to be operated at the highly productive level that has
contributed to the success of the management team in the last five
years.''
   BAT announced earlier Tuesday that it planned to sell its U.S.
retailing operations _ including Saks Fifth Avenue, Marshall
Field's and two regional retailers _ and concentrate on its tobacco
and financial services businesses.
</TEXT>
