<DOCNO> AP890927-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Tied-Aid     09-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tied-Aid,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Votes To Strip Treasury of Loan Authority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee has voted to strip
the Treasury Department's authority over low-interest loans and
loan guarantees to Third World countries for buying high-tech goods
or construction services from U.S. companies.
   On a 28-22 vote Tuesday, the committee effectively turned that
authority over to the Export-Import Bank as part of a bill raising
its ``tied-aid'' war chest by $200 million and imposing new
environmental conditions on U.S. approval of World Bank and
International Monetary Fund aid to underdeveloped countries.
   U.S. manufacturers have complained that the Treasury _ in its
effort to deter the use of such tied-aid packages by other other
countries, chiefly Japan and France _ has been too tight-fisted in
approving loans and loan guarantees to finance their exports.
   As a result, the American companies claim they are losing out on
$2 billion to $4 billion a year in foreign contracts.
   The bill also authorizes $400 million over the next five years
for the multinational Inter-American Development Bank to support
loans in Latin America and $150 million for a special IMF account
that subsidizes interest payments on loans owed by very poor
countries, especially in Africa.
   Under the legislation, which was approved by the committee on a
voice vote, the U.S. representatives to the World Bank and IMF
would be prohibited from approving loans for Third World projects
without an environmental assessment first.
   The environmental measure was modified Tuesday to allow for some
exceptions after the Treasury Department threatened to recommend a
veto of the bill unless it was given some discretion.
</TEXT>
