<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-Europe     09-27 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Europe,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Official: U.S. Need Not Fear `Fortress Europe' Trading Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should not fear a ``Fortress
Europe'' when the 12-nation European Economic Community forms a
single trading market in 1993, a European Community official said.
   The United States and other European Community trade partners
will benefit considerably when the Western European nations unify
into one, $4 trillion market with 320 million consumers, said Willy
de Clercq, a member of the European Parliament and chairman of its
committee for external relations.
   U.S. business interests fear that ``local content'' regulations
requiring many goods to be produced in European Community nations
and proposed technical standards for imports could result in
barriers against U.S. products and turn Europe into a trading
fortress.
   ``These fears are unjustified,'' de Clercq said Tuesday at a
Washington-Brussels trade forum. ``Far from creating a Fortress
Europe, the creation of an internal market will create significant
benefits for our trading partners.''
   He said the European Community 1992 internal markets scheme,
which goes into effect Jan. 1, 1993, ``will offer considerable
opportunities to non-community interests'' selling to the European
Community.
   Those would include, he said, uniform standards and procedures;
increased investment opportunities; and non-discrimination against
foreign companies with European Community ties.
   As for concerns that a self-absorbed European Community will
become more protectionist, de Clercq said ``It would not be in our
own interests to go down this road.''
   He noted that the European Community relies much more on trade
than the United States or Japan. The European Community derives 13
percent of its industrial and commercial goods from imports, while
it has captured 24 percent of the world's export trade.
   By comparison, the United States has 8 percent of the world
export market; the Japanese 16 percent, he said.
   Tom Duesterberg, the assistant commerce secretary for
international economic policy, said the United States welcomed the
European calls but still had major concerns over some provisions of
European Community 1992.
   The United States still is worried about standards, testing and
certification procedures for U.S. goods and by local content
provisions on the auto and broadcasting industries, Duesterberg
said.
   France is lobbying for tough mandatory quotas on
foreign-produced TV programs and the U.S. entertainment industry
fears it could suffer a drastic cutback in its multibillion-dollar
export business to Europe.
   The European Community will adopt a final guidelines on TV
program content next month, and if France prevails ``That would be
a very serious problem,'' Duesterberg said.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills earlier this year said a
tough European Community quota system on television would give the
Bush administration no choice but to consider sanctions under U.S.
trade laws.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 0854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BAT-US     09-27 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT-US,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Industries Should Have Plenty of Potential Buyers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-BAT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SCHREINER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wrter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC likely will lure
plenty of potential buyers for Saks Fifth Avenue, Marshall Field's
and its other retailers, to be sold in a major restructuring aimed
at thwarting an unwanted takeover attempt.
   The British conglomerate has pumped money into its retailing
businesses for renovation and expansion, said Eugene Russell, a
spokesman for Louisville-based BATUS Inc., BAT's U.S. holding
company.
   ``Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's are premier retailers
and Ivey's and Breuners are strong regional companies with great
potential,'' he said. ``And during the course of this recent
period, there has been unusually strong interest in these
properties.''
   BAT, trying to fight off a $22 billion bid from a group led by
financier Sir James Goldsmith, said Tuesday it planned to sell its
U.S. retailing operations and concentrate on its tobacco and
financial services businesses.
   Shareholders will vote on the proposed restructuring at an Oct.
19 meeting.
   Saks, which has 46 stores in 18 states, had sales of $1.2
billion in 1988. The chain, which has about 10,000 employees, is
undergoing a $360 million renovation and expansion program.
   Marshall Field's, with 24 stores in Illinois, Ohio, Wisconsin
and Texas, had sales of $1 billion in 1988, Russell said. The chain
employs 13,000 people, and its flagship store in Chicago is in the
midst of a $105 million restoration.
   After BAT revealed its intentions, the management of Marshall
Field &amp; Co. said they intend to try to buy the department store
chain. Philip B. Miller, chairman and chief executive officer of
the chain, said Tuesday that management intends to make ``an
aggressive buyout offer.''
   Ivey's, headquartered in Charlotte, N.C., has 24 stores in North
Carolina, South Carolina and Florida. The chain employs 5,000
people, said Russell, who did not provide sales figures.
   Breuners has more than 50 furniture stores and rental outlets in
California, Arizona and Nevada and employs about 1,200 people,
Russell said. He did not have sales figures for Breuners, either.
   BAT's plan would create two new publicly held companies by
giving its existing shareholders shares in its British retailing
company Argos, as well as shares in a combination of its paper
companies, London-based Wiggins Teape and Appleton.
   Appleton, headquartered in Appleton, Wis., is the world's
largest producer of carbonless paper and the nation's top producer
of thermal paper for facsimile machines, Russell said. The company,
with 3,600 employees, has eight plants in four states _ Wisconsin,
Ohio, Pennsyvlania and Michigan. It had sales of $844 million in
1988.
   BAT, originally called British-American Tobacco, is the world's
biggest tobacco company. It will retain Louisville-based Brown &amp;
Williamson Tobacco Corp., the nation's third-largest tobacco
concern.
   ``The company remains deeply committed to its Kentucky roots,
and the reshaped BAT Industries will allow B&amp;W to continue to grow
and flourish,'' Russell said.
   Brown &amp; Williamson, which employs about 5,000 people, had total
sales of nearly $2.8 million in 1988, Russell said. The company has
production facilities in Macon, Ga., and leaf processing facilities
in Wilson, N.C. Its cigarette brands include Kool, Viceroy and
Barclay.
   The cigarette company, which claims about 11 percent of the U.S.
market, holds 25 percent of the Japanese import market and 36
percent of the newly opened South Korean import market, Russell
said.
   BAT anticipates more rapid growth from its financial services
division.
   BAT's Farmers Insurance Group Inc., headquartered in Los
Angeles, is the nation's third largest personal lines insurer,
operating in 27 states in the western half of the United States.
   Russell said tobacco and financial services are ``generators of
cash and have robust qualities.''
   He said it was ``premature'' to comment on how BAT's
restructuring will affect BATUS, which has about 100 employees in
Louisville.
</TEXT>
