<DOCNO> AP890927-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-27 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened lower today, after
posting modest gains in the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which gained 4.75
points on Tuesday, was down 4.18 points at 2,659.76 at 10 a.m. on
Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by more than 2 to 1 among
those listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 272 issues up,
647 down and 464 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.50 million shares, up from
18.24 million shares at the same point in Tuesday's session.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.20 at 191.27.
   On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.04 at 382.23.
   The market appeared to be weighed down by International Business
Machines Corp.'s announcement this morning that it expects earnings
for the current quarter to come in below the current range of
security analysts' estimates.
   IBM's announcement came before the market opened, and its stock
fell 5| to 111~ in the early going.
   Among other early active issues, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
was down \ at 42], General Electric was down [ at 55] and Eastman
Kodak was down \ at 46~.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained 4.75
points to finish at 2,663.94, after climbing more than 21 points
during the session.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a margin of about 5 to
3 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks,
with 740 issues up, 634 down and 556 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 158.35 million shares, up from 121.13
million in Monday's session.
