<FIRST>r f PM-Checchi-Northwest     09-27 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Checchi-Northwest,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Agrees to Cut KLM Interest in Northwest Buyout, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi has
agreed to cut KLM Royal Dutch Airlines' stake in the Northwest
Airlines buyout to ease government concerns about foreign airline
influence over Northwest, according to a published report today.
   The Minneapolis-based Northwest has agreed to a Transportation
Department demand to reduce a $400 million investment by KLM and to
remove KLM from the board of NWA Inc., the airline's parent
company, The Wall Street Journal reported, quoting an unidentified
source.
   The Star Tribune, quoting unidentified government sources,
reported Wednesday that Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner has
determined that KLM's existing $400 million equity stake exceeds
federal regulations, which restrict foreign ownership to 25 percent
of a U.S. carrier.
   According to The Wall Street Journal, Checchi has agreed to cut
the KLM stake by $225 million, to $175 million.
   The cutback in the KLM investment would reduce the Dutch
airline's percentage of the $700 million in cash equity raised for
the buyout from 57 percent to 25 percent, the Journal said. KLM has
only a 5 percent voting stake in Northwest because its stake is
mostly in non-voting preferred stock.
   Skinner and Checchi met Friday to discuss Skinner's review of
Checchi's $3.65 billion takeover of NWA Inc. Neither Skinner nor
Checchi has commented publicly on the talks.
   Northwest spokesman Kevin Whalen said Wednesday the airline
would have no comment on the published reports until the
Transportation Department releases its findings.
   In his first public appearance since acquiring Northwest this
summer, Checchi Tuesday night made no reference to the
Transportation Department review other than to say, ``Sam Skinner
and I are becoming great friends.''
   In a speech to Minnesota businesspeople, Checchi predicted
dramatic growth for the airline and outlined his philosophy.
   ``All the assets are in place here for success,'' Checchi told
900 members of the Minnesota Chamber of Commerce at the group's
annual meeting. ``I look at Northwest as absolutely the culminating
challenge of my career.''
   Checchi, who has maintained a low profile since the acquisition,
has spent the past several months meeting Northwest employees at
the company headquarters in Eagan, a Minneapolis suburb. He said he
soon would ``embark on a worldwide tour of Northwest employees'' in
an effort to foster employee-management relations.
   ``I really do believe that people are our most important
assets,'' he said. ``I want our employees to have the same sense of
satisfaction from their work that I've had from mine in the last 15
years.''
   Checchi's group, Wings Holdings Ltd., bought NWA for $3.65
billion or $121 a share. He predicted that bank debt for the
acquisition would be paid off in ``between five and six years.''
   ``Northwest is going to grow dramatically in the Pacific ... and
domestically,'' Checchi predicted, noting that among the company's
``hidden assets'' is a $1.5 billion equity value in its aircraft.
   American airline companies, Checchi said, are basically the
same. He said NWA under his reign will surpass the others because
of its commitment to customer satisfaction.
   ``The airline industry is the industry in which the American
people have the least confidence of any industry in the U.S. ...
Providing superior service is the only way to differentiate
yourself,'' he said.
   Checchi, who holds an MBA from Harvard Business School, was
formerly associated with the Marriott Hotels and Walt Disney Co.
</TEXT>
