<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GM-Jaguar-Ford     09-27 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-Jaguar-Ford,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: GM Was on Verge of Jaguar Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. short-circuited a plan earlier
this month for General Motors Corp. to acquire 30 percent of Jaguar
plc by moving to buy some of the British luxury carmaker's stock,
the Wall Street Journal reported today.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources at Ford and GM, said
Ford announced it was seeking to buy 15 percent of Jaguar's stock
shortly after it got wind of the deal top GM executives were
discussing with Jaguar.
   Executives at GM and the financially troubled Jaguar are
reassessing their positions in light of the Ford move, the Journal
said.
   GM spokesman Jack Harned said the company had no comment on the
Journal report.
   Ford's announcement on Sept. 19 that it was buying the Jaguar
stock came in reaction to an anticipated bid by GM for all or part
of Jaguar, but Ford officials didn't know that the two companies
were on the verge of announcing the deal in which GM would own 30
percent of Jaguar, according to the newspaper.
   Ford spokesman Rex Greenslade said the company had heard rumors
for months that a variety of companies, including GM, were
interested in a stake in Jaguar. But Ford did not react solely to a
GM bid for part of Jaguar.
   ``We felt that we wanted to do this to show that we felt this
was a very good fit between the companies,'' Greenslade said. Talks
between Ford and Jaguar had gone on before Ford's announcement, he
added, and none have been scheduled since.
   Jaguar officials called Ford's announcement unwelcome.
   ``It's obvious that companies the size of Jaguar cannot and will
not survive in the long term,'' Greenslade said. ``They're going to
have to have strategic associations.''
   Ford has no luxury performance car in its lineup that would
compete with Jaguar. GM markets the Cadillac Allante in the market
segment. Ford has confirmed that it is talking with the Swedish
carmaker and truckmaker Saab-Scania AB.
</TEXT>
