<DOCNO> AP890927-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1226EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-OPEC 3rdLd-Writethru f0079 09-27 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0079,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Decide to Boost Ceiling, Algeria Balks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Kuwait also saying it will
not recognize a quota; picks up 8th graf pvs `The disarray ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers today struck a deal to boost their
production ceiling a modest amount in the final months of the year,
but two cartel members indicated they would not go along.
   Nigerian Oil Minister Rilwanu Lukman, president of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, said the countries
would lift their supply cap by a million barrels a day to 20.5
million barrels.
   Algeria declared the move illegal and Kuwait, who has been
openly exceeding its production limit, said it had made no
commitments.
   The head of the Algerian delegation, who demanded anonymity,
said, ``It is something that Algeria doesn't associate itself
with.''
   ``It is a decision that is illegal,'' he said immediately after
the ministers' final round of talks at a luxury Geneva hotel.
   ``As far as we can see, it has kind of poor thinking behind
it,'' he said.
   Kuwaiti oil minister Sheik Ali Khalifa al-Sabah said his country
would continue not to recognize any restrictions on its output. He
said Kuwait had made ``no commitments either legal or moral to hold
down production.''
   The disarray came in the fifth day of talks held to try to come
up with an acceptable production strategy in the final quarter of
the year.
   The ministers were at odds throughout the meeting over how much
they could raise any production ceiling without sending prices
sliding.
   Algerian Oil Minister Sadek Boussena, who left the meeting
Monday to return to Algiers for a legislative meeting, had pressed
for retaining the current ceiling of 19.5 million barrels a day.
   He had said the cartel should concentrate on bringing prices up
about a dollar to the cartel's benchmark of $18 a barrel.
   Others argued the market was strong enough to absorb the
additional supply.
   The ministers failed to come up with a formula for meeting some
countries' demands for a higher share of OPEC's production.
   ``We solved a good deal,'' Iraqi Oil Minister Issam al-Chalabi
said before the meeting. ``Maybe we'll leave something for
November.''
   The ministers were scheduled to meet in late November to plan
their production strategy for 1990.
   The officials had spent the day studying a surprise Iranian
proposal to see if it could form the basis of a compromise. But
they deferred taking any action on the plan.
   In its plan, Iran proposed the production ceiling be pegged
above 20.5 million barrels a day to take care of demands by Kuwait,
the United Arab Emirates, Gabon, Ecuador and Qatar. It could go as
high as 21.5 million barrels to cover them.
   ``It's a good proposal,'' said a senior Kuwaiti delegate, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   As sketched by Iranian delegates, their formula would give all
13 countries larger individual quotas, meaning they could produce
more crude in the last quarter than now. But Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates, Gabon, Ecuador and Qatar would be given bigger
percentage shares.
   Each country is assigned an individual quota, based on its
percentage share of the total. For example, Saudi Arabia, the
cartel's No. 1 producer, has nearly a 25 percent share of the total
supply.
   Before the latest proposal, the members were considering a Saudi
plan to push production up to 20.5 million barrels a day, according
to a delegate. All countries would share proportionately in the
increase.
   OPEC ministers have been meeting since Saturday to find a way to
raise their output ceiling in the last quarter without sending
prices tumbling. The talks had been on the verge of collapse Monday
evening.
   Crude prices have held fairly steady in recent months, despite
reports that some members have been overproducing.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the key American brand, closed up 7 cents
on Tuesday at $19.53 a 42-gallon barrel, well above the cartel's
benchmark $18 a barrel.
   OPEC members are: Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran,
Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
