<DOCNO> AP890927-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CementImports     09-27 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cement Imports,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Cement Manufacturers Cry Foul Over Mexican Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of seven cement manufacturers have
complained to federal officials that Mexican competitors unfairly
are selling cement in the United States at cut-rate prices.
   The manufacturers committee, made up of producers in Texas,
Arizona, New Mexico and Florida, said it filed petitions Tuesday
with the U.S. International Trade Commission and the U.S. Commerce
Dept. asking for duties on imports of gray portland cement large
enough to eliminate any price differential.
   ``Dumping cement in U.S. markets cannot be allowed to
continue,'' said Clarence C. Comer, chief executive of
Houston-based Southdown Inc. and head of the manufacturers group,
which claims the U.S. price for the imported cement is about
one-half what Mexicans are charged.
   ``If we lose out to fair competition from Mexico, so be it,''
Comer said. ``Our investigation to date, however, convinces us that
the Mexicans' success in U.S. markets is due to dumping and not to
any other factor.''
   Since 1983, the group said, seven cement plants have closed in
Arizona, New Mexico and Texas with two more closing in Florida.
   Last year Mexican imports accounted for 14 percent of the market
in the three border states and 22 percent of the Florida market,
the group said.
   ``Mexican producers continue to build export-oriented capacity
aimed at American markets,'' Comer said. ``We don't want to see
imports stopped, or to deter fair competition, but when dumping of
cement hurts U.S. companies and workers, the time has come to
enforce United States laws against unfair import practices.''
   Besides Southdown, the manufacturers are Box Crow Cement Co.,
Midlothian, Texas; Florida Crushed Stone Co., Brooksville, Fla.;
Gifford-Hill and Co., Dallas; Ideal Basic Industries, Denver;
Phoenix Cement Co., Phoenix; and Texas Industries Inc., Dallas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
