<FIRST>r f PM-TBS-Audubon 1stLd-Writethru   09-27 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TBS-Audubon, 1st Ld-Writethru,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>TBS Loses Sponsors For `World Of Audubon' Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS lead to clarify</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsor dropouts nearly placed the ``World of
Audubon'' specials on the TBS SuperStation on the endangered list,
but Turner Broadcasting System has come to the rescue.
   Sponsors, including Sears, Ford, Exxon, Citicorp, Michelin and
New York Life, pulled their advertisements before the show aired
Sunday night because of a program about trees last weekend that
drew criticism from the logging industry.
   The special, ``Ancient Forests: Rage Over Trees,'' about the
destruction of Pacific Northwest forests, was shown Sunday night
without sponsorship. It is to be shown again Saturday, Monday and
Oct. 16.
   Turner Broadcasting System officials said Tuesday that the cable
TV network will stand by the show through its new three-year
contract.
   TBS would not say how much it lost in advertising revenue when
the sponsors withdrew their commercials, but the National Audubon
Society said TBS lost $250,000 and the program's overall corporate
sponsor, the Stroh Brewery Co., earlier withdrew about $600,000 in
production money for the series.
   Chris Palmer, executive producer of the program and vice
president of National Audubon Society productions, said Stroh had
asked him to change his film before it withdrew. He said loggers
had boycotted Stroh beer in August.
   ``We did hear from the logging industry. They were asking for us
to ensure the content was accurate,'' said Stroh spokeswoman Lacey
Logan, denying that a boycott was called. ``Anytime there is a
grassroots level campaign, there are lots of different emotions.''
   Gerry Hogan, president of entertainment networks for TBS, said
in a statement that the company would continue its support of the
program ``despite pressure from special-interest groups.''
</TEXT>
