<SECOND>PM-BAT,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arizona Insurance Department Asserts Jurisdiction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Insurance Department said today it
will require a formal hearing and review before deciding whether
Hoylake Investment Limited can acquire Farmers Insurance Company of
Arizona as part of its attempt to take over BAT Industries PLC.
   BAT has been resisting the $21 billion takeover attempt by Sir
James Goldsmith and co-investors in Hoylake, and today's decision
will buy the company additional time.
   ``While we continue to believe the Insurance Department legally
lacks jurisdiction to consider the Hoylake proposal, we're
confident that the Department will ultimately approve it,'' said
Jack LaSota, a Hoylake attorney.
   Hoylake has said it plans to sell the Farmers Insurance unit to
Axa Midi Assurances if it acquires BAT, aand state Insurance
Director Susan Gallinger said in a formal order today that the
proposed sale to Axa Midi would be considered at the same time as
the proposed acquisition by Hoylake.
   She set a hearing for Oct. 16.
   Hoylake and BAT, both of which are headquartered in England,
have been battling in states across the United States over Farmers
units that now belong to BAT's BATUS Inc. subsidiary.
   Lawyers for BAT, formerly British American Tobacco, have used
many of the same arguments that they opposed earlier when its was
Farmers' turn to resist a BATUS takeover attempt.
   Hoylake announced its takeover intentions on July 11.
   Farmers, Arizona's second-largest auto and home insurer and
fifth-largest commercial insurer, wrote $270 million in direct
premiums in Arizona last year.
</TEXT>
