<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Skinner     09-27 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Skinner,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Wants To Stay Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the striking Eastern Airlines pilots
Wednesday said they are ``appalled'' at Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner's opposition to government intervention into the
strike.
   Skinner disclosed Tueday he has written to Senate Majority
Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, and called a proposed
congressionally mandated committee ``entirely inappropriate.'' Such
a move ``can only hinder the work of the bankruptcy court,''
Skinner wrote.
   The Senate may consider a version of a House of Representatives
bill passed in March that would force President Bush to establish
an emergency board, or blue-ribbon commission, to investigate and
make recommendations on the dispute between Eastern and its three
major labor unions.
   ``We urge the members of the Senate, who have followed the
course of this struggle for almost seventh months and who
understand both the issues and will of the voters, to look beyond
the limited vision of the Secretary's letter,'' said Skip Copeland,
recently elected to head the pilots local.
   Copeland said 1988 Department of Transportation and Federal
Aviation Adminstration probes of Eastern operations were ``fatally
flawed whitewashes.'' Copeland said the pilots union had withheld
criticism of the FAA probe, which Copeland said found safety
deficiencies that could have warranted shutting down Eastern,
because it was hoped promised safety improvements and cooperation
would save the airline.
   A new investigation would examine past practices. Current
Eastern operations, he said, are ``on a very thin margin of
safety.''
   ``They're trotting out the old red herring of safety,'' company
spokesman Robin Matell said. ``It's an obvious act of desperation
by the pilots union in response to Eastern's ability to rebuild
successfully despite ALPA's efforts to shut the airline down.''
   Eastern's three unions went on strike March 4, and Eastern filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization five days later. Eastern
is trying to rebuild without the unions and says it will emerge
from bankruptcy at about two-thirds its prestrike size.
   Copeland said Eastern's rebuilding plan is ``a controlled
liquidation that signals the demise of a once-proud company'' and
he said despite Skinner's comments, he didn't think President Bush
could ``in good conscious'' veto the bill if passed by the Senate.
   Skinner said that while the Bush administration regrets that the
strike wasn't resolved by mediation, it believes government should
not take over in management-labor disputes. He also noted that
Eastern is in the jurisdiction of federal bankruptcy court.
   Skinner told Mitchell the court is the proper place to handle
the dispute unless it threatens safety, in which case the DOT would
get involved. He argued that Congress has ``no appropriate role''
and said he would urge Bush to veto the bill if it is passed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
