<FIRST>u f PM-PostalService 1stLd-Writethru f0141 09-27 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postal Service, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0141,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Charges Company Tried to Win Contract by ``Buying'' Official</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `At Voss' ..., to CORRECT attribution from
Reedy to Valder.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dallas company tried to win a $400 million
contract to build mail-sorting equipment by ``buying'' a member of
the U.S Postal Service's board of governors, a federal prosecutor
charged today.
   In opening statements at the fraud and conspiracy trial of
Recognition Equipment Inc. and two of its top officers, Assistant
U.S. Attorney Joseph Valder said the firm's chief executive
officer, William Moore, became ``obsessed'' with getting a major
postal contract.
   In an attempt to achieve his goal, said the prosecutor, Moore
and his co-defendant, REI Vice President for Marketing Robert
Reedy, sought help from Peter Voss, a member of the postal
service's board of governors.
   At Voss' urging, REI hired a small consulting firm headed by
Detroit-area businessman John Gnau, Valder said. REI arranged to
pay $325,000 to Gnau's firm in little more than a year, the
prosecutor said, with a portion of the proceeds being funneled to
Voss.
   ``This case is not about aggressive-but-legal business
practices,'' said Valder. ``It's about the fact that'' Moore and
Reedy ``cheated ... they lied ... they stole ... they covered up.''
   ``The case is about Moore and Reedy blocking government
functions by deceit,'' Valder said.
   Moore and Reedy were involved in a scheme to ``defraud the
government by buying a governor,'' he said.
   Voss, who headed Ronald Reagan's 1980 Ohio presidential
campaign, received a four-year sentence in 1986 after pleading
guilty to taking an illegal gratuity and to expense account fraud.
   Gnau, who headed Reagan's 1980 Michigan campaign, was sentenced
to three years for conspiracy and paying an illegal $2,500 gratuity
to Voss.
   The case is being heard by U.S. District Court Judge George
Revercomb because attorneys for REI, Moore and Reedy waived their
clients' constitutional right to a jury trial.
   Jenny Haynes Barker, REI vice president, said the case is so
complicated that it would best be handled by a judge.
   If convicted, Moore and Reedy would each face a maximum of 33
years' imprisonment and $1.5 million in fines. Both men are on paid
leaves of absence. They have maintained their innocence and say
they plan to return to their former jobs if exonerated.
   A seven-count indictment in October 1988 followed an
investigation by the U.S. Postal Inspection Service and a federal
grand jury into details of competition for a computer automation
contract with the postal service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
