<DOCNO> AP890927-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1617EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Spending-Music Adv01   09-27 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spending-Music, Adv 01,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Oct. 1 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Right Tunes Can Help Merchants Ring Up Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Spending Junkies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget elevator music.
   Teen-agers hanging out near the Merry-Go-Round clothing store in
the Eastlake Square Mall in Tampa, Fla., weren't bopping to a
homogenized version of the Who or synthetic Bruce Springsteen.
   The piped-in music featured original recordings of hip rhythms
by Paula Abdul, Bobby Brown, Taylor Dayne, Jody Watley and others.
   The teens' enthusiasm for the sounds caused a temporary tiff
between Merry-Go-Round and the mall's management, who worried that
a horde of teen-agers could cause problems, recalls Kristy Collar,
a troubleshooter for the retailer.
   The situation, which has been sorted out, is an extreme example
of what can happen when retailers or restaurants play the right
music: Tunes _ not just merchandise and food _ can attract
potential customers.
   Merry-Go-Round Enterprises Inc. is one of many clients of AEI
Music Network Inc., a firm that designs what it calls
``marketing-oriented music profiles'' that appeal to particular
customers.
   ``Our approach to the entertainment medium of music is to use
music as a marketing tool,'' says AEI President Michael J. Malone,
a former financial analyst who came up with the concept for the
company after helping a friend whose cassette player in his
restaurant kept going on the blink.
   By way of explanation, Malone says the profile for Victoria's
Secret, the intimate apparel store owned by specialty retailer
Limited Inc., calls for elegant, classical melodies that wouldn't
be out of place in a boudoir.
   Limited's Express shops pipe in European pop to complement the
international flair Express tries to get across to customers
seeking entry to the forefront of world fashion. The retailer's
flagship chain prefers a mixture of top 40, jazz, contemporary
tunes and light rock 'n roll to make the buttoned-down, blazered
set feel at home.
   Retailers changing their merchandise mix might need a face lift
for their musical profiles. When safari wear seemed to be going out
of style Gap Inc.'s Banana Republic chain switched from Fantasy
Island-type melodies and bird calls to contemporary jazz, says
Malone.
   Marketing experts say music is an important element of the
atmosphere within stores and elsewhere. Tailoring an
establishment's ambience to a specific target market can work
wonders for business.
   ``It's very clear that music affects behavior, especially in
terms of shopping behavior,'' says Ronald E. Milliman, a marketing
professor at Western Kentucky University.
   Research on the subject is limited, Milliman says, but it is
believed that music can improve store image, make employees
happier, reduce stress and stimulate purchases.
   A poll by the Gallup Organization Inc. done for AEI said 91
percent of store patrons surveyed thought music had an effect on
their actions. The respondents said music could induce good moods
and boost energy levels. AEI contends that customers who feel
comfortable in stores might spend more time there and wind up
spending more money.
   AEI, which claims to have pioneered the idea of programming
original artist music, is regarded as the leader in the field. The
privately-held Seattle company supplies sound for most major
restaurant chains and scores of retailers, hotels, banks and other
places where music is heard. It also handles in-flight music for
numerous airlines.
   Besides offering advice on which music would suit a specific
audience, AEI helps with selection and installation of sound
systems.
   But most important, it provides a constantly updated collection
of tapes that fits into various categories ranging from ``smooth
savoir faire'' featuring swing, blues and sultry numbers, to ``hot
&amp; hip,'' a mixture of current pop favorites, light funk, dance,
reggae and foreign hits.
   To preserve the mood during special seasons like Christmas, a
dash of traditional fare can be blended into the mix.
   ``People would get suicidal if you blasted White Christmas at
them all day,'' says Malone.
   The music on AEI's tapes are original recordings, not special
arrangements made just for the tapes. AEI negotiates with artists
to use their work and works closely with the distribution arms of
record companies.
   A casual listener might think they're hearing a commercial-free
radio station instead of an AEI tape. Playing radio stations in
stores is a marketing no-no because competitors' ads might be heard.
   ``Music can have a great impact on a comfort zone,'' says
Malone, referring to how an atmosphere affects a listener.
   Obviously, not everyone has the same taste in music.
   So, next time you're blasted out of a trendy boutique by
ear-piercing rock with a chest-pummeling beat, consider this: Maybe
you're not the type of customer that the retailer expects to shop
there.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
