<DOCNO> AP890927-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1523EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SugarCaneSuit     09-27 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sugar Cane Suit,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit: Cane Cutters Underpaid $30 Million in Six Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar cane harvesters have filed a
lawsuit claiming they have been underpaid by more than $30 million
during the past six seasons by south Florida growers.
   The lawsuit, filed Monday as an amended class-action to include
more than 10,000 workers who have worked for six companies since
1982, alleges that sugar cane harvesters were not given proper
credit for the amount of cane cut.
   The original lawsuit was filed in Palm Beach County Circuit
Court in August on behalf of four Jamaican farmworkers. In a
separate action Monday, the growers filed a motion to dismiss the
original lawsuit.
   Defendants named in the suit are the Sugar Cane Growers
Cooperative, Atlantic Sugar Association, United States Sugar Corp.,
Okeelanta Corp., Osceola Farms and Cane Contractors.
   Under the federal government's guest-worker program, growers can
hire foreign cane cutters if the companies can show there are not
enough U.S. citizens willing to work for the minimum task rate of
$5.30 for each ton cut. Growers then submit to several state
employment centers ``clearance orders'' that explain the work, the
rate of pay and how much work is expected each day.
   The clearance orders cited in the suit stated that workers were
to average one ton per hour for eight hours a day, according to Jim
Green, a lawyer for the cane-cutters.
   For that work, according to the clearance orders, harvesters
were to be paid at a rate of $5.30 a ton, the attorney said. The
lawsuit claims the workers received $3.50 per ton and $4.25 per ton.
   But Charles Caulkins, an attorney for the growers, said the six
companies contend the clearance order calls for payment per hour,
not per ton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Hasbro-AnimalTesting     09-27 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hasbro-Animal Testing,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro To Stop Using Animals To Test Cosmetics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hasbro Inc. said it will no longer use
white rats, rabbits and other animals to test children's cosmetics
for safety.
   The decision follows similar announcements by adult cosmetic
manufacturers. Animal-rights activists have staged two
demonstrations at Hasbro's plant here in the past two years and
urged consumers to boycott Hasbro cosmetics.
   ``We certainly applaud Hasbro's decision,'' said Steven Ruggeri,
New England director of Friends of Animals. ``I think it's the most
enlightened approach.''
   Hasbro spokesman Wayne Charness said Tuesday the company has
used animals to test 15 products in the past six years. He did not
identify the products, but said the tests verified they were safe
if swallowed and did not irritate eyes or skin.
   ``We've always been sensitive to both sides of the issue and
always made a policy of avoiding tests on animals whenever
possible,'' he said. ``Because there was such a limited amount of
products (requiring animal testing), we decided to eliminate it.''
   Charness declined to say whether the protests influenced
Hasbro's decision.
   Animal-rights activists have said tests to determine whether the
products are safe for eyes caused the rabbits unnecessary pain
because their eyes do not produce tears to wash the substances away.
   Avon Products Inc. and Revlon Inc., two of the biggest
manufacturers of adult cosmetics, recently announced they would
replace animal tests of new toiletries with computer models,
existing safety records and human volunteers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
