<FIRST>u f AM-Columbia-Analysis     09-27 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Columbia-Analysis,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Acquisition of Columbia Prompted by Expanding Global Marketplace</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Columbia-Sony Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment isn't top dog
in Hollywood these days. But in the global marketplace, the studio
has enormous potential, which is why Sony snapped up Columbia on
Wednesday for $3.4 billion.
   The buyout will yield a fully-integrated company combining two
prominent players in entertainment hardware and software, giving
Sony a repository of films and television programs to show the
world over _ preferably on Sony equipment.
   Sony now can control an entertainment property from start to
finish _ owning the movie, the movie theater, the snack bar, the
soundtrack album, the television series adaptation and the VCR and
stereo system on which the movie and album can be played.
   While not in the same league as the $14 billion Time-Warner
merger earlier this year _ which created the world's biggest media
concern _ the Sony-Columbia pact does share the same motivation:
survival in the booming international entertainment emporium.
   Sony's new multinational enterprise is the result of a yearlong
effort by the Japanese electronics giant to establish a Hollywood
foothold. It marise in credit-market interest rates.
   It also was weighed down by International Business Machines
Corp.'s disclosure that it expects earnings for the third quarter
to come in well below current estimates by analysts.
   IBM shares fell 5~ to 111|, and some other technology issues
also were weak. Unisys was off } at 18~, Digital Equipment dropped
1] to 93|, and Apple Computer lost { to 44} in the over-the-counter
market.
   But brokers said buyers were encouraged by takeover news and
rumors, notably in the entertainment industry, that seemed to ease
recent fears that Wall Street's boom in buyouts and mergers might
be nearing an end.
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment, which agreed to be acquired by
Sony Corp. for $27 a share, rose \ to 26{ in heavy trading.
   Paramount Communications, another prominent factor in the
entertainment business, gained 1[ to 57].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.14 to 191.31. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 0.17 at 382.36.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 153.53 million shares at 3 p.m.
on Wall Street.
</TEXT>
