<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BuildingContracts     09-27 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Building Contracts,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Contracts Fall in August</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A slowdown in public works projects helped push
the level of new construction contracts down 3 percent in August, a
survey found.
   The latest setback followed a brief period of stability
nationwide for new construction of all types, according to the F.W.
Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co., which
conducted the survey.
   The survey found that overall construction last month declined
to $252 billion after a 2 percent rise to $256.6 billion in July.
   Contracts for public works projects fell 10 percent to an annual
rate of $42.4 billion, the lowest value in six months, reflecting
``budgetary restraint on the funding for construction of highways,
bridges and other infrastructure work,'' the survey said.
   August contracts for new residential construction were
relatively unchanged from July at $118.6 billion. A decline in
multi-family construction was offset by a gain in hotel contracts.
One-family home contracts remained steady.
   ``Starts of one-family units haven't changed significantly since
April, despite the decline in mortgage rates since that time,''
said George A. Christie, economist for F.W. Dodge.
   Non-residential building slipped 2 percent in August to an
annual rate of $91 billion.
   For the first eight months of the year, the unadjusted figure
for all newly started construction totaled $175.8 billion, down 1
percent from the same period in 1988.
   Only the North Central region showed an increase _ 3 percent _
in building contracts over the first eight months of last year. The
northeastern and western sections of the country were unchanged
from last year and the South was down 4 percent.
</TEXT>
