<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CoorsBrands     09-27 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coors Brands,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors May Find Itself With Nearly Two Dozen Beer Brands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co. may have to juggle nearly
two dozen brands of beer until it decides which ones will fail if
its proposed purchase of Stroh Brewing Co. is finalized, analysts
say.
   The Golden-based brewer has offered $425 million for most of the
Detroit-based Stroh's assets. The proposal is subject to the
approval of the boards of directors of both companies and the
Justice Department.
   Officials have said they don't expect it to be finalized before
early next year.
   Coors' best known brands _ Coors, Coors Light and Coors Extra
Gold _ are ranked as premium, one notch below the top quality of
super premium.
   Its other brands include Herman Joseph's, Herman Joseph's Light
and Killian's Irish Red, in the premium category; and Keystone and
Keystone Light in the popular category.
   Stroh's most popular brands are Stroh's and Stroh's Light, in
the popular price category, and Old Milwaukee and Old Milwaukee
Light in the low-priced economy category.
   Its other brands include: Signature, super premium; Schlitz and
Schlitz Light, popular; Schaefer, Schaefer Light and Piels,
economy; and Schlitz Malt Liquor, Red Bull and Silver Thunder, malt
liquors.
   Benj Steinman, an associate publisher of the Beer Marketer's
Insights newsletter, said it only would be speculation at this
point to predict which brands would be eliminated.
   The number of brands will pose problems, but ``some of them
could be attractive to other brewers at the right price,'' he said.
   Some of the brands that would be competing against each other
are Coors' new Keystone brand and Stroh's Old Milwaukee.
   Some analysts said the brands most likely to succeed in the
newly merged company would be Coors, Coors Light, Schlitz Malt
Liquor and Old Milwaukee, which is the seventh best-selling beer in
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
