<FIRST>r f BC-Tyson-WhiteLily     09-27 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tyson-White Lily,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Sells Knoxville Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc. has found a buyer for
White Lily Foods Co. as part of its plan to sell off assets of
recently acquired Holly Farms Corp.
   Terms of the sale to ADM Milling Inc., which is subject to
approval by the Federal Trade Commission, were not disclosed by
company officials Wednesday.
   Knoxville-based White Lilly, a 107-year-old company with 150
employees that markets its flour and cornmeal products throughout
the Southeast, was a subsidiary of Memphis-based Holly Farms.
   Tyson Foods, of Springdale, Ark., purchased Holly Farms in July
for $1.29 billion, and soon after said it would need to raise $300
million through asset sales to ease more than $1 billion in debt.
   White Lily, along with two other Tyson flour milling companies _
Dixie Portland Flour Mill Inc. and Dixie Portland of Georgia _ have
agreed to sell their operating assets and related liabilities to
ADM Milling.
   ADM Milling is a subsidiary of Archer Daniels Midland Co. It is
the second-largest flour milling company in the United States,
behind ConAgra Inc., with 30 plants across the country.
</TEXT>
