<DOCNO> AP890927-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-StoresForSale Bjt   09-27 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stores For Sale, Bjt,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stores Galore on the Block</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stores-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With several big-name department stores seeking new owners, the
U.S. retail industry may be looking at a $4 billion clearance sale.
   In an industry already reeling from the effects of financial
difficulties facing one major store operator, some of the nation's
most famous department store chains are on the block in sales that
analysts estimate could reap more than $4 billion.
   Two respected chains catering to affluent customers, Saks and
Marshall Field's, became the latest to go on sale as their parent
company, BAT Industries PLC, launched a major realignment of
operations.
   By undoing some of its diversity, the British conglomerate hopes
to thwart a $22 billion takeover charge led by financier Sir James
Goldsmith.
   BAT will sell its American retail holdings but keep its
lucrative tobacco and financial services businesses in a plan to
boost its worth to shareholders and keep them loyal to current
management.
   Arthur Martinez, senior vice president in charge of retail
operations at BATUS Inc., BAT's American arm, expressed optimism
about the intention to sell the retailing businesses, which was
announced Tuesday.
   ``We have working for us the lack of a distress sale environment
and some splendid properties,'' he said in an interview. ``I'm very
confident of our ability to get a satisfactory price.''
   The BAT-owned retailers joined trend-setting Bloomingdale's on
the auction block. Bloomingdale's has been on the market for
several weeks due to the problems of its debt-encumbered owner,
Campeau Corp.
   The Canadian holding company might be forced to part with other
pieces of its vast retail collection, depending on orders from its
financial rescuer, Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd.
   If high fashion isn't to everyone's tastes, May Department
Stores Co. wants to sell its Caldor and Venture discount chains.
   And if this isn't a big enough selection, U.S. stores belonging
to Australia's troubled Hooker Corp., including the B. Altman &amp; Co.
and Bonwit Teller chains, may be in the market for new owners.
Hooker's U.S. subsididary, L.J. Hooker Corp., is restructuring
after filing for bankruptcy court protection from creditors.
   ``There's an awful lot of retail property on the block right
now. It may make some available at very attractive terms _ and I
don't mean junk debt,'' said analyst Janet Mangano of Josephthal &amp;
Co. Inc.
   Bidders with the wherewithal to make a mostly cash offer could
be in the driver's seat if they're steering toward a retail
acquisition, said Mangano.
   But the glut means a desperate seller like Campeau probably
can't count on getting as much money as desired.
   Gilbert Harrison, chairman of Financo Inc., a merger advisory
firm specializing in retail industry transactions, said Saks and
Bloomingdale's are world-class businesses that will lure many
potential buyers from the United States and abroad.
   Two possible bidders have revealed their intentions toward
Bloomingdale's: the chain's chairman, Marvin S. Traub, and Crown
American Corp., a big U.S. shopping mall developer.
   As many as 10 other individuals or groups reportedly are
considering whether to pursue the New York-based, 17-store chain.
   Non-retail groups might be reluctant to bid for the stores in
light of the predicaments of Campeau and Hooker, which both were
more sure-footed in real estate when they ventured into U.S.
retailing.
   For one thing, non-retailers are unaccustomed to the amount of
credit management that's involved in buying merchandise that might
sell out quickly or linger on shelves if fickle consumers change
their buying habits.
   ``I am distressed to see how many retail properties are for sale
at the same time,'' said Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. analyst Walter Loeb.
He said heavy debt loads have put unbearable pressure on retailers
and led many of them into trouble.
   On top of the $1 billion or so analysts expect Bloomingdale's
might sell for, there's the roughly $1.5 billion that Caldor and
Venture should fetch.
   St. Louis-based May, which itself is mentioned as a possible
pursuer of Saks or Bloomingdale's, has about 120 Caldor stores and
about 73 Venture outlets. May owns the Lord &amp; Taylor chain.
   BAT's retail businesses would go for at least $2 billion,
analysts said. New York-based Saks has 46 stores from coast to
coast, and Chicago-based Marshall Field's operates about two dozen
stores in Illinois, Ohio, Texas and Wisconsin.
   Field's chairman, Philip B. Miller, is considering a
management-led buyout of the chain but he has not disclosed what
price might be offered.
   Among BAT's other U.S. retail businesses are Ivey's, a
Charlotte, N.C.-based chain of 20-plus stores, and Breuners of San
Ramon, Calif., which has nearly four dozen furniture stores and
rental outlets.
</TEXT>
