<FIRST>u f AM-C&amp;S-Sovran 1stLd-Writethru f0212 09-27 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-C&amp;S-Sovran, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0212,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>C&amp;S-Sovran Combination Creates Banking Powerhouse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New 8th graf, Wall Street ..., to UPDATE with closing
stock prices. Picks up 8th graf pvs, The merger ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens &amp; Southern Corp. of Atlanta said
Wednesday its merger with Virginia-based Sovran Financial Corp.
creating the nation's 14th-largest banking company was not a
reaction to an earlier hostile bid by NCNB Corp.
   ``This is not a reactionary thing. ... We started conversations
(with Sovran) two years ago,'' Bennett A. Brown, C&amp;S chairman and
designated chief executive officer of the new combined company,
told a meeting of securities analysts in New York.
   He said those negotiations weren't revealed at the time of
NCNB's stock-swap offer last April because the bid, valued at
around $44 a share, or $2.4 billion, was too pricey.
   Citizens' had claimed the value of NCNB's stock was inflated
after its takeover of the banks of the First RepublicBank Corp of
Dallas last year.
   ``Sovran didn't have the capacity to be a `white knight,'''
Brown said. ``We were never considering an acquisition of each
other ... only a merger of equals.''
   The C&amp;S-Sovran agreement, announced Tuesday, would give Sovran
control of 53 percent of the combined bank holding company _ to be
known as Avantor Financial Corp. _ and C&amp;S a 47 percent stake.
   Under the deal, Sovran shareholders would receive 1.23 shares of
Avantor for each of their 59.8 milliion common shares outstanding.
Citizen shareholders would get one share for each of their 62
million outstanding shares. The agreement is conditioned upon
approval from shareholders and bank regulators.
   Wall Street gave the deal a luke-warm reception Wednesday. In
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, C&amp;S closed down
25 cents to $34.62{ while Sovran fell 75 cents to $41.37{.
   The merger creates the nation's 14th-largest bank holding
company with $47 billion in assets, $34 billion in deposits and 976
branches in eight states in the Southeast.
   Besides creating a regional powerhouse, the deal also represents
the second-largest bank merger in the United States, behind the
combination of Bank of New York Co. and the Irving Bank Corp.
earlier this year.
   Brown said C&amp;S' board of directors saw greater long-term value
in the deal with Sovran than in the ``short profit'' shareholders
would have received from NCNB.
   ``The mutual attractions are largely due to the cultural
similarities,'' Brown said.
   He noted the combined banking company will have double market
power but little overlapping operations in Maryland, Virginia,
Kentucky, Tennessee, South Carolina, Georgia, Florida and
Wshington, D.C.
   Brown said Avantor had more growth potential on the consumer
level than most larger money-center banks because it wasn't bogged
down by problem loans to less developed countries. Only $50 million
of Avantor's $31 billion total loan portfolio includes Third World
debt, he said.
   ``I believe we're well armed to address the future challenges of
the 1990s,'' added Hugh M. Chapman, C&amp;S president and chief
operating officer.
   Sovran Chairman Albert B. Gornto will serve as chairman of the
executive committee of Avantor.
   During Wednesday's meeting, at least one analyst speculated NCNB
might want to re-enter the picture since its previous offer would
now be worth about $54 a share, much higher than the approximately
$34 of stock C&amp;S shareholders will get under the Sovran merger.
   But Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB, which withdrew the previous
offer after C&amp;S refused to even discuss the deal, dismissed such
speculation.
   In a brief statement Wednesday, it said it would continue its
strategy of acquiring thrifts in Texas and the Southeast.
</TEXT>
