<FIRST>u f AM-IBMForecast 1stLd-Writethru   09-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Forecast, 1st Ld-Writethru,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Expects Earnings Below Analysts' Forecasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing stock price and overall
market performance; picks up 4th graf, Besides its ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.'s stock
sank Wednesday, putting a drag on the broader market, after the
company said it expected earnings for the quarter to be below
analysts' forecasts.
   The stock dropped at the opening bell and ended up down $6 a
share to $111.50 on heavy volume of more than 5 million shares.
   IBM is the most valuable company in the United States as
measured by its market value and is a component of the Dow Jones
industrial average of 30 stocks. The average managed a gain of 9.12
points to 2,673.06, but it would have risen more without IBM's drop.
   Besides its quarterly troubles, IBM said that if the effects of
the stronger dollar and the shift to leasing by IBM customers
continues for the rest of 1989, ``it will also be difficult for IBM
to achieve full-year results within the current range of
estimates.''
   The rise of the dollar hurts reported earnings of multinationals
such as IBM by cutting the dollar value of profits that are made in
foreign currencies. The shift to leasing from buying cuts into
short-term revenue by spreading out payments received from placing
new products with customers.
   In addition, IBM said profits were being hurt in the
July-September quarter by the transition to a new range of
products, which increases costs and temporarily depresses revenue
by interrupting sales of the older lines.
   IBM Chairman John F. Akers said demand for IBM products and
services continues to be good worldwide. He said the company
expects growth in all major geographic areas for the year, with the
rate of growth continuing to be stronger outside the United States.
   IBM had been expected to earn about $2.22 a share in the current
quarter, according to a survey of 23 security analysts by the
Institutional Brokers Estimate System of Lynch, Jones &amp; Ryan. The
range of estimates was $2.14 to $2.28.
   Frank Metz, IBM's chief financial officer, told an analyst that
net earnings in the current quarter would be measurably below the
$1.95 a share in operating earnings the company had a year ago,
spokesman Peter Thonis confirmed.
   For the full year, the average estimate of 42 analysts had been
$10.36 a share and the range was $10 to $10.80, the estimate
service said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
