<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-27 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures seesawed in hectic trading
Wednesday before closing higher after OPEC announced it had agreed
to raise its official production limit by 1 million barrels a day.
   Observers said that while the agreement legitimizes part of what
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is already
producing, it still undershoots the cartel's actual production,
believed to be above 22.5 million barrels a day.
   The new accord raises the official ceiling to 20.5 million
barrels a day in the fourth quarter from 19.5 million in the third
period.
   ``They're getting closer to institutionalizing what they're
already doing,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of the
energy group at Elders Futures Inc. ``So it didn't solve any
questions.''
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, closed 6
cents higher at $19.59 a barrel after trading as much as 30 cents
under Tuesday's close of $19.53.
   Among refined products, heating oil for October delivery rose
0.75 cent to finish at 58.46 cents a gallon and November added 0.84
cent to 58.90 cents.
   Unleaded gasoline for delivery in October dipped 1.64 cents to
58.74 cents a gallon.
   It was the third straight decline in as many days after a sharp
increase last week on news that a big refinery in the Virgin
Islands had sustained severe hurricane damage and would be closed
for 60 days. The refinery, owned by Amerada Hess Corp., supplies
markets in the eastern United States.
   ``The market is saying that it overreacted to the Hess refinery
damage,'' said Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc.
   Baker, as well as other market analysts, predicted that crude
prices in coming weeks would ``fluctuate along with the temperature
in OPEC'' in advance of the regularly scheduled meeting in November
of the oil group. But no sharp fluctuations are anticipated, they
said.
   Observers have already predicted that OPEC would make yet
another change in its production ceiling at the next meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
