<FIRST>r f BC-AmwaySales     09-27 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Amway Sales,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway: Hirohito Death Slowed Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADA, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Emperor Hirohito's illness and death
cut into Amway Corp.'s sales growth for the fiscal year that ended
Aug. 31, company officials said.
   Amway said growth in sales of its laundry and bath soaps and
more than 4,000 other home and personal care products dipped to 7
percent for the fiscal year from a 20 percent increase last year.
   Commerce in Japan, which accounts for 35 percent of Amway's
business, slumped during Hirohito's illness, William Nicholson,
Amway's chief operating officer, said Tuesday.
   ``All activity in Japan came to a stop because of that,'' he
said.
   Amway-Japan shut down completely during the three-day mourning
period following Hirohito's death Jan. 7.
   Without that impact, Nicholson estimated sales growth would have
been 12 percent. He said Amway's Japanese sales, which amount to
more than $500 million annually for the direct-sales giant, started
growing again early this year.
   Amway estimated retail sales by its more than one million
independent distributors at $1.9 billion worldwide for the fiscal
year, up from $1.8 billion in the previous fiscal year. The
privately held company does not report earnings.
   Nicholson said Amway's U.S. market, which accounts for 40
percent of sales, saw the largest increase in revenue and new
distributors.
   A failed attempt to take over Avon Products Inc., Amway's
largest rival, apparently helped sales in the United States last
spring. Nicholson had no explanation.
</TEXT>
