<FIRST>u f AM-FDRoberts     09-27 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FD Roberts,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Former F.D. Roberts Employees Plead Guilty to Stock Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former presidents of a defunct
penny-stock brokerage firm _ including a former federal securities
examiner _ were among five men who pleaded guilty Wednesday to
violating federal securities laws and bilking about $68 million
from investors.
   Sheldon Kanoff, 53, of Flushing, N.Y., a former president of
Paramus-based F.D. Roberts Securities Inc., confessed guilt before
U.S. District Judge Nicholas H. Politan to two counts of securities
fraud and one count of conspiracy to commit securities fraud and
defraud the U.S. government.
   Kanoff became the 11th F.D. Roberts employee to plead guilty to
illegal practices in the penny-stock field. He had worked as a
chief examiner for broker-dealer inspection for the Securities and
Exchange Commission's New York office from 1970 to 1983, heading
investigations of securities fraud.
   Former F.D. Roberts president, treasurer and partner Albert
Weiss, 44, of Ramsey, pleaded guilty to one count of securities
fraud and one count of conspiracy to commit securities fraud. He
also admitted filing a false tax return in 1987.
   Both men admitted that from March 1985 to February 1989, F.D.
Roberts hired brokers with little or no experience and trained them
to badger customers into buying securities at inflated prices.
   Kanoff, a member of the firm's board who shared in its profits,
also told the judge that F.D. Roberts funds were used to pay
organized crime figures who had undisclosed interests in the firm.
   ``There was money owed to organized crime figures and money to
be paid to organized crime figures,'' said First Assistant U.S.
Attorney Michael Chertoff.
   Kanoff faces 15 years in prison and fines of up to $750,000.
Weiss faces a 13-year prison term and fines of up to $750,000.
Sentencing was set for November 14.
   Kanoff, Weiss and the three others who entered guilty pleas told
the judge that F.D. Roberts brokers used deceptive and manipulative
sales techniques to persuade customers to buy stocks the firm
usually controlled, and that false records were maintained.
   They also said some of those involved in fraudulent activity
would would maintain nominee accounts and profit by as much as 400
percent in one day.
   Earlier Wednesday, three former brokers _ John Landrum, 31, and
Kevin Zacharawicz, 35, both of Boca Raton, Fla.; and Fred Schneider
of Sparta _ pleaded guilty to stock fraud.
   Each faces a five-year jail term and a $250,000 fine.
   F.D. Roberts' had branch offices in New York, Florida and
California.
   Penny stocks are low-priced securities that are not listed on
any exchange.
   The firm, which has been under investigation by state and
federal authorities for about 1{-years, voluntarily closed in
February after the National Association of Securities Dealers
informed it that it fell below the minimum capital requirements.
   F.D. Roberts' former national sales manager, a former branch
manager, two assistant branch managers and two other brokers
already have pleaded guilty to using similar fraudulent practices
on clients.
   Four of the firm's top executives, including Kanoff, have been
banned by the NASD from working in the securities industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
