<FIRST>r f BC-HenleyRestructuring     09-27 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Henley Restructuring,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Henley Group To Split in December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., a conglomerate based in
Hampton and California with more than $4 billion in assets, will
split into two companies in December, the company announced
Wednesday.
   The move will continue Henley's program of creating new publicly
held companies ``to help enhance the value of its assets,'' the
company said in a statement.
   The two companies will be Henley Properties Inc., specializing
in real estate, and a new Henley Group Inc.
   Existing Henley stockholders will get one share of the new
Henley Group, an industrial company, as a tax-free distribution in
December for each share they hold in the existing company; what's
left will be renamed Henley Properties.
   The company said it filed a registration statement for the
distribution with the Securities and Exchange Commission on
Wednesday.
   Henley Properties, with assets of more than $600 million, will
own the existing company's real estate developments and acreage in
Southern California, Hawaii, Wisconsin, Michigan and New Hampshire.
Michael Dingman, chairman and chief executive of the conglomerate,
will hold both titles in the new company as well.
   The new Henley Group Inc. will own the existing company's
remaining assets of about $3.5 billion. Included are two wholly
owned subsidiaries: Fisher Scientific Group Inc., which makes and
distributes laboratory and medical products; and Pneumo Abex Corp.,
which makes equipment for aircraft and friction-braking products
for cars, trucks and other vehicles.
   Cape Horn Methanol Ltd., now mostly owned by Henley, also will
be part of the new company. Cape Horn Methanol makes methanol from
natural gas in Chile.
   Henley Properties will include the existing company's wholly
owned subsidiary Signal Landmark Holdings Inc., which the company
described as a major developer of residential commercial and
industrial real estate, mainly in Southern California and Hawaii.
Henley said Signal Landmark also owns more than 300,000 acres of
recreational and residential real estate in northern Michigan and
Wisconsin.
   The company said Henley Properties also will own the existing
company's half-interest in Wentworth by the Sea, an oceanfront
project in New Castle consisting of a planned hotel at the site of
an old resort hotel, a 200-slip marina, a golf course and
restaurants and homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
