<DOCNO> AP890927-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 2206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Sun-NewFuels     09-27 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sun-New Fuels,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sun Oil To Test New Fuels to Lower Emissions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Co. on Wednesday announced it will begin
testing a series of reformulated fuels and gasolines in hopes of
lowering harmful emissions by 1993.
   The new fuels will include a reformulated diesel, a methanol mix
and unleaded gasolines.
   The first phase of the program will begin Nov. 1, when the
company plans to market the new diesel fuel at selected
Philadelphia-area service stations.
   The fuel is designed to meet stricter Environmental Protection
Agency standards scheduled to take effect in 1993. The fuel will
meet the proposed standard of 0.5 percent sulfur by weight, the
company said, and will maintain a cetane rating of 45. Cetane is
the diesel equivalent of a gasoline's octane rating.
   In January, the Armellini Trucking Co. will use the fuel on its
Florida-to-New England runs. Testing will compare tailpipe
emissions from the eight test trucks against emissions from four
trucks not using the reformulated fuel. The company said it expects
to see reductions in sulfur emissions of up to 80 percent.
   Sun plans three tests for its methanol mix, which will contain
15 percent gasoline. Sun does not manufacture methanol, but will
blend the mixture, known as M-85, using methonal purchased from
other producers.
   M-85 will be sold at selected Sunoco service stations in Detroit
and Washington, D.C., starting in early 1990, but will be sold only
to cars taking part in the experiment.
   Ford Motor Co. is cooperating with the study by providing
``flexible fuel'' cars that can run on either gasoline or a mixture
of methanol and gasoline up to 85 percent methonal, Sun said.
   Proponents of methanol claim substantial reductions in
hydrocarbon emissions, Sun said, but the company also plans to
examine the emission of formaldehyde, a gas that is an irritant.
   The third phase of the program involves new unleaded gasolines.
Sun currently markets gasoline under the Sunoco brand in 28 states
east of the Rockies as well as under the Atlantic brand in New York
and Pennsylvania.
   Several reformulated gasolines will be tested starting Dec. 1.
The reformulated gasolines will vary in composition, but all will
have reduced amounts of aromatics and olefins and increased amounts
of oxygen compounds, the company said.
   The tests will involve a variety of post-1975 cars that require
unleaded gasoline. The emissions will be compared with emissions
levels from comparable cars running on existing Sunoco Economy and
Ultra. Automobile performence also will be evaluated.
   The company expects to see reductions in carbon monoxide
emissions of up to 10 percent.
   The company declined to release information on how much the
tests or the new fuel mixes will cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890927-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-89 2129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IMF 2ndLd-Writethru f0280 09-27 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0280,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Polish Official Plead for Western Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 20th graf, `IMF officials ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
loan amount to $1.4 billion sted $1.5 billion. Also moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday urged Western
nations to increase their financial support for Poland, and a top
Polish official appealed for $1.5 billion to help his nation cope
with a period of ``potentially explosive social conditions.''
   In his first address to the annual meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank, Bush praised the efforts of the
Solidarity-led government to handle the economic crisis facing
Poland.
   ``There may be no greater opportunity before us all today than
the challenge of Poland, and more broadly Eastern Europe _ where
countries are in the throes of dramatic political and economic
change,'' Bush told the delegates from 152 nations.
   The United States, Bush said, will be in the forefront of aid
efforts as Eastern Europe's first non-Communist-led government in
four decades struggles with soaring inflation, food shortages and a
huge foreign debt.
   He called on the IMF and the World Bank, the top international
lending agencies, and Western nations individually to boost their
aid for Poland.
   ``In light of clearly growing needs, the recent accession of a
Solidarity-led government and our self-evident stake in its
success, we must do more,'' Bush said.
   However, he immediately told reporters he's not prepared to
increase his $219 million U.S. aid package, saying any increase
will be hinged on the success of the reform measures being drafted
by the Polish government.
   The urgency of the situation was stressed by Polish Finance
Minister Leszek Balcerowicz, who sought immediate assistance during
a round of meetings with finance officials attending the IMF and
World Bank meetings.
   Balcerowicz told reporters he wanted a $1 billion loan from
Western nations by early next year to provide critical reserves
needed to stabilize exchange rates. But Poland also needs up to
$500 million in short-term trade loans sooner to buy essential
foreign goods such as fertilizer and medical drugs, he said.
   ``The reform process, at least in its initial phase, will
proceed in extremely difficult and potentially explosive social
conditions,'' Balcerowicz said, pleading for Western aid to ease
the Poles' hardships.
   He said he wasn't disappointed that Bush didn't offer any
specific figures on how much the United States might boost its aid
proposal, saying he expected the details to be forthcoming.
   The administration is supporting a $119 million package of U.S.
economic aid to Poland and another $100 million in food aid.
Congressional Democrats have termed the package woefully inadequate
and called for more.
   Polish officials have sought $700 million a year over the next
three years from the IMF, and there were indications that the IMF
assistance program could be approved as soon as November.
   In his speech, Bush also stressed the need to keep pushing
forward with his initiative to ease the $1.3 trillion burden of
debt being carried by developing countries in Latin America and
elswhere.
   The IMF and the World Bank have been supporting the effort by
providing incentives to encourage commerical banks to forgive a
portion of their loans to poor nations. But banks have been
reluctant to support the plan because it requires them to partially
forgive old loans, then make new loans.
   Bush made an even more blunt appeal to a group of commercial
bankers at a White House reception Tuesday night, lobbying for the
debt-relief plan put forward by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson told reporters
Wednesday that twisting bankers' arms was a ``very foolish thing to
do.''
   ``Banks have to make their own decisions in light of their own
assessment of their long-term interests,'' he said.
   Later Wednesday, Argentine President Carlos Menem announced that
his country had reached agreement clearing the way for an IMF loan
to his nation, the third largest debtor in the developing world
with $60 billion owed.
   An IMF statement put the loan amount at $1.4 billion.
   Menem, in a speech after a morning meeting with Bush at the
White House, said Argentina was facing ``the most dangerous
economic crisis in our history'' because of hyperinflation, a huge
foreign debt and a stagnating economy.
   ``The government must root out the structural causes of
stagnation,'' he said. ``Individual initiative and competitiveness
within a market framework is the answer.''
</TEXT>
